{"title_page": "Peacekeeper", "text_new": "{{wiktionary|peacekeeper|peacekeepers}}\n'''Peacekeeper''' may refer to:\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==General==\n* A person involved in [[peacekeeping]]\n** [[United Nations peacekeeping]]\n* [[Peace officer]]\n* [[Conservator of the peace]]\n\n== Military ==\n* The [[LGM-118 Peacekeeper]], a land-based nuclear ICBM\n** [[Peacekeeper Rail Garrison]], a mobile missile system for the LGM-118 Peacekeeper\n* [[Cadillac Gage Ranger]] armored fighting vehicles\n** [[Cadillac Gage Peacekeeper II]], one of the two models of the vehicle\n\n== Fiction ==\n* ''[[The Peacekeepers]]'', a 1988 ''Star Trek: The Next Generation'' novel by Gene DeWeese\n* ''[[The Peacekeeper]]'', a 1997 Canadian and American action film\n* [[Peacekeepers (Farscape)|Peacekeepers (''Farscape'')]], a fictional military and law enforcement organization in ''Farscape''\n* [[Peacekeepers (Hunger Games)|Peacekeepers (''The Hunger Games'')]], the combined military and police force in Panem in ''The Hunger Games''\n* ''Peacekeepers'', a science fiction novel written by [[Ben Bova]]\n\n== Video games ==\n* ''[[The Peace Keepers]]'', a 1993 video game for the Super Nintendo Entertainment System\n* [[Peacekeeper Revolver]], a video game gun for the Phillips Cd-i video game console\n\n== Other uses ==\n* [[Peacekeeper (Fleetwood Mac song)|\"Peacekeeper\" (Fleetwood Mac song)]], a 2003 song by Fleetwood Mac from ''Say You Will''\n<!-- * [[Peacekeeper (benchmark)]], a web browser benchmark from [[Futuremark]] Corporation -->\n* [[Peacekeeper Park]], an urban park in Calgary, Alberta, Canada\n* [[Peacekeepers Way]], a highway in Nova Scotia, Canada\n* [[Newfoundland and Labrador Route 2]], also known as Peacekeepers Way, a highway in Newfoundland, Canada\n\n==See also==\n* [[Peacemaker (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "text_old": "{{wiktionary|peacekeeper|peacekeepers}}\n'''Peacekeeper''' may refer to:\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==General==\n* A person involved in [[peacekeeping]]\n** [[United Nations peacekeeping]]\n* [[Peace officer]]\n* [[Conservator of the peace]]\n\n== Military ==\n* The [[LGM-118 Peacekeeper]], a land-based nuclear ICBM\n** [[Peacekeeper Rail Garrison]], a mobile missile system for the LGM-118 Peacekeeper\n* [[Cadillac Gage Ranger]] armored fighting vehicles\n** [[Cadillac Gage Peacekeeper II]], one of the two models of the vehicle\n\n== Fiction ==\n* ''[[The Peacekeepers]]'', a 1988 ''Star Trek: The Next Generation'' novel by Gene DeWeese\n* ''[[The Peacekeeper]]'', a 1997 Canadian and American action film\n* [[Peacekeepers (Farscape)|Peacekeepers (''Farscape'')]], a fictional military and law enforcement organization in ''Farscape''\n* [[Peacekeepers (Hunger Games)|Peacekeepers (''The Hunger Games'')]], the combined military and police force in Panem in ''The Hunger Games''\n* ''Peacekeepers'', a science fiction novel written by [[Ben Bova]]\n\n== Video games ==\n* ''[[The Peace Keepers]]'', a 1993 video game for the Super Nintendo Entertainment System\n* [[Peacekeeper Revolver]], a video game gun for the Phillips Cd-i video game console\n\n== Other uses ==\n* [[Peacekeeper (Fleetwood Mac song)|\"Peacekeeper\" (Fleetwood Mac song)]], a 2003 song by Fleetwood Mac from ''Say You Will''\n<!-- * [[Peacekeeper (benchmark)]], a web browser benchmark from [[Futuremark]] Corporation -->\n* [[Peacekeeper Park]], an urban park in Calgary, Alberta, Canada\n* [[Peacekeepers Way]], a highway in Nova Scotia, Canada\n* [[Newfoundland and Labrador Route 2]], also known as Peacekeepers Way, a highway in Newfondland, Canada\n\n==See also==\n* [[Peacemaker (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "name_user": "Wandererjon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther uses:Correct typo Newfondland to Newfoundland", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peacekeeper"}
{"title_page": "Higgins (dog)", "text_new": "{{Infobox animal\n| name = Higgins\n| image = Higgins the Dog.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| birth_date = December 12, 1957<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1372235/|title=Higgins|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], <br/>[[United States]]\n| death_date = November 11, 1975 (aged 17)\n| death_place = Los Angeles, California, <br/>United States\n| years_active = 1960\u20131974\n| occupation = Actor\n| children = Benjean\n| role = '''Dog''' in ''[[Petticoat Junction]]''<br />\n| awards = [[PATSY Award]] for Best Canine<br/> 1966\n}}\n\n'''Higgins''' (December 12, 1957 - November 11, 1975) was one of the best-known [[dog]] actors of the 1960s and 1970s. Most people remember him as the original dog from ''[[Petticoat Junction]]'', two of the most popular roles he played during a 14-year career in show business.\n\n==Early life==\nIn 1960, animal trainer [[Frank Inn]] found the dog at the [[Burbank, California|Burbank]] Animal Shelter as a puppy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.burbankleader.com/2001-09-08/news/export12814_1_frank-inn-burbank-animal-shelter-ryan-carter|title='Benji' began in Burbank|work=tribunedigital-burbankleader|access-date=2018-04-17|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/08/04/nyregion/frank-inn-who-trained-lassie-and-benji-is-dead-at-86.html|title=Frank Inn, Who Trained Lassie and Benji, Is Dead at 86|last=Martin|first=Douglas|date=2002-08-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> A fluffy black-and-tan [[mixed breed dog]], he was marked like a [[Border Terrier]], and Inn believed him to be a mix of [[Miniature Poodle]], [[Cocker Spaniel]], and [[Schnauzer]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/08/31/archives/benji-a-doghouse-hero.html|title='Benji,' a Doghouse Hero|last=Bender|first=Marylin|date=1975-08-31|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The animals' who's who : 1,146 celebrated animals in history, popular culture, literature, and lore|last=Ruthven.|first=Tremain|date=1982|publisher=Routledge & K. Paul|isbn=9780710094490|location=London|pages=22|oclc=10573542}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHiggins' career was facilitated by [[Frank Inn]], who also trained [[Arnold Ziffel]] (the pig) and all of the other animals used on ''[[The Beverly Hillbillies]]'', ''[[Petticoat Junction]]'', ''[[Green Acres]]'', and ''[[The Waltons]]'' TV series. His on-set assistant trainers included Gerry Warshauer and Karl Miller.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.li/8PfBi|title=Petticoat Junction - Linda Henning w/ Higgins at the Patsy Awards|date=2002-08-07|work=archive.li|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref>\n\nAs an actor, Higgins first came to national attention as the uncredited dog who played the character of \"Dog\" on the television sitcom ''[[Petticoat Junction]]'' for six of the show's seven seasons, from 1964 to 1970, appearing in 149 episodes.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Hooterville handbook : a viewer's guide to Green acres|last=1966-|first=Cox, Stephen|date=1993|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9780312088118|edition= 1st|location=New York|oclc=27146845}}</ref> He guest-appeared on the television sitcom ''[[Green Acres]]'' with [[Eva Gabor]] in 1965 and also made a guest appearance on the television sitcom ''[[The Beverly Hillbillies]]''. Due to his work in ''[[Petticoat Junction]]'', Higgins received a [[PATSY Award]] in 1966 in the television category<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animalhealthfoundation.net/magazines/ac9-10-1973.pdf|title=1973 PATSY Awards|last=Harris|first=Norene|date=September\u2013October 1973|work=Animal Cavalcade (Official Journal of the Animal Health Foundation)|accessdate=November 26, 2018|issue=5|volume=4|pages=24\u201325}} Additional , December 15, 2015.</ref>, and he was cover-featured on an issue of [[TV Guide]] magazine{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}.\n\nHiggins was able to convey a broad range of emotions through his facial expressions. Inn, who trained thousands of animals of many species during his lifetime, told reporters that Higgins was the smartest dog he had ever worked with and noted that during his prime years in television, he learned one new trick or routine per week and retained these routines from year to year, making it possible for him to take on increasingly varied and complex roles. Higgins's tricks included yawning and sneezing on cue.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Animal stars : behind the scenes with your favorite animal actors|last=Robin|first=Ganzert|publisher=|others=Anderson, Allen, 1954-, Anderson, Linda C., 1946-|isbn=9781608682645|location=Notavo, California|pages=220|oclc=869266470|date = 2014-08-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/1001reasonstolov0000miel|title=1,001 reasons to love dogs|last=Christine.|first=Miele|date=2006|publisher=Stewart Tabori & Chang|others=Tiegreen, Mary.|isbn=9781584795261|location=New York|oclc=65400365}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, Higgins starred in the film ''[[Mooch Goes to Hollywood]]'' with [[Zsa Zsa Gabor]] and [[Vincent Price]]. He came out of retirement at an estimated age of 16<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/animalstarsbehin0000ganz/page/219|title=Animal stars : behind the scenes with your favorite animal actors|last=Robin|first=Ganzert|publisher=|others=Anderson, Allen, 1954-, Anderson, Linda C., 1946-|isbn=9781608682638|location=Notavo, California|pages=[https://archive.org/details/animalstarsbehin0000ganz/page/219 219\u2013220]|oclc=869266470|date=2014-09-15}}</ref> to star in the 1974 feature film ''[[Benji (1974 film)|Benji]]'', which became his greatest commercial success.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1iwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA142 |title=Upwardly Mogul [November 1976]|last=Greene|first=A. C.|date=2002-04-30|work=Texas Monthly|access-date=2018-04-17|archive-url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/upwardly-mogul-november-1976/|archive-date=1976-11-01|url-status=|pages=142\u2013145|language=en-US}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Personal life==\n===Friends===\nHiggins had a close rapport with the actor [[Edgar Buchanan]], who played Uncle Joe Carson on ''Petticoat Junction.'' In the official cast pictures taken each year during the run of ''Petticoat Junction,'' Buchanan is shown holding or petting Higgins.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730111412/http://petticoat.topcities.com:80/season2.htm|title=Petticoat Junction - Cast Photo - Season Two|date=2012-07-30|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730111537/http://petticoat.topcities.com:80/season3.htm|title=Petticoat Junction - Cast Photo - Season Three|date=2012-07-30|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730111537/http://petticoat.topcities.com:80/season5.htm|title=Petticoat Junction - Cast Photo - Season Five|date=2012-07-30|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref> Buchanan guest-starred on 17 episodes of the sitcom ''Green Acres'', and Higgins guest-starred in two of those appearances. Buchanan and Higgins crossed paths for the last time in ''Benji'', which was coincidentally also the last film in which both actors starred. The two actors had an obvious fondness for one another, which is especially clear in ''Benji,'' because the movie's naturalistic pacing allowed them to interact as friends rather than requiring that Higgins perform a specific trick to which Buchanan would react.\n\nFrank Inn and Higgins were very close in real life as well as on the job. Inn wrote a poem about the dog called ''My Little Brown Dog''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://petticoat.topcities.com/frankinn.htm#my%20little%20brown%20dog|archive-url=https://archive.is/20050308174105/http://petticoat.topcities.com/frankinn.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2005-03-08|title=Petticoat Junction - Frank Inn (Freeman)|work=topcities.com}}</ref>\n\n===Family===\nHiggins' progeny carried on his work in a continuing series of movies and television series featuring the [[Benji|Benji character]], beginning with ''[[For the Love of Benji]]'' in 1977, in which Higgins' daughter Benjean inherited the role of Benji after Higgins' death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.benji.com/FAQ.htm|title=Benji superstar acting dog FAQ's|work=benji.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Benjean]], who was also trained by Frank Inn, starred in more ''Benji'' movies than Higgins did because she was younger when she first took on the role. Benjean can be differentiated from Higgins by the fact that she was a female with no visible genitalia, and she had a large patch of white hairs on her muzzle around her nose, whereas Higgins was mostly black around his nose. In addition, Higgins\u2019 bark was a deep, froggy sound, while Benjean had a higher-pitched, more traditional-sounding yelp. This is readily apparent when comparing ''Benji'' and ''For the Love of Benji''.\n\nConfusion between the two dogs was increased when VHS and DVD videos of the original ''Benji'' movie were released with pictures of Benjean on the cover.\n\nAlso, the dog \"Tramp\" from the TV series ''[[My Three Sons]]'' was one of Higgins' puppies; his real-life name was \"Mac\".\n\n==Death==\nHiggins died at age 17, just four weeks short of his 18th birthday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dogs-in-history.blogspot.com.br/2017/07/higgins-from-shelter-dog-to-beloved.html|title=Famous Dogs in History: Higgins: From Shelter Dog to Beloved Benji|last=Diana|date=2017-07-30|website=Famous Dogs in History|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref> Inn had the dog's body cremated and saved the ashes in an urn on his mantelpiece. He then wrote a Christian poem in memory of Higgins called ''My Gift to Jesus''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://petticoat.topcities.com/frankinn.htm#my%20gift%20to%20jesus|archive-url=https://archive.is/20050308174105/http://petticoat.topcities.com/frankinn.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2005-03-08|title=Petticoat Junction - Frank Inn (Freeman)|work=topcities.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Chiens Celebres, R\u00e9els et Fictifs, dans l'Art, la Culture et l'Histoire.|last=de Lavigne|first=Guillaume|date=2015|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=9781326035655|location=[S.l.]|pages=381|oclc=982604562}}</ref> Inn died in 2002 and requested that Higgins' ashes be buried in his coffin with him.<ref name=\":0\" /> This request was not fulfilled due to legal reasons,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/07/27/155949615/the-trainer-who-created-four-legged-stars|title=The Trainer Who Created Four-Legged Stars|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-04-17|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Animal stars : behind the scenes with your favorite animal actors|last=Robin|first=Ganzert|publisher=|others=Anderson, Allen, 1954-, Anderson, Linda C., 1946-|isbn=9781608682645|location=Notavo, California|pages=222|oclc=869266470|date = 2014-08-19}}</ref> and Higgins' ashes remain with Inn's daughters. Inn is buried at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Resting places : the burial sites of more than 14,000 famous persons|last=1953-|first=Wilson, Scott|others=Mank, Gregory W.|isbn=9780786479924|edition= Third |location=Jefferson, North Carolina|oclc=948561021|date = 2016-08-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Benji}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Higgins}}\n[[Category:1957 animal births]]\n[[Category:1975 animal deaths]]\n[[Category:Benji]]\n[[Category:Dog actors]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox animal\n| name = Higgins\n| image = Higgins the Dog.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| birth_date = December 12, 1957<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1372235/|title=Higgins|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], <br/>[[United States]]\n| death_date = November 11, 1975 (aged 17)\n| death_place = Los Angeles, California, <br/>United States\n| years_active = 1960\u20131974\n| occupation = Actor\n| children = Benjean\n| role = '''Dog''' in ''[[Petticoat Junction]]''<br />'''Benji''' in ''[[Benji (1974 film)|Benji]]''\n| awards = [[PATSY Award]] for Best Canine<br/> 1966\n}}\n\n'''Higgins''' (December 12, 1957 - November 11, 1975) was one of the best-known [[dog]] actors of the 1960s and 1970s. Most people remember him as the original [[Benji (1974 film)|Benji]] or as the uncredited dog from ''[[Petticoat Junction]]'', two of the most popular roles he played during a 14-year career in show business.\n\n==Early life==\nIn 1960, animal trainer [[Frank Inn]] found the dog at the [[Burbank, California|Burbank]] Animal Shelter as a puppy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.burbankleader.com/2001-09-08/news/export12814_1_frank-inn-burbank-animal-shelter-ryan-carter|title='Benji' began in Burbank|work=tribunedigital-burbankleader|access-date=2018-04-17|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/08/04/nyregion/frank-inn-who-trained-lassie-and-benji-is-dead-at-86.html|title=Frank Inn, Who Trained Lassie and Benji, Is Dead at 86|last=Martin|first=Douglas|date=2002-08-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> A fluffy black-and-tan [[mixed breed dog]], he was marked like a [[Border Terrier]], and Inn believed him to be a mix of [[Miniature Poodle]], [[Cocker Spaniel]], and [[Schnauzer]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/08/31/archives/benji-a-doghouse-hero.html|title='Benji,' a Doghouse Hero|last=Bender|first=Marylin|date=1975-08-31|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The animals' who's who : 1,146 celebrated animals in history, popular culture, literature, and lore|last=Ruthven.|first=Tremain|date=1982|publisher=Routledge & K. Paul|isbn=9780710094490|location=London|pages=22|oclc=10573542}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHiggins' career was facilitated by [[Frank Inn]], who also trained [[Arnold Ziffel]] (the pig) and all of the other animals used on ''[[The Beverly Hillbillies]]'', ''[[Petticoat Junction]]'', ''[[Green Acres]]'', and ''[[The Waltons]]'' TV series. His on-set assistant trainers included Gerry Warshauer and Karl Miller.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.li/8PfBi|title=Petticoat Junction - Linda Henning w/ Higgins at the Patsy Awards|date=2002-08-07|work=archive.li|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref>\n\nAs an actor, Higgins first came to national attention as the uncredited dog who played the character of \"Dog\" on the television sitcom ''[[Petticoat Junction]]'' for six of the show's seven seasons, from 1964 to 1970, appearing in 149 episodes.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Hooterville handbook : a viewer's guide to Green acres|last=1966-|first=Cox, Stephen|date=1993|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9780312088118|edition= 1st|location=New York|oclc=27146845}}</ref> He guest-appeared on the television sitcom ''[[Green Acres]]'' with [[Eva Gabor]] in 1965 and also made a guest appearance on the television sitcom ''[[The Beverly Hillbillies]]''. Due to his work in ''[[Petticoat Junction]]'', Higgins received a [[PATSY Award]] in 1966 in the television category<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animalhealthfoundation.net/magazines/ac9-10-1973.pdf|title=1973 PATSY Awards|last=Harris|first=Norene|date=September\u2013October 1973|work=Animal Cavalcade (Official Journal of the Animal Health Foundation)|accessdate=November 26, 2018|issue=5|volume=4|pages=24\u201325}} Additional , December 15, 2015.</ref>, and he was cover-featured on an issue of [[TV Guide]] magazine{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}.\n\nHiggins was able to convey a broad range of emotions through his facial expressions. Inn, who trained thousands of animals of many species during his lifetime, told reporters that Higgins was the smartest dog he had ever worked with and noted that during his prime years in television, he learned one new trick or routine per week and retained these routines from year to year, making it possible for him to take on increasingly varied and complex roles. Higgins's tricks included yawning and sneezing on cue.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Animal stars : behind the scenes with your favorite animal actors|last=Robin|first=Ganzert|publisher=|others=Anderson, Allen, 1954-, Anderson, Linda C., 1946-|isbn=9781608682645|location=Notavo, California|pages=220|oclc=869266470|date = 2014-08-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/1001reasonstolov0000miel|title=1,001 reasons to love dogs|last=Christine.|first=Miele|date=2006|publisher=Stewart Tabori & Chang|others=Tiegreen, Mary.|isbn=9781584795261|location=New York|oclc=65400365}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, Higgins starred in the film ''[[Mooch Goes to Hollywood]]'' with [[Zsa Zsa Gabor]] and [[Vincent Price]]. He came out of retirement at an estimated age of 16<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/animalstarsbehin0000ganz/page/219|title=Animal stars : behind the scenes with your favorite animal actors|last=Robin|first=Ganzert|publisher=|others=Anderson, Allen, 1954-, Anderson, Linda C., 1946-|isbn=9781608682638|location=Notavo, California|pages=[https://archive.org/details/animalstarsbehin0000ganz/page/219 219\u2013220]|oclc=869266470|date=2014-09-15}}</ref> to star in the 1974 feature film ''[[Benji (1974 film)|Benji]]'', which became his greatest commercial success.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1iwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA142 |title=Upwardly Mogul [November 1976]|last=Greene|first=A. C.|date=2002-04-30|work=Texas Monthly|access-date=2018-04-17|archive-url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/upwardly-mogul-november-1976/|archive-date=1976-11-01|url-status=|pages=142\u2013145|language=en-US}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Personal life==\n===Friends===\nHiggins had a close rapport with the actor [[Edgar Buchanan]], who played Uncle Joe Carson on ''Petticoat Junction.'' In the official cast pictures taken each year during the run of ''Petticoat Junction,'' Buchanan is shown holding or petting Higgins.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730111412/http://petticoat.topcities.com:80/season2.htm|title=Petticoat Junction - Cast Photo - Season Two|date=2012-07-30|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730111537/http://petticoat.topcities.com:80/season3.htm|title=Petticoat Junction - Cast Photo - Season Three|date=2012-07-30|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730111537/http://petticoat.topcities.com:80/season5.htm|title=Petticoat Junction - Cast Photo - Season Five|date=2012-07-30|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref> Buchanan guest-starred on 17 episodes of the sitcom ''Green Acres'', and Higgins guest-starred in two of those appearances. Buchanan and Higgins crossed paths for the last time in ''Benji'', which was coincidentally also the last film in which both actors starred. The two actors had an obvious fondness for one another, which is especially clear in ''Benji,'' because the movie's naturalistic pacing allowed them to interact as friends rather than requiring that Higgins perform a specific trick to which Buchanan would react.\n\nFrank Inn and Higgins were very close in real life as well as on the job. Inn wrote a poem about the dog called ''My Little Brown Dog''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://petticoat.topcities.com/frankinn.htm#my%20little%20brown%20dog|archive-url=https://archive.is/20050308174105/http://petticoat.topcities.com/frankinn.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2005-03-08|title=Petticoat Junction - Frank Inn (Freeman)|work=topcities.com}}</ref>\n\n===Family===\nHiggins' progeny carried on his work in a continuing series of movies and television series featuring the [[Benji|Benji character]], beginning with ''[[For the Love of Benji]]'' in 1977, in which Higgins' daughter Benjean inherited the role of Benji after Higgins' death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.benji.com/FAQ.htm|title=Benji superstar acting dog FAQ's|work=benji.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Benjean]], who was also trained by Frank Inn, starred in more ''Benji'' movies than Higgins did because she was younger when she first took on the role. Benjean can be differentiated from Higgins by the fact that she was a female with no visible genitalia, and she had a large patch of white hairs on her muzzle around her nose, whereas Higgins was mostly black around his nose. In addition, Higgins\u2019 bark was a deep, froggy sound, while Benjean had a higher-pitched, more traditional-sounding yelp. This is readily apparent when comparing ''Benji'' and ''For the Love of Benji''.\n\nConfusion between the two dogs was increased when VHS and DVD videos of the original ''Benji'' movie were released with pictures of Benjean on the cover.\n\nAlso, the dog \"Tramp\" from the TV series ''[[My Three Sons]]'' was one of Higgins' puppies; his real-life name was \"Mac\".\n\n==Death==\nHiggins died at age 17, just four weeks short of his 18th birthday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dogs-in-history.blogspot.com.br/2017/07/higgins-from-shelter-dog-to-beloved.html|title=Famous Dogs in History: Higgins: From Shelter Dog to Beloved Benji|last=Diana|date=2017-07-30|website=Famous Dogs in History|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref> Inn had the dog's body cremated and saved the ashes in an urn on his mantelpiece. He then wrote a Christian poem in memory of Higgins called ''My Gift to Jesus''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://petticoat.topcities.com/frankinn.htm#my%20gift%20to%20jesus|archive-url=https://archive.is/20050308174105/http://petticoat.topcities.com/frankinn.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2005-03-08|title=Petticoat Junction - Frank Inn (Freeman)|work=topcities.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Chiens Celebres, R\u00e9els et Fictifs, dans l'Art, la Culture et l'Histoire.|last=de Lavigne|first=Guillaume|date=2015|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=9781326035655|location=[S.l.]|pages=381|oclc=982604562}}</ref> Inn died in 2002 and requested that Higgins' ashes be buried in his coffin with him.<ref name=\":0\" /> This request was not fulfilled due to legal reasons,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/07/27/155949615/the-trainer-who-created-four-legged-stars|title=The Trainer Who Created Four-Legged Stars|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-04-17|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Animal stars : behind the scenes with your favorite animal actors|last=Robin|first=Ganzert|publisher=|others=Anderson, Allen, 1954-, Anderson, Linda C., 1946-|isbn=9781608682645|location=Notavo, California|pages=222|oclc=869266470|date = 2014-08-19}}</ref> and Higgins' ashes remain with Inn's daughters. Inn is buried at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Resting places : the burial sites of more than 14,000 famous persons|last=1953-|first=Wilson, Scott|others=Mank, Gregory W.|isbn=9780786479924|edition= Third |location=Jefferson, North Carolina|oclc=948561021|date = 2016-08-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Benji}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Higgins}}\n[[Category:1957 animal births]]\n[[Category:1975 animal deaths]]\n[[Category:Benji]]\n[[Category:Dog actors]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n", "name_user": "2601:704:3:a8d0:dc71:71d:a92a:4df5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Higgins_(dog)"}
{"title_page": "Abdi Farah Shirdon", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Abdi Shirdon<br>{{small|\u0639\u0628\u062f\u064a \u0641\u0627\u0631\u062d \u0634\u0631\u062f\u0648\u0646}}\n| office = 16th [[Prime Minister of Somalia]]\n| image = File:Abdi Farah Shirdon.png\n| president = [[Hassan Sheikh Mohamud]]\n| term_start = 17 October 2012\n| term_end = 21 December 2013\n| predecessor = [[Abdiweli Mohamed Ali]]\n| successor = [[Abdiweli Sheikh Ahmed]]\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1958}}\n| birth_place = [[Dhusamareb]], [[Somalia]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n| alma_mater = [[Somali National University]]\n| spouse = [[Asha Haji Elmi]]\n| website = http://abdifarah.org/\n}}\n'''Abdi Farah Shirdon''' ({{lang-so|Cabdi Faarax Shirdoon}}; {{lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f\u064a \u0641\u0627\u0631\u062d \u0634\u0631\u062f\u0648\u0646}}; born 1958) is a [[Somali people|Somali]] businessman, economist and politician. He served as the [[Prime Minister of Somalia|Prime Minister]] of [[Somalia]] between October 2012 and December 2013. Shirdon is credited with having overseen significant development in social services and the national budget, as well as improving local security.<ref name=\"Gosfmdimap\"/>\n\n==Background==\n===Personal life===\nShirdon was born in 1958 in the town of [[Dhusamareb]], situated in the central [[Galguduud]] region of [[Somalia]].<ref name=\"Nnsppabapnapm\">{{cite news |last=Ibrahim |first=Mohammed |title=New Somalian President Picks a Businessman, a Political Newcomer, as Prime Minister |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/07/world/africa/somalian-president-picks-businessman-abdi-farah-shirdon-saaid-as-prime-minister.html?_r=1 |accessdate=7 October 2012 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=6 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\">{{cite news |title=Somalis welcome new prime minister but see difficult road ahead |url=http://sabahionline.com/en_GB/articles/hoa/articles/features/2012/10/08/feature-01 |accessdate=9 October 2012 |newspaper=Sabahi |date=8 October 2012}}</ref> He comes from a middle-class background,<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/> and belongs to the [[Marehan]] [[Darod]] clan.<ref name=\"Afpspnnpm\">{{cite news |title=Somali president names new prime minister |url=http://www.nation.co.ke/News/africa/Somali+president+names+new+prime+minister/-/1066/1526730/-/w2tweo/-/index.html |accessdate=6 October 2012 |newspaper=[[Daily Nation]] |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |date=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nShirdon is married to [[Asha Haji Elmi]] a prominent peace activist and former Member of the [[Federal Parliament of Somalia]].<ref name=\"Rspnpnapm\">{{cite news |title=Somali president names political newcomer as PM - diplomats |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL6E8L60GZ20121006 |accessdate=6 October 2012 |publisher=Reuters Africa |date=6 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Adhspaanpm\">{{cite news |title=Somalia president appoints a new prime minister |url=http://democratherald.com/news/world/africa/somalia-president-appoints-a-new-prime-minister/article_371fb478-d2f5-5ff3-80a2-369a411c77f1.html |accessdate=6 October 2012 |newspaper=Albany Democrat Herald |date=6 October 2012}}</ref> The couple have four children.<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/>\n\nHe is also multilingual, speaking [[Somali language|Somali]], [[Italian language|Italian]] and [[English language|English]].<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/>\n\n===Education===\nAfter finishing high school, Shirdon relocated to Somalia's capital, [[Mogadishu]], to attend college. He studied at the [[Somali National University]] (SNU), where he earned a bachelor's degree in economics, graduating with honours in 1983. Furthering his education Abdi Farah Shirdoon attended the [[University of Oxford]] where he completed his Masters in Diplomatic Studies <ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/>\n\n===Early career===\nShirdon briefly worked as an economist in the national Ministry of Finance and Ministry of Agriculture from 1983 to 1985,<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/> during the [[Siad Barre]] administration.<ref name=\"Nnsppabapnapm\"/> He subsequently left government to pursue an entrepreneurial career. He established Shirdon International, serving as the company's CEO.<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/>\n\nAfter the [[Somali Civil War|civil war]] broke out in Somalia in 1991,<ref name=\"Adhspaanpm\"/> Shirdon moved to [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]]. There, he opened up another business, running a prominent import-export firm.<ref name=\"Nnsppabapnapm\"/><ref name=\"Afpspnnpm\"/>\n\nIn March 2012, Shirdon was also named Chairman of the Rajo Forum, a Somali civil society institution he co-founded composed of professionals, intellectuals, businesspeople and politicians.<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/><ref name=\"Bsmasatnpm\">{{cite news |title=Somalia MPs approve Shirdon as the new prime minister |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-19979371 |accessdate=18 October 2012 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=17 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Prime Minister of Somalia==\n===Appointment===\nOn 6 October 2012, Shirdon was appointed the new Prime Minister of Somalia by incumbent President [[Hassan Sheikh Mohamud]].<ref name=\"Rspnpnapm\"/> He succeeded [[Abdiweli Mohamed Ali]] in office. A close ally of President Mohamud,<ref name=\"Afpspnnpm\"/> Shirdon was reportedly chosen for the position due in part to his academic background.<ref name=\"Adhspaanpm\"/>\n\nHis selection was greeted with rallies of support in several cities across the country, including his hometown of Dhusamareb and [[Buuhoodle]]. The autonomous [[Puntland]] regional administration in northeastern Somalia also welcomed Shirdon's appointment and indicated that it would partner with the central government to uphold the new federal system of governance.<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/>\n\nIf endorsed, Shirdon pledged that he would name a competent and cohesive Cabinet with no tolerance for corruption.<ref name=\"Adhspaanpm\"/> He also vowed in a statement that he would perform his duties in accordance with the national [[Constitution of Somalia|Constitution]].<ref name=\"Nnsppabapnapm\"/>\n\nOn 17 October 2012, the [[Federal Parliament of Somalia|Federal Parliament]] approved Shirdon as Prime Minister by a large majority, with 215 of 275 legislators endorsing his nomination.<ref name=Cslanpm>{{cite news |title=Somali lawmakers approve new prime minister |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/10/17/world/africa/somalia-prime-minister/index.html |accessdate=17 October 2012 |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=17 October 2012}}</ref> UN Special Representative for Somalia [[Augustine Mahiga]] welcomed the development, describing it as \"further incontrovertible evidence of progress in Somalia\". Mahiga also pledged to collaborate with the new Somali government in the post-conflict reconstruction process.<ref name=\"Rspcafsanp\">{{cite news|title=Somali Parliament Confirms Abdi Farah Shirdon As New PM |url=http://www.rttnews.com/1985413/somali-parliament-confirms-abdi-farah-shirdon-as-new-pm.aspx?type=gn |accessdate=18 October 2012 |publisher=[[RTTNews]] |date=17 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221411/http://www.rttnews.com/1985413/somali-parliament-confirms-abdi-farah-shirdon-as-new-pm.aspx?type=gn |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Cabinet===\nOn 4 November 2012, Shirdon named a new 10 member Cabinet after extensive consultations with local stakeholders. The council of ministers consists of many newcomers, including two women: [[Fowsiyo Yussuf Haji Aadan]] as the nation's first female Minister of Foreign Affairs, and [[Maryam Kassim]] as Minister of Social Development.<ref name=\"Smnspmuhnc\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Prime Minister Unveils His New Cabinet|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201211050009.html|accessdate=5 November 2012|newspaper=Shabelle Media Network|date=4 November 2012}}</ref> The new Cabinet was later endorsed by the legislature on 13 November 2012, with 219 MPs approving the selection, 3 voting against it, and 3 abstaining.<ref name=\"Agapspedc\">{{cite news|last=Guled|first=Abdi|title=Somali parliament endorses downsized Cabinet|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20121113/af-somalia-cabinet/|accessdate=13 November 2012|newspaper=Associated Press|date=13 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Task Force===\nIn early February 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon launched an Independent Task Force on Human Rights in order to firm up on the protection of individual rights. The 13-member committee of volunteers was formed after extensive consultations with civil society groups and the Speaker of Parliament, [[Mohamed Osman Jawari]]. Chaired by prominent human rights attorney Maryam Yusuf Sheikh Ali, one of four women on the panel, the Task Force includes an educator, a peace activist, leaders of Somali women's organizations, senior police officers, a humanitarian campaigner, a religious leader, and a media representative. It is tasked with investigating allegations of human rights abuses and journalist intimidation. At the end of its three-month mandate, the committee is scheduled to publish a report on its findings and recommended courses of action. The Task Force will eventually give way to a permanent parliamentary Human Rights Commission, which will have the capacity to investigate allegations over a longer period.<ref name=\"Xspmlhrtf\">{{cite news|title=Somali PM launches Human Rights Task Force |url=http://www.xikmo.com/en/?p=3092 |accessdate=10 March 2013 |newspaper=Xikmo |date=6 February 2013 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Listening Tour===\nIn February 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon, along with Minister of Defence [[Abdihakim Mohamoud Haji-Faqi]], Minister of Interior [[Abdikarim Hussein Guled]], and Deputy Speaker of Parliament [[Jaylaani Nur Ikar]], embarked on a Listening Tour of various cities across Somalia to meet with the population, establish public service priorities, and facilitate the creation of local administrations. Shirdon pledged that the federal government would deliver public services to the regions, contingent with the formation of effective local government and an acceleration of the reconciliation process. Toward this end, he negotiated an agreement with community leaders in the central [[Galguduud]] province to set up a district administration and signed a cooperative security pact with [[Ahlu Sunna Waljama'a]].<ref name=\"Prpmblgafsonltcig\">{{cite news|last=Ahmed Adan Prime Minister's Media Office |title=Press Release: PM boosts local government as first stage of national Listening Tour closes in Galgadud |url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/03/somalia-pm-boosts-local-government-as-first-stage-of-national-listening-tour-closes-in-galgadud/ |accessdate=10 March 2013 |newspaper=Raxanreeb |date=6 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310053321/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/03/somalia-pm-boosts-local-government-as-first-stage-of-national-listening-tour-closes-in-galgadud/ |archivedate=10 March 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Prpmltctg\">{{cite news|last=Ahmed Adan, Prime Minister's Media Office |title=Press Release: Prime Minister's Listening Tour continues to Garowe |url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/03/somalia-prime-ministers-listening-tour-continues-to-garowe/ |accessdate=10 March 2013 |newspaper=Raxanreeb |date=9 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314095458/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/03/somalia-prime-ministers-listening-tour-continues-to-garowe/ |archivedate=14 March 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Counter-terrorism law===\nOn April 18, 2013, the Premier's Office announced in a press release that the Somali Council of Ministers had approved draft legislation on a new [[counter-terrorism]] law. The bill formalizes proper conduct and structures vis-a-vis the national security and intelligence agencies. It also establishes a legal definition for terrorism, and aims to meet international best practices. According to Prime Minister Shirdon, the law constitutes a key component of his administration's counter-terrorism strategy. It is now expected to be put before the legislature for deliberation and approval.<ref name=\"Sscactl\">{{cite news|title=Somali cabinet approves counter-terrorism law|url=http://sabahionline.com/en_GB/articles/hoa/articles/newsbriefs/2013/04/19/newsbrief-02|accessdate=21 June 2013|newspaper=Sabahi|date=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Public Finance Management Policy===\nIn May 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon announced that the Somali federal government had launched a new Public Finance Management Policy (PFMP) in order to streamline the public sector's financial system and to strengthen the delivery capacity of the government's financial sector. Endorsed by the Council of Ministers on May 2, the reform plan is intended to serve as a benchmark for public financial management and the re-establishment of national institutions. The PFMP aims to provide transparent, accurate and timely public sector financial information by ameliorating the national budget process' openness, rendering more efficient and effective public spending, and improving fiscal discipline via both internal and external control. It also sets out to concentrate public expenditure on government priority areas. According to Cabinet members, the policy will cost an estimated $26 million and is expected to be fully implemented over the next fours years.<ref name=\"Arsanfp\">{{cite news|last=Khalif|first=Abdulkadir|title=Somalia adopts new finance policy|url=http://www.africareview.com/Business---Finance/Somalia-adopts-new-finance-policy/-/979184/1840986/-/sbrewsz/-/index.html|accessdate=5 June 2013|newspaper=Africa Review|date=3 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Somali Disaster Management Agency===\nOn May 30, 2013, the [[Federal Government of Somalia]] announced that the Cabinet had approved draft legislation on a new [[Somali Disaster Management Agency]] (SDMA), which had originally been proposed by the Ministry of Interior. According to Prime Minister Shirdon's Media Office, the SDMA will lead and coordinate the government's response to various natural disasters. It is part of a broader effort by the federal authorities to re-establish national institutions. The Federal Parliament is now expected to deliberate on the proposed bill for endorsement after any amendments.<ref name=\"Rspmcfptel\">{{cite news|last=Prime Minister\u2019s Media Office |title=SOMALIA: Prime Minister calls for parliament to enact legislation as Cabinet moves to establish disaster management agency |url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/05/somalia-prime-minister-calls-for-parliament-to-enact-legislation-as-cabinet-moves-to-establish-disaster-management-agency/ |accessdate=5 June 2013 |newspaper=Raxanreeb |date=30 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608200154/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/05/somalia-prime-minister-calls-for-parliament-to-enact-legislation-as-cabinet-moves-to-establish-disaster-management-agency/ |archivedate=8 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Foreign investment law===\nOn June 10, 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon signed a new [[foreign direct investment|foreign investment]] law. The draft bill was prepared by the Ministry of Commerce and Industry in conjunction with government attorneys. Approved by the Cabinet, it establishes a secure legal framework for foreign investment. Shirdon welcomed the legislation as an important step toward creating a business-friendly environment. The bill will now be presented to parliament for approval, where Minister of Commerce and Industry, Mohamoud Ahmed Hassan, is slated to field questions from lawmakers. A committee is also set to review the draft law line-by-line and make additional procedural recommendations.<ref name=\"Rspmwfilabfsitrd\">{{cite news|last=Prime Minister\u2019s Media Office |title=SOMALIA: Prime Minister welcomes foreign investment law as business-friendly step in the right direction |url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/06/somalia-prime-minister-welcomes-foreign-investment-law-as-business-friendly-step-in-the-right-direction/ |accessdate=21 June 2013 |newspaper=Raxanreeb |date=10 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614225723/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/06/somalia-prime-minister-welcomes-foreign-investment-law-as-business-friendly-step-in-the-right-direction/ |archivedate=14 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Civil aviation law===\nOn June 13, 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon's Office announced that the Cabinet had forwarded to parliament a new draft [[civil aviation]] law. The bill is part of a larger initiative by the federal authorities to reassume control of Somalia's airspace. According to Abdullahi Ilmoge Hirsi, Minister of Information, Posts and Telecommunications, the law aims to develop national aviation skills. It is also expected to help spur economic growth and facilitate the creation of employment opportunities.<ref name=\"Sscacal\">{{cite news|title=Somali cabinet approves civil aviation law|url=http://sabahionline.com/en_GB/articles/hoa/articles/newsbriefs/2013/06/14/newsbrief-02|accessdate=21 June 2013|newspaper=Sabahi|date=14 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Somali National University===\nOn 14 November 2013, Shirdon's Cabinet unanimously approved a federal government plan to reopen the [[Somali National University]] (SNU), which had closed down in the early 1990s. The SNU had historically served as an expansive institution of higher learning, with 13 departments, 700 staff and over 15,000 students. The refurbishing initiative is expected to cost $3.6 million USD, and is part of a broader government effort to re-establish national institutions.<ref name=\"Ceptrsnu\">{{cite news|title=Cabinet endorses plans to reopen Somali National University|url=http://horseedmedia.net/2013/11/14/cabinet-endorses-plans-reopen-somali-national-university/|accessdate=18 November 2013|newspaper=Horseed Media|date=14 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Vote of confidence===\nOn 6 October 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon announced that he would significantly reshuffle the Council of Ministers in response to speculation regarding his potential resignation. He also highlighted the growth in revenue that the federal government managed to secure under his administration, with monthly proceeds having risen from $2.5 million to $10 million.<ref name=\"Gspsboeg\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: PM Shirdon boasts of economic growth |url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_PM_Shirdon_boasts_of_Budget_growth_printer.shtml |accessdate=2 December 2013 |newspaper=Garowe Online |date=6 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203040552/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_PM_Shirdon_boasts_of_Budget_growth_printer.shtml |archivedate=3 December 2013 }}</ref> The following month, President Hassan Sheikh Mohamud asked Shirdon to resign from office on the grounds that Shirdon was allegedly ineffective in the job. Mohamud was reportedly acting on the advice of the State Minister for Presidency, Farah Abdulkadir.<ref name=\"Gspmatsd\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Prime Minister asked to step down |url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_Prime_Minister_asked_to_step_down_printer.shtml |accessdate=2 December 2013 |newspaper=Garowe Online |date=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203025544/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_Prime_Minister_asked_to_step_down_printer.shtml |archivedate=3 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 12 November 2013, Shirdon confirmed that there was a dispute between himself and the president, but indicated that the row was constitutional rather than political. He also asserted that the matter should be resolved in parliament.<ref name=\"Sspmarwp\">{{cite news|title=Somali prime minister admits rift with president|url=http://sabahionline.com/en_GB/articles/hoa/articles/newsbriefs/2013/11/13/newsbrief-01|accessdate=2 December 2013|newspaper=Sabahi|date=13 November 2013}}</ref> According to MP Mohamed Abdi Yusuf, the rift between Shirdon and Mohamud centered over through what constitutional mechanism and by whom the Cabinet was ultimately to be formed. The relevant Articles 90, 100 and 69 of the [[Constitution of Somalia|national constitution]] address these issues, specifying that the President has the power to appoint the Prime Minister; the Prime Minister, in turn, has the discretionary power to appoint members of the Council of Ministers, who then must be endorsed by the House of the People of the Federal Parliament; and the House of the People of the Federal Parliament likewise has the power to endorse or remove the Prime Minister through a vote of confidence.<ref name=\"Ssccoroppmap\">{{cite news|title=Somali constitution clear on roles of president, prime minister and parliament|url=http://sabahionline.com/en_GB/articles/hoa/articles/newsbriefs/2013/11/15/newsbrief-01|accessdate=2 December 2013|newspaper=Sabahi|date=15 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 November 2013, 168 MPs endorsed a document submitted to parliament, which outlined a motion against Prime Minister Shirdon's administration. A group of legislators believed to be loyal to Shirdon suggested that the document may not have been properly endorsed, and demanded that the names of the lawmakers who approved the motion be attached to the paper.<ref name=\"Gsptfvtw\">{{cite news|title=Somali PM to face vote this week |url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somali-PM-to-face-vote-this-week_printer.shtml |accessdate=2 December 2013 |newspaper=Garowe Online |date=26 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203030320/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somali-PM-to-face-vote-this-week_printer.shtml |archivedate=3 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 December 2013, 140 MPs voted against a request from Shirdon and the Speaker of the Parliament Mohamed Osman Jawari asking lawmakers to allow Shirdon to appear before the national assembly in order to brief legislators on his government's accomplishments. Shirdon subsequently issued a statement wherein he asserted that the constitution conferred upon him the right to defend himself against the motion, insisting that the proposal was not based on evidence and fair information. He also indicated that his administration had prepared a full response report and that he still wanted an opportunity to address the national assembly. Additionally, Shirdon stated that he would not abide by any decision made in his absence. According to [[Garowe Online]], independent sources in Mogadishu indicated that the motion was being led by former TFG Parliament Speaker [[Sharif Hassan Sheikh Adan]].<ref name=\"Gosfmdimap\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Federal MPs debate impeachment motion against PM |url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Federal-MPs-debate-impeachment-motion-against-PM_printer.shtml |accessdate=2 December 2013 |newspaper=Garowe Online |date=1 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203034015/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Federal-MPs-debate-impeachment-motion-against-PM_printer.shtml |archivedate=3 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 2 December 2013, a parliamentary [[vote of confidence]] was held against Shirdon. Parliament Speaker Jawari subsequently announced that 184 of the present MPs had voted against the Prime Minister, whereas 65 legislators had voted to retain him.<ref>[http://www.hiiraan.com/news4/2013/Dec/52307/somali_parliament_impeaches_prime_minister_shirdon.aspx \"Somali parliament impeaches Prime minister Shirdon\"], Hiiraan.com, on 2 December 2013.</ref> On 5 December 2013, Shirdon released a statement confirming that he and his Cabinet accepted the legislature's decision. He also expressed disappointment that he had not been allowed to address parliament, and urged the citizenry to support the incoming administration in order build on the development gains that had been achieved during his tenure.<ref name=\"Qpmtc\">{{cite news|title=Prime Minister thanks Cabinet for their hard work and dedication over the past year |url=http://www.qurbejoog.com/2013/12/05/prime-minister-thanks-cabinet-for-their-hard-work-and-dedication-over-the-past-year/ |accessdate=9 December 2013 |newspaper=Quberjoog |date=5 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214060825/http://www.qurbejoog.com/2013/12/05/prime-minister-thanks-cabinet-for-their-hard-work-and-dedication-over-the-past-year/ |archivedate=14 December 2013 }}</ref> UN Special Representative for Somalia [[Nicholas Kay]] paid tribute to the outgoing Prime Minister, noting that Shirdon had endeavoured to promote growth and progress and was an important principal in establishing the New Deal Compact between Somalia and its international partners. He also commended the legislators on adhering to procedural rules during the vote, and pledged to work constructively with the succeeding administration.<ref name=\"Rsnkptsopmafss\">{{cite news|title=SOMALIA: Nicholas Kay paid tribute today to Somalia\u2019s outgoing Prime Minister, Abdi Farah Shirdon Saaid|url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/12/somalia-nicholas-kay-paid-tribute-today-to-somalias-outgoing-prime-minister-abdi-farah-shirdon-saaid/|accessdate=2 December 2013|newspaper=Raxanreeb|date=2 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203011533/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/12/somalia-nicholas-kay-paid-tribute-today-to-somalias-outgoing-prime-minister-abdi-farah-shirdon-saaid/|archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref> On 12 December 2013, President Mohamud named [[Abdiweli Sheikh Ahmed]] as the new Prime Minister.<ref name=\"Msphmwbaasaatnp\">{{cite news|title=Somali President Hassan Mohamud will be appointing Abdiweli Sheikh Ahmed as the next PM|url=http://www.midnimo.com/2013/12/12/breaking-somali-president-hassan-mohamud-will-appointing-abdiweli-sheikh-ahmed-next-pm/|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=Midnimo|date=12 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Abdiweli Mohamed Ali]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Somalia]]|years=2012\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after={{nowrap|[[Abdiweli Sheikh Ahmed]]}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SomaliaPMs}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shirdon, Abdi Farah}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Ethnic Somali people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Somalia]]\n[[Category:Somalian economists]]\n[[Category:Somali National University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Abdi Shirdon<br>{{small|\u0639\u0628\u062f\u064a \u0641\u0627\u0631\u062d \u0634\u0631\u062f\u0648\u0646}}\n| office = 16th [[Prime Minister of Somalia]]\n| image = File:Abdi Farah Shirdon.png\n| president = [[Hassan Sheikh Mohamud]]\n| term_start = 17 October 2012\n| term_end = 21 December 2013\n| predecessor = [[Abdiweli Mohamed Ali]]\n| successor = [[Abdiweli Sheikh Ahmed]]\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1958}}\n| birth_place = [[Dhusamareb]], [[Somalia]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n| alma_mater = [[Somali National University]]\n| spouse = [[Asha Haji Elmi]]\n| website = http://abdifarah.org/\n}}\n'''Abdi Farah Shirdon''' ({{lang-so|Cabdi Faarax Shirdoon}}; {{lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f\u064a \u0641\u0627\u0631\u062d \u0634\u0631\u062f\u0648\u0646}}; born 1958) is a [[Somali people|Somali]] businessman, economist and politician. He served as the [[Prime Minister of Somalia|Prime Minister]] of [[Somalia]] between October 2012 and December 2013. Shirdon is credited with having overseen significant development in social services and the national budget, as well as improving local security.<ref name=\"Gosfmdimap\"/>\n\n==Background==\n===Personal life===\nShirdon was born in 1958 in the town of [[Dhusamareb]], situated in the central [[Galguduud]] region of [[Somalia]].<ref name=\"Nnsppabapnapm\">{{cite news |last=Ibrahim |first=Mohammed |title=New Somalian President Picks a Businessman, a Political Newcomer, as Prime Minister |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/07/world/africa/somalian-president-picks-businessman-abdi-farah-shirdon-saaid-as-prime-minister.html?_r=1 |accessdate=7 October 2012 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=6 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\">{{cite news |title=Somalis welcome new prime minister but see difficult road ahead |url=http://sabahionline.com/en_GB/articles/hoa/articles/features/2012/10/08/feature-01 |accessdate=9 October 2012 |newspaper=Sabahi |date=8 October 2012}}</ref> He comes from a middle-class background,<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/> and belongs to the [[Marehan]] [[Darod]] clan.<ref name=\"Afpspnnpm\">{{cite news |title=Somali president names new prime minister |url=http://www.nation.co.ke/News/africa/Somali+president+names+new+prime+minister/-/1066/1526730/-/w2tweo/-/index.html |accessdate=6 October 2012 |newspaper=[[Daily Nation]] |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |date=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nShirdon is married to [[Asha Haji Elmi]] a prominent peace activist and former Member of the [[Federal Parliament of Somalia]].<ref name=\"Rspnpnapm\">{{cite news |title=Somali president names political newcomer as PM - diplomats |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL6E8L60GZ20121006 |accessdate=6 October 2012 |publisher=Reuters Africa |date=6 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Adhspaanpm\">{{cite news |title=Somalia president appoints a new prime minister |url=http://democratherald.com/news/world/africa/somalia-president-appoints-a-new-prime-minister/article_371fb478-d2f5-5ff3-80a2-369a411c77f1.html |accessdate=6 October 2012 |newspaper=Albany Democrat Herald |date=6 October 2012}}</ref> The couple have four children.<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/>\n\nHe is also multilingual, speaking [[Somali language|Somali]], [[Italian language|Italian]] and [[English language|English]].<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/>\n\n===Education===\nAfter finishing high school, Shirdon relocated to Somalia's capital, [[Mogadishu]], to attend college. He studied at the [[Somali National University]] (SNU), where he earned a bachelor's degree in economics, graduating with honours in 1983. Furthering his education Abdi Farah Shirdoon attended the [[University of Oxford]] where he completed his Masters in Diplomatic Studies <ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/>\n\n===Early career===\nShirdon briefly worked as an economist in the national Ministry of Finance and Ministry of Agriculture from 1983 to 1985,<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/> during the [[Siad Barre]] administration.<ref name=\"Nnsppabapnapm\"/> He subsequently left government to pursue an entrepreneurial career. He established Shirdon International, serving as the company's CEO.<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/>\n\nAfter the [[Somali Civil War|civil war]] broke out in Somalia in 1991,<ref name=\"Adhspaanpm\"/> Shirdon moved to [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]]. There, he opened up another business, running a prominent import-export firm.<ref name=\"Nnsppabapnapm\"/><ref name=\"Afpspnnpm\"/>\n\nIn March 2012, Shirdon was also named Chairman of the Rajo Forum, a Somali civil society institution he co-founded composed of professionals, intellectuals, businesspeople and politicians.<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/><ref name=\"Bsmasatnpm\">{{cite news |title=Somalia MPs approve Shirdon as the new prime minister |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-19979371 |accessdate=18 October 2012 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=17 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Prime Minister of Somalia==\n===Appointment===\nOn 6 October 2012, Shirdon was appointed the new Prime Minister of Somalia by incumbent President [[Hassan Sheikh Mohamud]].<ref name=\"Rspnpnapm\"/> He succeeded [[Abdiweli Mohamed Ali]] in office. A close ally of President Mohamud,<ref name=\"Afpspnnpm\"/> Shirdon was reportedly chosen for the position due in part to his academic background.<ref name=\"Adhspaanpm\"/>\n\nHis selection was greeted with rallies of support in several cities across the country, including his hometown of Dhusamareb and [[Buuhoodle]]. The autonomous [[Puntland]] regional administration in northeastern Somalia also welcomed Shirdon's appointment and indicated that it would partner with the central government to uphold the new federal system of governance.<ref name=\"Sswnpmbsdra\"/>\n\nIf endorsed, Shirdon pledged that he would name a competent and cohesive Cabinet with no tolerance for corruption.<ref name=\"Adhspaanpm\"/> He also vowed in a statement that he would perform his duties in accordance with the national [[Constitution of Somalia|Constitution]].<ref name=\"Nnsppabapnapm\"/>\n\nOn 17 October 2012, the [[Federal Parliament of Somalia|Federal Parliament]] approved Shirdon as Prime Minister by a large majority, with 215 of 275 legislators endorsing his nomination.<ref name=Cslanpm>{{cite news |title=Somali lawmakers approve new prime minister |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/10/17/world/africa/somalia-prime-minister/index.html |accessdate=17 October 2012 |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=17 October 2012}}</ref> UN Special Representative for Somalia [[Augustine Mahiga]] welcomed the development, describing it as \"further incontrovertible evidence of progress in Somalia\". Mahiga also pledged to collaborate with the new Somali government in the post-conflict reconstruction process.<ref name=\"Rspcafsanp\">{{cite news|title=Somali Parliament Confirms Abdi Farah Shirdon As New PM |url=http://www.rttnews.com/1985413/somali-parliament-confirms-abdi-farah-shirdon-as-new-pm.aspx?type=gn |accessdate=18 October 2012 |publisher=[[RTTNews]] |date=17 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221411/http://www.rttnews.com/1985413/somali-parliament-confirms-abdi-farah-shirdon-as-new-pm.aspx?type=gn |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Cabinet===\nOn 4 November 2012, Shirdon named a new 10 member Cabinet after extensive consultations with local stakeholders. The council of ministers consists of many newcomers, including two women: [[Fowsiyo Yussuf Haji Aadan]] as the nation's first female Minister of Foreign Affairs, and [[Maryam Kassim]] as Minister of Social Development.<ref name=\"Smnspmuhnc\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Prime Minister Unveils His New Cabinet|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201211050009.html|accessdate=5 November 2012|newspaper=Shabelle Media Network|date=4 November 2012}}</ref> The new Cabinet was later endorsed by the legislature on 13 November 2012, with 219 MPs approving the selection, 3 voting against it, and 3 abstaining.<ref name=\"Agapspedc\">{{cite news|last=Guled|first=Abdi|title=Somali parliament endorses downsized Cabinet|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20121113/af-somalia-cabinet/|accessdate=13 November 2012|newspaper=Associated Press|date=13 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Task Force===\nIn early February 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon launched an Independent Task Force on Human Rights in order to firm up on the protection of individual rights. The 13-member committee of volunteers was formed after extensive consultations with civil society groups and the Speaker of Parliament, [[Mohamed Osman Jawari]]. Chaired by prominent human rights attorney Maryam Yusuf Sheikh Ali, one of four women on the panel, the Task Force includes an educator, a peace activist, leaders of Somali women's organizations, senior police officers, a humanitarian campaigner, a religious leader, and a media representative. It is tasked with investigating allegations of human rights abuses and journalist intimidation. At the end of its three-month mandate, the committee is scheduled to publish a report on its findings and recommended courses of action. The Task Force will eventually give way to a permanent parliamentary Human Rights Commission, which will have the capacity to investigate allegations over a longer period.<ref name=\"Xspmlhrtf\">{{cite news|title=Somali PM launches Human Rights Task Force |url=http://www.xikmo.com/en/?p=3092 |accessdate=10 March 2013 |newspaper=Xikmo |date=6 February 2013 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Listening Tour===\nIn February 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon, along with Minister of Defence [[Abdihakim Mohamoud Haji-Faqi]], Minister of Interior [[Abdikarim Hussein Guled]], and Deputy Speaker of Parliament [[Jaylaani Nur Ikar]], embarked on a Listening Tour of various cities across Somalia to meet with the population, establish public service priorities, and facilitate the creation of local administrations. Shirdon pledged that the federal government would deliver public services to the regions, contingent with the formation of effective local government and an acceleration of the reconciliation process. Toward this end, he negotiated an agreement with community leaders in the central [[Galguduud]] province to set up a district administration and signed a cooperative security pact with [[Ahlu Sunna Waljama'a]].<ref name=\"Prpmblgafsonltcig\">{{cite news|last=Ahmed Adan Prime Minister's Media Office |title=Press Release: PM boosts local government as first stage of national Listening Tour closes in Galgadud |url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/03/somalia-pm-boosts-local-government-as-first-stage-of-national-listening-tour-closes-in-galgadud/ |accessdate=10 March 2013 |newspaper=Raxanreeb |date=6 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310053321/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/03/somalia-pm-boosts-local-government-as-first-stage-of-national-listening-tour-closes-in-galgadud/ |archivedate=10 March 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Prpmltctg\">{{cite news|last=Ahmed Adan, Prime Minister's Media Office |title=Press Release: Prime Minister's Listening Tour continues to Garowe |url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/03/somalia-prime-ministers-listening-tour-continues-to-garowe/ |accessdate=10 March 2013 |newspaper=Raxanreeb |date=9 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314095458/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/03/somalia-prime-ministers-listening-tour-continues-to-garowe/ |archivedate=14 March 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Counter-terrorism law===\nOn April 18, 2013, the Premier's Office announced in a press release that the Somali Council of Ministers had approved draft legislation on a new [[counter-terrorism]] law. The bill formalizes proper conduct and structures vis-a-vis the national security and intelligence agencies. It also establishes a legal definition for terrorism, and aims to meet international best practices. According to Prime Minister Shirdon, the law constitutes a key component of his administration's counter-terrorism strategy. It is now expected to be put before the legislature for deliberation and approval.<ref name=\"Sscactl\">{{cite news|title=Somali cabinet approves counter-terrorism law|url=http://sabahionline.com/en_GB/articles/hoa/articles/newsbriefs/2013/04/19/newsbrief-02|accessdate=21 June 2013|newspaper=Sabahi|date=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Public Finance Management Policy===\nIn May 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon announced that the Somali federal government had launched a new Public Finance Management Policy (PFMP) in order to streamline the public sector's financial system and to strengthen the delivery capacity of the government's financial sector. Endorsed by the Council of Ministers on May 2, the reform plan is intended to serve as a benchmark for public financial management and the re-establishment of national institutions. The PFMP aims to provide transparent, accurate and timely public sector financial information by ameliorating the national budget process' openness, rendering more efficient and effective public spending, and improving fiscal discipline via both internal and external control. It also sets out to concentrate public expenditure on government priority areas. According to Cabinet members, the policy will cost an estimated $26 million and is expected to be fully implemented over the next fours years.<ref name=\"Arsanfp\">{{cite news|last=Khalif|first=Abdulkadir|title=Somalia adopts new finance policy|url=http://www.africareview.com/Business---Finance/Somalia-adopts-new-finance-policy/-/979184/1840986/-/sbrewsz/-/index.html|accessdate=5 June 2013|newspaper=Africa Review|date=3 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Somali Disaster Management Agency===\nOn May 30, 2013, the [[Federal Government of Somalia]] announced that the Cabinet had approved draft legislation on a new [[Somali Disaster Management Agency]] (SDMA), which had originally been proposed by the Ministry of Interior. According to Prime Minister Shirdon's Media Office, the SDMA will lead and coordinate the government's response to various natural disasters. It is part of a broader effort by the federal authorities to re-establish national institutions. The Federal Parliament is now expected to deliberate on the proposed bill for endorsement after any amendments.<ref name=\"Rspmcfptel\">{{cite news|last=Prime Minister\u2019s Media Office |title=SOMALIA: Prime Minister calls for parliament to enact legislation as Cabinet moves to establish disaster management agency |url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/05/somalia-prime-minister-calls-for-parliament-to-enact-legislation-as-cabinet-moves-to-establish-disaster-management-agency/ |accessdate=5 June 2013 |newspaper=Raxanreeb |date=30 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608200154/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/05/somalia-prime-minister-calls-for-parliament-to-enact-legislation-as-cabinet-moves-to-establish-disaster-management-agency/ |archivedate=8 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Foreign investment law===\nOn June 10, 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon signed a new [[foreign direct investment|foreign investment]] law. The draft bill was prepared by the Ministry of Commerce and Industry in conjunction with government attorneys. Approved by the Cabinet, it establishes a secure legal framework for foreign investment. Shirdon welcomed the legislation as an important step toward creating a business-friendly environment. The bill will now be presented to parliament for approval, where Minister of Commerce and Industry, Mohamoud Ahmed Hassan, is slated to field questions from lawmakers. A committee is also set to review the draft law line-by-line and make additional procedural recommendations.<ref name=\"Rspmwfilabfsitrd\">{{cite news|last=Prime Minister\u2019s Media Office |title=SOMALIA: Prime Minister welcomes foreign investment law as business-friendly step in the right direction |url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/06/somalia-prime-minister-welcomes-foreign-investment-law-as-business-friendly-step-in-the-right-direction/ |accessdate=21 June 2013 |newspaper=Raxanreeb |date=10 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614225723/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/06/somalia-prime-minister-welcomes-foreign-investment-law-as-business-friendly-step-in-the-right-direction/ |archivedate=14 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Civil aviation law===\nOn June 13, 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon's Office announced that the Cabinet had forwarded to parliament a new draft [[civil aviation]] law. The bill is part of a larger initiative by the federal authorities to reassume control of Somalia's airspace. According to Abdullahi Ilmoge Hirsi, Minister of Information, Posts and Telecommunications, the law aims to develop national aviation skills. It is also expected to help spur economic growth and facilitate the creation of employment opportunities.<ref name=\"Sscacal\">{{cite news|title=Somali cabinet approves civil aviation law|url=http://sabahionline.com/en_GB/articles/hoa/articles/newsbriefs/2013/06/14/newsbrief-02|accessdate=21 June 2013|newspaper=Sabahi|date=14 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Somali National University===\nOn 14 November 2013, Shirdon's Cabinet unanimously approved a federal government plan to reopen the [[Somali National University]] (SNU), which had closed down in the early 1990s. The SNU had historically served as an expansive institution of higher learning, with 13 departments, 700 staff and over 15,000 students. The refurbishing initiative is expected to cost $3.6 million USD, and is part of a broader government effort to re-establish national institutions.<ref name=\"Ceptrsnu\">{{cite news|title=Cabinet endorses plans to reopen Somali National University|url=http://horseedmedia.net/2013/11/14/cabinet-endorses-plans-reopen-somali-national-university/|accessdate=18 November 2013|newspaper=Horseed Media|date=14 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Vote of confidence===\nOn 6 October 2013, Prime Minister Shirdon announced that he would significantly reshuffle the Council of Ministers in response to speculation regarding his potential resignation. He also highlighted the growth in revenue that the federal government managed to secure under his administration, with monthly proceeds having risen from $2.5 million to $10 million.<ref name=\"Gspsboeg\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: PM Shirdon boasts of economic growth |url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_PM_Shirdon_boasts_of_Budget_growth_printer.shtml |accessdate=2 December 2013 |newspaper=Garowe Online |date=6 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203040552/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_PM_Shirdon_boasts_of_Budget_growth_printer.shtml |archivedate=3 December 2013 }}</ref> The following month, President Hassan Sheikh Mohamud asked Shirdon to resign from office on the grounds that Shirdon was allegedly ineffective in the job. Mohamud was reportedly acting on the advice of the State Minister for Presidency, Farah Abdulkadir.<ref name=\"Gspmatsd\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Prime Minister asked to step down |url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_Prime_Minister_asked_to_step_down_printer.shtml |accessdate=2 December 2013 |newspaper=Garowe Online |date=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203025544/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_Prime_Minister_asked_to_step_down_printer.shtml |archivedate=3 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 12 November 2013, Shirdon confirmed that there was a dispute between himself and the president, but indicated that the row was constitutional rather than political. He also asserted that the matter should be resolved in parliament.<ref name=\"Sspmarwp\">{{cite news|title=Somali prime minister admits rift with president|url=http://sabahionline.com/en_GB/articles/hoa/articles/newsbriefs/2013/11/13/newsbrief-01|accessdate=2 December 2013|newspaper=Sabahi|date=13 November 2013}}</ref> According to MP Mohamed Abdi Yusuf, the rift between Shirdon and Mohamud centered over through what constitutional mechanism and by whom the Cabinet was ultimately to be formed. The relevant Articles 90, 100 and 69 of the [[Constitution of Somalia|national constitution]] address these issues, specifying that the President has the power to appoint the Prime Minister; the Prime Minister, in turn, has the discretionary power to appoint members of the Council of Ministers, who then must be endorsed by the House of the People of the Federal Parliament; and the House of the People of the Federal Parliament likewise has the power to endorse or remove the Prime Minister through a vote of confidence.<ref name=\"Ssccoroppmap\">{{cite news|title=Somali constitution clear on roles of president, prime minister and parliament|url=http://sabahionline.com/en_GB/articles/hoa/articles/newsbriefs/2013/11/15/newsbrief-01|accessdate=2 December 2013|newspaper=Sabahi|date=15 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 November 2013, 168 MPs endorsed a document submitted to parliament, which outlined a motion against Prime Minister Shirdon's administration. A group of legislators believed to be loyal to Shirdon suggested that the document may not have been properly endorsed, and demanded that the names of the lawmakers who approved the motion be attached to the paper.<ref name=\"Gsptfvtw\">{{cite news|title=Somali PM to face vote this week |url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somali-PM-to-face-vote-this-week_printer.shtml |accessdate=2 December 2013 |newspaper=Garowe Online |date=26 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203030320/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somali-PM-to-face-vote-this-week_printer.shtml |archivedate=3 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 December 2013, 140 MPs voted against a request from Shirdon and the Speaker of the Parliament Mohamed Osman Jawari asking lawmakers to allow Shirdon to appear before the national assembly in order to brief legislators on his government's accomplishments. Shirdon subsequently issued a statement wherein he asserted that the constitution conferred upon him the right to defend himself against the motion, insisting that the proposal was not based on evidence and fair information. He also indicated that his administration had prepared a full response report and that he still wanted an opportunity to address the national assembly. Additionally, Shirdon stated that he would not abide by any decision made in his absence. According to [[Garowe Online]], independent sources in Mogadishu indicated that the motion was being led by former TFG Parliament Speaker [[Sharif Hassan Sheikh Adan]].<ref name=\"Gosfmdimap\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Federal MPs debate impeachment motion against PM |url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Federal-MPs-debate-impeachment-motion-against-PM_printer.shtml |accessdate=2 December 2013 |newspaper=Garowe Online |date=1 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203034015/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Federal-MPs-debate-impeachment-motion-against-PM_printer.shtml |archivedate=3 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 2 December 2013, a parliamentary [[vote of confidence]] was held against Shirdon. Parliament Speaker Jawari subsequently announced that 184 of the present MPs had voted against the Prime Minister, whereas 65 legislators had voted to retain him.<ref>[http://www.hiiraan.com/news4/2013/Dec/52307/somali_parliament_impeaches_prime_minister_shirdon.aspx \"Somali parliament impeaches Prime minister Shirdon\"], Hiiraan.com, on 2 December 2013.</ref> On 5 December 2013, Shirdon released a statement confirming that he and his Cabinet accepted the legislature's decision. He also expressed disappointment that he had not been allowed to address parliament, and urged the citizenry to support the incoming administration in order build on the development gains that had been achieved during his tenure.<ref name=\"Qpmtc\">{{cite news|title=Prime Minister thanks Cabinet for their hard work and dedication over the past year |url=http://www.qurbejoog.com/2013/12/05/prime-minister-thanks-cabinet-for-their-hard-work-and-dedication-over-the-past-year/ |accessdate=9 December 2013 |newspaper=Quberjoog |date=5 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214060825/http://www.qurbejoog.com/2013/12/05/prime-minister-thanks-cabinet-for-their-hard-work-and-dedication-over-the-past-year/ |archivedate=14 December 2013 }}</ref> UN Special Representative for Somalia [[Nicholas Kay]] paid tribute to the outgoing Prime Minister, noting that Shirdon had endeavoured to promote growth and progress and was an important principal in establishing the New Deal Compact between Somalia and its international partners. He also commended the legislators on adhering to procedural rules during the vote, and pledged to work constructively with the succeeding administration.<ref name=\"Rsnkptsopmafss\">{{cite news|title=SOMALIA: Nicholas Kay paid tribute today to Somalia\u2019s outgoing Prime Minister, Abdi Farah Shirdon Saaid|url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/12/somalia-nicholas-kay-paid-tribute-today-to-somalias-outgoing-prime-minister-abdi-farah-shirdon-saaid/|accessdate=2 December 2013|newspaper=Raxanreeb|date=2 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203011533/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2013/12/somalia-nicholas-kay-paid-tribute-today-to-somalias-outgoing-prime-minister-abdi-farah-shirdon-saaid/|archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref> On 12 December 2013, President Mohamud named [[Abdiweli Sheikh Ahmed]] as the new Prime Minister.<ref name=\"Msphmwbaasaatnp\">{{cite news|title=Somali President Hassan Mohamud will be appointing Abdiweli Sheikh Ahmed as the next PM|url=http://www.midnimo.com/2013/12/12/breaking-somali-president-hassan-mohamud-will-appointing-abdiweli-sheikh-ahmed-next-pm/|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=Midnimo|date=12 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Abdiweli Mohamed Ali]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Somalia]]|years=2012\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after={{nowrap|[[Abdiweli Sheikh Ahmed]]}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SomaliaPMs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shirdon, Abdi Farah}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Ethnic Somali people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Somalia]]\n[[Category:Somalian economists]]\n[[Category:Somali National University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdi_Farah_Shirdon"}
{"title_page": "J\u00fcrgen Sch\u00fctz", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = J\u00fcrgen Sch\u00fctz\n| fullname = \n| height = 1.78 m\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1939|7|1}}\n| birth_place = [[Dortmund]], [[Germany]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1995|3|19|1939|7|1}}\n| death_place = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1959\u20131963\n| years2 = 1963\u20131964\n| years3 = 1964\u20131965\n| years4 = 1965\u20131966\n| years5 = 1966\u20131967\n| years6 = 1967\u20131968\n| years7 = 1968\u20131969\n| years8 = 1969\u20131972\n| years9 = 1972\u20131973\n| clubs1 = [[Borussia Dortmund]]\n| clubs2 = [[A.S. Roma]]\n| clubs3 = [[F.C. Messina Peloro|Messina]]\n| clubs4 = [[Torino F.C.]]\n| clubs5 = A.S. Roma\n| clubs6 = [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]]\n| clubs7 = [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]]\n| clubs8 = Borussia Dortmund\n| clubs9 = [[Rot-Weiss L\u00fcdenscheid]]\n| caps1 = 85\n| caps2 = 15\n| caps3 = 6\n| caps4 = 14\n| caps5 = 6\n| caps6 = 20\n| caps7 = 20\n| caps8 = 73\n| goals1 = 103\n| goals2 = 5\n| goals3 = 2\n| goals4 = 3\n| goals5 = 1\n| goals6 = 3\n| goals7 = 6\n| goals8 = 30\n| nationalyears1 = 1960\u20131963\n| nationalyears2 = 1962\u20131963\n| nationalteam1 = [[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| pcupdate = 14:34, 23 February 2009 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''J\u00fcrgen Sch\u00fctz''' (1 July 1939 \u2013 19 March 1995) was a [[Germany|German]] football player from [[Dortmund]], Germany; he died of [[laryngeal cancer]]. He spent 4 seasons in the [[Fu\u00dfball-Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] with [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]] and [[Borussia Dortmund]]. Sch\u00fctz also  represented [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in 6 friendlies.\n\n==Honours==\n* [[DFB-Pokal]] finalist: 1963.\n* [[Bundesliga]] Winner: 1963.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Fussballdaten|schuetzjuergen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schutz, Jurgen}}\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany international footballers]]\n[[Category:Borussia Dortmund players]]\n[[Category:A.S. Roma players]]\n[[Category:A.C.R. Messina players]]\n[[Category:Torino F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brescia Calcio players]]\n[[Category:TSV 1860 Munich players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:German expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Dortmund]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Footballers from North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n\n\n{{germany-footy-midfielder-1930s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = J\u00fcrgen Sch\u00fctz\n| fullname = \n| height = 1.78 m\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1939|7|1}}\n| birth_place = [[Dortmund]], [[Germany]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1995|3|19|1939|7|1}}\n| death_place = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1959\u20131963\n| years2 = 1963\u20131964\n| years3 = 1964\u20131965\n| years4 = 1965\u20131966\n| years5 = 1966\u20131967\n| years6 = 1967\u20131968\n| years7 = 1968\u20131969\n| years8 = 1969\u20131972\n| years9 = 1972\u20131973\n| clubs1 = [[Borussia Dortmund]]\n| clubs2 = [[A.S. Roma]]\n| clubs3 = [[F.C. Messina Peloro|Messina]]\n| clubs4 = [[Torino F.C.]]\n| clubs5 = A.S. Roma\n| clubs6 = [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]]\n| clubs7 = [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]]\n| clubs8 = Borussia Dortmund\n| clubs9 = [[Rot-Weiss L\u00fcdenscheid]]\n| caps1 = 85\n| caps2 = 15\n| caps3 = 6\n| caps4 = 14\n| caps5 = 6\n| caps6 = 20\n| caps7 = 20\n| caps8 = 73\n| goals1 = 103\n| goals2 = 5\n| goals3 = 2\n| goals4 = 3\n| goals5 = 1\n| goals6 = 3\n| goals7 = 6\n| goals8 = 30\n| nationalyears1 = 1960\u20131963\n| nationalyears2 = 1962\u20131963\n| nationalteam1 = [[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| pcupdate = 14:34, 23 February 2009 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''J\u00fcrgen Sch\u00fctz''' (July 1, 1939 \u2013 March 19, 1995) was a [[Germany|German]] football player from [[Dortmund]], Germany; he died of [[laryngeal cancer]]. He spent 4 seasons in the [[Fu\u00dfball-Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] with [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]] and [[Borussia Dortmund]]. Sch\u00fctz also  represented [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in 6 friendlies.\n\n==Honours==\n* [[DFB-Pokal]] finalist: 1963.\n* [[Bundesliga]] Winner: 1963.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Fussballdaten|schuetzjuergen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schutz, Jurgen}}\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany international footballers]]\n[[Category:Borussia Dortmund players]]\n[[Category:A.S. Roma players]]\n[[Category:A.C.R. Messina players]]\n[[Category:Torino F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brescia Calcio players]]\n[[Category:TSV 1860 Munich players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:German expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Dortmund]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Footballers from North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n\n\n{{germany-footy-midfielder-1930s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "S.A. Julio", "label": "safe", "comment": "cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%BCrgen_Sch%C3%BCtz"}
{"title_page": "Aaron Farrugia", "text_new": "{{short description|Minister for the Environment, Climate Change & Planning}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[Member of the Maltese Parliament|MP]]\n| name             = Aaron Farrugia\n| office           = Member of the [[Maltese Parliament]] [[Parliament)|Malta]]\n| image            = Aaron Farrugia.jpg\n| caption          = \n| constituency_MP  = \n| office2          = Minister for the Environment, Climate Change & Planning\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1980|1|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[St. Julians]]\n| party            = [[Labour Party (Malta)]] (national)<br>[[Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats|Socialists & Democrats]] (European)\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Malta]]\n| website          = {{url|aaronfarrugia.com}}\n| signature        = \n}}\n\n'''Aaron Farrugia''' (born 1 January 1980) is a [[Malta|Maltese]] Partit Laburista (Labour Party) politician and the Minister for the Environment, Climate Change & Planning in Prime Minister Robert Abela\u2019s cabinet in early 2020, and served as Parliamentary Secretary for European Funds and Social Dialogue in former Prime Minister Joseph Muscat\u2019s cabinet.\n\nHe was elected as a member of the Parliament of Malta in June 2017, is a member of the Cabinet of the Government of Malta, member of the Foreign Affairs Committee, and Head of the Maltese Delegation in the Parliamentary Assembly for the Mediterranean.\n\nAs an economist, Farrugia worked as an Advisor to the Maltese Delegation in the Committee of the Regions and later on as the Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of the [[Malta Freeport]] Corporation\n\nFarrugia served in a number of positions in the Labour Party, mainly as an elected member of the Administrative Council and National Executive Committee of the Malta Labour Party and founder of the Labour Party think-tank Fondazzjoni IDEAT.\n\n== Biography==\n=== Studies and personal life===\n\nFarrugia obtained a B.A. with Honours in Finance at the [[University of Malta]] in 2002<ref>Thesis title: ''Foreign Direct Investment in Malta \u2013 A Review of Measures of Attraction and Problems in Implementation''</ref> and a M.A. in European Politics, Economics and Law at the same university in 2005.<ref>Thesis title: ''Welfare Policy Reforms in Contemporary Europe: The Ideological Shift in the European Social Democrat Parties''</ref> He then read for a Doctorate of Laws degree and graduated in 2017 with a dotoral thesis on direct democracy.<ref>Thesis title: ''Enhancing civic engagement: the Growing use of Direct Democracy in Malta and other relevant countries''</ref><ref name=linkedin>[https://www.linkedin.com/in/aaronfarrugia/ Linkedin]</ref>\n\nAaron Farrugia is a visiting lecturer at the Faculty of Economics, Management and Accountancy of the University of Malta. He teaches Politics, Political Campaigning, Policies and Governance.\n\nAaron Farrugia is married since 2010 to Charmaine Farrugia (n\u00e9e Micallef). They have two daughters, Petra, born in 2012 and Angelica, born in 2018.\n\n=== Political career ===\n\nDuring his student days Farrugia was a member and Secretary General of  ''Pulse'',<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090205121741/http://pulse.org.mt/ Pulse]</ref> a social democrat student organisation from 1998 to 2002, and later Financial Secretary of the Maltese National Youth Council between 2004 and 2005.\n\nFarrugia then joined the Labour Party and served as Vice President (2000-2001) and then as President of the Labour Youth Forum (Forum Zghazagh Laburisti) between 2002\u20132004 and 2006\u20132008.\n\nIn 2005 Farrugia was elected as deputy mayor of the Ta\u2019 Xbiex Local Council. \nFarrugia assisted Joseph Muscat's Labour Party leadership bid in 2008. He was then elected as education secretary in the new Labour Party executive, and coordinated the compilation of the 2013 party manifesto, besides founding and chairing the party think tank, Fondazzjoni Ideat, between 2009 and 2011.\n\nAt the 2017 Maltese general election Farrugia was elected to Parliament from the 1st electoral district where he obtained 3,600 first count votes. Farrugia was immediately appointed Junior Minister for European Funds and Social Dialogue by the Maltese Prime Minister. Internationally linked, he is a member of the Cabinet of Ministers.\n\nFarrugia is currently serving as Minister for the Environment, Climate Change & Planning in Prime Minister Robert Abela\u2019s cabinet.\n\nFarrugia expressed support for a change towards a first past the post system, a separate list to increase the number of women in Parliament, and for higher salaries for Members of Parliament.\n\n=== Memberships ===\nFarrugia is an Atlantic Forum Young Leader Alumnus (2011) and U.S. International Visitor Leadership Program's alumnus (2012); on the occasion, he spent four weeks with the 2012 Obama campaign. Farrugia is also a member of the Malta-United States Alumni Association (MUSAA). Friends of Europe listed him among the 40under40 European Young Leaders in 2017.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Farrugia, Aaron}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Maltese people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Maltese Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Maltese economists]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (Malta) politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Minister for the Environment, Climate Change & Planning}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[Member of the Maltese Parliament|MP]]\n| name             = Aaron Farrugia\n| office           = Member of the [[Maltese Parliament]] [[Parliament)|Malta]]\n| image            = Aaron Farrugia.jpg\n| caption          = \n| constituency_MP  = \n| office2          = Minister for the Environment, Climate Change & Planning\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1980|1|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[St. Julians]]\n| party            = [[Labour Party (Malta)]] (national)<br>[[Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats|Socialists & Democrats]] (European)\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Malta]]\n| website          = {{url|aaronfarrugia.com}}\n| signature        = \n}}\n\n'''Aaron Farrugia''' (born 1 January 1980) is a [[Malta|Maltese]] Partit Laburista (Labour Party) politician and the Minister for the Environment, Climate Change & Planning in Prime Minister Robert Abela\u2019s cabinet in early 2020, and served as Parliamentary Secretary for European Funds and Social Dialogue in former Prime Minister Joseph Muscat\u2019s cabinet. \n\nHe was elected as a member of the Parliament of Malta in June 2017, is a member of the Cabinet of the Government of Malta, member of the Foreign Affairs Committee, and Head of the Maltese Delegation in the Parliamentary Assembly for the Mediterranean.\n\nAs an economist, Farrugia worked as an Advisor to the Maltese Delegation in the Committee of the Regions and later on as the Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of the [[Malta Freeport]] Corporation\n\nFarrugia served in a number of positions in the Labour Party, mainly as an elected member of the Administrative Council and National Executive Committee of the Malta Labour Party and founder of the Labour Party think-tank Fondazzjoni IDEAT.\n\n== Biography==\n=== Studies and personal life===\n\nFarrugia obtained a B.A. with Honours in Finance at the [[University of Malta]] in 2002<ref>Thesis title: ''Foreign Direct Investment in Malta \u2013 A Review of Measures of Attraction and Problems in Implementation''</ref> and a M.A. in European Politics, Economics and Law at the same university in 2005.<ref>Thesis title: ''Welfare Policy Reforms in Contemporary Europe: The Ideological Shift in the European Social Democrat Parties''</ref> He then read for a Doctorate of Laws degree and graduated in 2017 with a dotoral thesis on direct democracy.<ref>Thesis title: ''Enhancing civic engagement: the Growing use of Direct Democracy in Malta and other relevant countries''</ref><ref name=linkedin>[https://www.linkedin.com/in/aaronfarrugia/ Linkedin]</ref>\n\nAaron Farrugia is a visiting lecturer at the Faculty of Economics, Management and Accountancy of the University of Malta. He teaches Politics, Political Campaigning, Policies and Governance.\n\nAaron Farrugia is married since 2010 to Charmaine Farrugia (n\u00e9e Micallef). They have two daughters, Petra, born in 2012 and Angelica, born in 2018.\n\n=== Political career ===\n\nDuring his student days Farrugia was a member and Secretary General of  ''Pulse'',<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090205121741/http://pulse.org.mt/ Pulse]</ref> a social democrat student organisation from 1998 to 2002, and later Financial Secretary of the Maltese National Youth Council between 2004 and 2005.\n\nFarrugia then joined the Labour Party and served as Vice President (2000-2001) and then as President of the Labour Youth Forum (Forum Zghazagh Laburisti) between 2002\u20132004 and 2006\u20132008.\n\nIn 2005 Farrugia was elected as deputy mayor of the Ta\u2019 Xbiex Local Council. \nFarrugia assisted Joseph Muscat's Labour Party leadership bid in 2008. He was then elected as education secretary in the new Labour Party executive, and coordinated the compilation of the 2013 party manifesto, besides founding and chairing the party think tank, Fondazzjoni Ideat, between 2009 and 2011.\n\nAt the 2017 Maltese general election Farrugia was elected to Parliament from the 1st electoral district where he obtained 3,600 first count votes. Farrugia was immediately appointed Junior Minister for European Funds and Social Dialogue by the Maltese Prime Minister. Internationally linked, he is a member of the Cabinet of Ministers.\n\nFarrugia is currently serving as Minister for the Environment, Climate Change & Planning in Prime Minister Robert Abela\u2019s cabinet.\n\nFarrugia expressed support for a change towards a first past the post system, a separate list to increase the number of women in Parliament, and for higher salaries for Members of Parliament.\n\n=== Memberships ===\nFarrugia is an Atlantic Forum Young Leader Alumnus (2011) and U.S. International Visitor Leadership Program's alumnus (2012); on the occasion, he spent four weeks with the 2012 Obama campaign. Farrugia is also a member of the Malta-United States Alumni Association (MUSAA). Friends of Europe listed him among the 40under40 European Young Leaders in 2017.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Farrugia, Aaron}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Maltese people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Maltese Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Maltese economists]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (Malta) politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aaron_Farrugia"}
{"title_page": "Casey Coleman (baseball)", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Casey Coleman\n|image=Casey Coleman on March 10, 2012.jpg\n|image_size=\n|caption=Coleman with the Chicago Cubs\n|position=[[Pitcher]]\n|team=Toros de Tijuana\n|number=35\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1987|7|3}}\n|birth_place=[[Fort Myers, Florida]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=August 2\n|debutyear=2010\n|debutteam=Chicago Cubs\n|statyear= 2014 season\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label= [[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value= 8\u201313\n|stat2label= [[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value= 5.72\n|stat3label= [[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value= 123\n|teams=\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2012}})\n* [[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|2014}})\n}}\n'''Joseph Casey Coleman''' (born July 3, 1987) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[pitcher]] for the [[Toros de Tijuana]] of the [[Mexican League]]. He has played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) for the [[Chicago Cubs]] and the [[Kansas City Royals]].\n\n{{MedalTableTop|name=no}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[Baseball at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Men's tournament|2015 Toronto]] | Team }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[2015 WBSC Premier12]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2015 WBSC Premier12|2015 Tokyo]] | Team }}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n==Early life==\nColeman was born in [[Fort Myers, Florida]], and graduated from [[Mariner High School (Cape Coral, Florida)|Mariner High School]] in [[Cape Coral, Florida]]. He played college baseball at [[Florida Gulf Coast University]] (FGCU) for the [[Florida Gulf Coast Eagles baseball]] team.  At FGCU, Coleman was teammates with future major league pitchers [[Richard Bleier]] and [[Chris Sale]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=colemca01| title= Casey Coleman Stats |publisher= Baseball Almanac |accessdate= November 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/?key_school=0c9895fa&exact=1&query_type=key_school|title=MLB Amateur Draft Picks who came from|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Chicago Cubs===\nColeman was drafted by the Cubs in the 15th round (461st overall) of the [[2008 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/c/colemca01.shtml| title =Casey Coleman\n| publisher= Baseball-Reference.Com|accessdate= November 26, 2012}}</ref> He was called up to the majors for the first time on August 2, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=5431907|title=Cubs recall pitcher Coleman from Iowa|date=2 August 2010|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Coleman earned his first major league win on August 23, 2010 on a 9\u20131 victory against the [[Washington Nationals]]. He also recorded his first RBI in the same game.\n\nIn 2011, Coleman did not make the team out of Spring Training and was optioned to Triple-A Iowa. After injuries to starting pitchers [[Andrew Cashner]] and [[Randy Wells]], he was recalled to Chicago and made his first start of the season on April 10 against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]].\n\nOn May 28, 2011, Coleman was optioned to the [[Iowa Cubs]], Chicago's Triple-A affiliate after [[Randy Wells]] was activated from the 15-day disabled list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cubbiescrib.com/2011/05/27/casey-coleman-optioned-to-iowa|title=Casey Coleman Optioned to Iowa|last=Campbell|first=Jordan|date=2011-05-27|work=Cubbies Crib|accessdate=2011-05-28}}</ref> He was recalled to minors after 2012 Season.\n\n===Kansas City Royals===\nColeman signed a minor league deal with the [[Kansas City Royals]] in April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=MLB: Ex-FGCU pitcher Casey Coleman sent to minors by Royals|url=http://www.naplesnews.com/tablet-showcase/top-sports/mlb-ex-fgcu-pitcher-casey-coleman-sent-to-minors|accessdate=December 16, 2014|work=Naples Daily News|date=May 27, 2014}}</ref> On December 15, 2014, Coleman was designated for assignment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Royals sign right-hander Pino, designate Coleman|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=12034081|accessdate=December 16, 2014|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=December 15, 2014}}</ref> He was outrighted to Triple-A on December 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2014/12/minor-moves-sierra-coleman-albers.html|title=Minor Moves: Mijares, Bowden, Runzler|last=Polishuk|first=Mark|work=mlbtraderumors.com|date=December 24, 2014|accessdate=December 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Seattle Mariners===\nColeman signed a minor league deal with the [[Seattle Mariners]] in December 2015. He opted out of his contract on July 2, 2016.\n\n===Tampa Bay Rays===\nOn July 8, 2016, Coleman signed a minor league contract with the [[Tampa Bay Rays]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/baseball/news/rays-casey-coleman-rays-sign-coleman/|title=Rays' Casey Coleman: Rays sign Coleman|work=cbssports.com|date=July 8, 2016|accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===New Britain Bees===\nOn April 7, 2017, Coleman signed with the [[New Britain Bees]] of the [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]].\n\n===Houston Astros===\nOn May 1, 2017, Coleman signed a minor league deal with the [[Houston Astros]]. He was released on July 6, 2017.\n\n===Return to Bees===\nOn July 24, 2017, Coleman resigned with the [[New Britain Bees]] of the [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]]. He became a free agent after the 2017 season.\n\n===Sugar Land Skeeters===\nOn May 26, 2018, Coleman signed with the [[Sugar Land Skeeters]] of the [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]]. In 7 games and 6 starts he was 3-0 with a 0.96 ERA and with a 38/10 K/BB ratio.\n\n===Return to the Chicago Cubs===\nOn July 3, 2018, Coleman's contract was purchased by the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TommyBirch/status/1013956099672666113|title=Tommy Birch on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> In 10 games and 5 starts he was 2-4 with a 6.91 ERA and with a 23/10 K/BB ratio. He elected free agency on November 3, 2018.\n\n===New York Mets===\nOn January 3, 2019, Coleman signed a minor league deal with the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ByRobertMurray/status/1080978465019572225|title=Robert Murray on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> He was assigned to AAA [[Syracuse Mets]]. Coleman was released by the organization on July 4, 2019. \n\n===Toros de Tijuana===\nOn July 23, 2019, Coleman signed with the [[Toros de Tijuana]] of the [[Mexican League]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBoth his father and grandfather were pitchers in the major leagues, making them the fourth family with three generations of major leaguers. His father, [[Joe Coleman (1970s pitcher)|Joe]], played from 1965 to 1979, and his grandfather, also named [[Joe Coleman (1950s pitcher)|Joe]], played from 1942 to 1955.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobreakingsports.com/2010/08/cubs-call-coleman-up-from-iowa.html|title=Chicago Breaking Sports News - Chicago Tribune|website=www.chicagobreakingsports.com}}</ref> He is also the first third-generation pitcher in Major League history.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Muskat|first1=Carrie|title=Cubs summon rookies Diamond, Coleman|url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/12935090/|accessdate=August 29, 2015|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n*[[List of second generation MLB players#Three-generation families|Third-generation Major League Baseball families]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n \n{{Baseballstats |mlb=488787 |espn=30947|br=c/colemca01|fangraphs=8270|brm=colema001cas}}\n* [http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=colemca01 Baseball Almanac]\n*{{Twitter}}\n{{United States roster 2015 WBSC Premier12}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coleman, Casey}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Fort Myers, Florida]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Florida]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 2015 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals players]]\n[[Category:Florida Gulf Coast Eagles baseball players]]\n[[Category:Boise Hawks players]]\n[[Category:Peoria Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Daytona Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Smokies players]]\n[[Category:Iowa Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Omaha Storm Chasers players]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Rainiers players]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:New Britain Bees players]]\n[[Category:Tomateros de Culiac\u00e1n players]]\n[[Category:Sugar Land Skeeters players]]\n[[Category:Syracuse Mets players]]\n[[Category:Caribbean Series players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate baseball players in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Toros de Tijuana players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Casey Coleman\n|image=Casey Coleman on March 10, 2012.jpg\n|image_size=\n|caption=Coleman with the Chicago Cubs\n|position=[[Pitcher]]\n|team=Toros de Tijuana\n|number=35\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1987|7|3}}\n|birth_place=[[Fort Myers, Florida]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=August 2\n|debutyear=2010\n|debutteam=Chicago Cubs\n|statyear= 2014 season\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label= [[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value= 8\u201313\n|stat2label= [[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value= 5.72\n|stat3label= [[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value= 123\n|teams=\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2012}})\n* [[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|2014}})\n}}\n'''Joseph Casey Coleman''' (born July 3, 1987) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[pitcher]] for the [[Toros de Tijuana]] of the [[Mexican League]]. He has played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) for the [[Chicago Cubs]] and [[Kansas City Royals]].\n\n{{MedalTableTop|name=no}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[Baseball at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Men's tournament|2015 Toronto]] | Team }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[2015 WBSC Premier12]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2015 WBSC Premier12|2015 Tokyo]] | Team }}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n==Early life==\nColeman was born in [[Fort Myers, Florida]], and graduated from [[Mariner High School (Cape Coral, Florida)|Mariner High School]] in [[Cape Coral, Florida]]. He played college baseball at [[Florida Gulf Coast University]] (FGCU) for the [[Florida Gulf Coast Eagles baseball]] team.  At FGCU, Coleman was teammates with future major league pitchers [[Richard Bleier]] and [[Chris Sale]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=colemca01| title= Casey Coleman Stats |publisher= Baseball Almanac |accessdate= November 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/?key_school=0c9895fa&exact=1&query_type=key_school|title=MLB Amateur Draft Picks who came from|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Chicago Cubs===\nColeman was drafted by the Cubs in the 15th round (461st overall) of the [[2008 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/c/colemca01.shtml| title =Casey Coleman\n| publisher= Baseball-Reference.Com|accessdate= November 26, 2012}}</ref> He was called up to the majors for the first time on August 2, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/news/story?id=5431907|title=Cubs recall pitcher Coleman from Iowa|date=2 August 2010|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Coleman earned his first major league win on August 23, 2010 on a 9\u20131 victory against the [[Washington Nationals]]. He also recorded his first RBI in the same game.\n\nIn 2011, Coleman did not make the team out of Spring Training and was optioned to Triple-A Iowa. After injuries to starting pitchers [[Andrew Cashner]] and [[Randy Wells]], he was recalled to Chicago and made his first start of the season on April 10 against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]].\n\nOn May 28, 2011, Coleman was optioned to the [[Iowa Cubs]], Chicago's Triple-A affiliate after [[Randy Wells]] was activated from the 15-day disabled list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cubbiescrib.com/2011/05/27/casey-coleman-optioned-to-iowa|title=Casey Coleman Optioned to Iowa|last=Campbell|first=Jordan|date=2011-05-27|work=Cubbies Crib|accessdate=2011-05-28}}</ref> He was recalled to minors after 2012 Season.\n\n===Kansas City Royals===\nColeman signed a minor league deal with the [[Kansas City Royals]] in April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=MLB: Ex-FGCU pitcher Casey Coleman sent to minors by Royals|url=http://www.naplesnews.com/tablet-showcase/top-sports/mlb-ex-fgcu-pitcher-casey-coleman-sent-to-minors|accessdate=December 16, 2014|work=Naples Daily News|date=May 27, 2014}}</ref> On December 15, 2014, Coleman was designated for assignment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Royals sign right-hander Pino, designate Coleman|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=12034081|accessdate=December 16, 2014|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=December 15, 2014}}</ref> He was outrighted to Triple-A on December 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2014/12/minor-moves-sierra-coleman-albers.html|title=Minor Moves: Mijares, Bowden, Runzler|last=Polishuk|first=Mark|work=mlbtraderumors.com|date=December 24, 2014|accessdate=December 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Seattle Mariners===\nColeman signed a minor league deal with the [[Seattle Mariners]] in December 2015. He opted out of his contract on July 2, 2016.\n\n===Tampa Bay Rays===\nOn July 8, 2016, Coleman signed a minor league contract with the [[Tampa Bay Rays]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/baseball/news/rays-casey-coleman-rays-sign-coleman/|title=Rays' Casey Coleman: Rays sign Coleman|work=cbssports.com|date=July 8, 2016|accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===New Britain Bees===\nOn April 7, 2017, Coleman signed with the [[New Britain Bees]] of the [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]].\n\n===Houston Astros===\nOn May 1, 2017, Coleman signed a minor league deal with the [[Houston Astros]]. He was released on July 6, 2017.\n\n===Return to Bees===\nOn July 24, 2017, Coleman resigned with the [[New Britain Bees]] of the [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]]. He became a free agent after the 2017 season.\n\n===Sugar Land Skeeters===\nOn May 26, 2018, Coleman signed with the [[Sugar Land Skeeters]] of the [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]]. In 7 games and 6 starts he was 3-0 with a 0.96 ERA and with a 38/10 K/BB ratio.\n\n===Return to the Chicago Cubs===\nOn July 3, 2018, Coleman's contract was purchased by the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TommyBirch/status/1013956099672666113|title=Tommy Birch on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> In 10 games and 5 starts he was 2-4 with a 6.91 ERA and with a 23/10 K/BB ratio. He elected free agency on November 3, 2018.\n\n===New York Mets===\nOn January 3, 2019, Coleman signed a minor league deal with the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ByRobertMurray/status/1080978465019572225|title=Robert Murray on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> He was assigned to AAA [[Syracuse Mets]]. Coleman was released by the organization on July 4, 2019. \n\n===Toros de Tijuana===\nOn July 23, 2019, Coleman signed with the [[Toros de Tijuana]] of the [[Mexican League]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBoth his father and grandfather were pitchers in the major leagues, making them the fourth family with three generations of major leaguers. His father, [[Joe Coleman (1970s pitcher)|Joe]], played from 1965 to 1979, and his grandfather, also named [[Joe Coleman (1950s pitcher)|Joe]], played from 1942 to 1955.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobreakingsports.com/2010/08/cubs-call-coleman-up-from-iowa.html|title=Chicago Breaking Sports News - Chicago Tribune|website=www.chicagobreakingsports.com}}</ref> He is also the first third-generation pitcher in Major League history.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Muskat|first1=Carrie|title=Cubs summon rookies Diamond, Coleman|url=http://m.cubs.mlb.com/news/article/12935090/|accessdate=August 29, 2015|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n*[[List of second generation MLB players#Three-generation families|Third-generation Major League Baseball families]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n \n{{Baseballstats |mlb=488787 |espn=30947|br=c/colemca01|fangraphs=8270|brm=colema001cas}}\n* [http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=colemca01 Baseball Almanac]\n*{{Twitter}}\n{{United States roster 2015 WBSC Premier12}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coleman, Casey}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Fort Myers, Florida]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Florida]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 2015 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals players]]\n[[Category:Florida Gulf Coast Eagles baseball players]]\n[[Category:Boise Hawks players]]\n[[Category:Peoria Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Daytona Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Smokies players]]\n[[Category:Iowa Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Omaha Storm Chasers players]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Rainiers players]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:New Britain Bees players]]\n[[Category:Tomateros de Culiac\u00e1n players]]\n[[Category:Sugar Land Skeeters players]]\n[[Category:Syracuse Mets players]]\n[[Category:Caribbean Series players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate baseball players in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Toros de Tijuana players]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casey_Coleman_(baseball)"}
{"title_page": "Aanund Hylland", "text_new": "{{short description|Norwegian economist}}\n'''Aanund Hylland''' (born 19 October 1949) is a Norwegian economist.\n\nHe took a master's degree in [[mathematical logic]] at the [[University of Oslo]] in 1974, and the Ph.D. at the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]], [[Harvard University]] in 1980. He worked at the University of Oslo and [[BI Norwegian Business School]] from 1983, and in 1991 he was promoted to professor at the University of Oslo. He was the [[dean (education)|dean]] of the Faculty of Social Sciences from 1996 to 1998.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jubilanter|date=19 October 1999|work=Aftenposten|page=14|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnva.no/c26848/artikkel/vis.html?tid=27644|title=Gruppe 7: Samfunnsfag (herunder sosiologi, statsvitenskap og \u00f8konomi)|publisher=[[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=12 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927170048/http://www.dnva.no/c26848/artikkel/vis.html?tid=27644|archive-date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was the vice chairman of the board of the [[Norwegian Institute for Social Research]] from 2005 to 2008, and was re-elected for the term 2009 to 2012.<ref>[http://www.socialresearch.no/About-ISF/Board Board] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130000603/http://www.socialresearch.no/About-ISF/Board |date=2011-01-30 }} &ndash; Norwegian Institute for Social Research</ref><ref>[http://www.samfunnsforskning.no/nor/ISF/Styret-ved-ISF Styret ved ISF] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101102163304/http://www.samfunnsforskning.no/nor/ISF/Styret-ved-ISF |date=2010-11-02 }} &ndash; Norwegian Institute for Social Research {{in lang|no}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box |before=[[Tore Hansen (political scientist)|Tore Hansen]] |title=[[dean (education)|Dean]] of the Faculty of Social Sciences, [[University of Oslo]] |years=1996&ndash;1998 |after=[[Marit Melhuus]] }}\n{{end box}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hylland, Aanund}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian economists]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo faculty]]\n[[Category:Norwegian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Members of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n\n\n{{Norway-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Norwegian economist}}\n'''Aanund Hylland''' (born 19 October 1949) is a Norwegian economist.\n\nHe took a master's degree in [[mathematical logic]] at the [[University of Oslo]] in 1974, and the Ph.D. at the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]], [[Harvard University]] in 1980. He worked at the University of Oslo and [[BI Norwegian Business School]] from 1983, and in 1991 he was promoted to professor at the University of Oslo. He was the [[dean (education)|dean]] of the Faculty of Social Sciences from 1996 to 1998.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jubilanter|date=19 October 1999|work=Aftenposten|page=14|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnva.no/c26848/artikkel/vis.html?tid=27644|title=Gruppe 7: Samfunnsfag (herunder sosiologi, statsvitenskap og \u00f8konomi)|publisher=[[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=12 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927170048/http://www.dnva.no/c26848/artikkel/vis.html?tid=27644|archive-date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was the vice chairman of the board of the [[Norwegian Institute for Social Research]] from 2005 to 2008, and was re-elected for the term 2009 to 2012.<ref>[http://www.socialresearch.no/About-ISF/Board Board] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130000603/http://www.socialresearch.no/About-ISF/Board |date=2011-01-30 }} &ndash; Norwegian Institute for Social Research</ref><ref>[http://www.samfunnsforskning.no/nor/ISF/Styret-ved-ISF Styret ved ISF] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101102163304/http://www.samfunnsforskning.no/nor/ISF/Styret-ved-ISF |date=2010-11-02 }} &ndash; Norwegian Institute for Social Research {{in lang|no}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box |before=[[Tore Hansen (political scientist)|Tore Hansen]] |title=[[dean (education)|Dean]] of the Faculty of Social Sciences, [[University of Oslo]] |years=1996&ndash;1998 |after=[[Marit Melhuus]] }}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hylland, Aanund}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian economists]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo faculty]]\n[[Category:Norwegian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Members of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n\n{{Norway-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aanund_Hylland"}
{"title_page": "Victor Gonzalez (director)", "text_new": "{{short description|American television director}}\n{{Notability|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Victor Gonzalez\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| othername                 =\n| birth_date                = <!--{{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| birth_place               = \n| death_date                = \n| death_place               = \n| alma_mater                = \n| occupation                = Television director\n| years_active              = 1987\u2013present\n| spouse                    = \n}}\n\n'''Victor Gonzalez''' is an American [[television director]].\n\nHe began his career as [[camera operator]] on the sitcom ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]''. He continued to camera operate for many years on the sitcoms ''[[Roseanne (TV series)|Roseanne]]'', ''[[Married... with Children]]'', ''[[Home Improvement (TV series)|Home Improvement]]'', ''[[Reba (TV series)|Reba]]'' and ''[[That's So Raven]]''.\n\nHe made his directorial debut on the [[Telemundo]] sitcom ''[[Los Beltr\u00e1n]]'' in 2000. He then went on to direct episodes of ''[[Half & Half]]'', ''[[George Lopez (TV series)|George Lopez]]'', ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place]]'', ''[[Pair of Kings]]'', ''[[I'm in the Band]]'', ''[[A.N.T. Farm]]'', ''[[Rules of Engagement (TV series)|Rules of Engagement]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/victor-gonzalez/credits/276342 |title=Victor Gonzalez credits |publisher=[[TV Guide]].com |accessdate=August 23, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Lab Rats (U.S. TV series)|Lab Rats]]'', ''[[Level Up (U.S. TV series)|Level Up]]'', ''[[Kickin' It]]'', ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'', ''[[See Dad Run]]'', ''[[Wendell & Vinnie]]'', ''[[Instant Mom]]'', ''[[The Thundermans]]'', ''[[Mike & Molly]]'', ''[[Last Man Standing (U.S. TV series)|Last Man Standing]]'' and ''[[Man with a Plan (TV series)|Man with a Plan]]''. He has also directed ''[[The Wizards Return: Alex vs. Alex]]'', a special episode based on a Disney Channel series, ''Wizards of Waverly Place''.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Note(s)\n|-\n\n| 1987-89 || ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'' || rowspan=10|Camera Operator || 8 episodes \n|-\n| 1989-92 || ''[[Roseanne (TV series)|Roseanne]]'' || 72 episodes \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1990 || ''[[227 (TV series)|227]]'' || Episode: \"No Place Like Home\"\n|-\n| ''[[The Munsters Today]]'' || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1991 || ''[[Davis Rules]]'' || 4 episodes \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1993 || ''[[A Different World]]'' || Episode: \"Great X-Pectations\"\n|-\n| ''[[Thea (TV series)|Thea]]'' || Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1995 || ''[[Married... with Children]]'' || Episode: \"And Bingo Was Her Game-O\"\n|-\n| ''[[Simon (American TV series)|Simon]]'' || Episode: \"Watch This\"\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Home Improvement (TV series)|Home Improvement]]'' || Episode: \"The Longest Day\"\n|-\n| 1997-98 || ''[[Living Single]]'' || Associate Director || 7 episodes \n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Costello (TV series)|Costello]]'' || Technical Coordinator || 7 episodes\n|-\n| 1999-02 || ''[[For Your Family]]'' || Technical Coordinator/Director || 3 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2000 || ''[[Los Beltran]]'' || rowspan=2|Director || 4 episodes \n|-\n| ''Viva Vegas!'' ||\n|-\n| ''[[Rude Awakening (TV series)|Rude Awakening]]'' || Associate Director || Episode: \"Me, Myself and I\"\n|-\n| ''[[Spin City]]'' || Camera Operator || Episode: \"Balloons over Broadway\"\n|-\n| 2002-07 || ''[[George Lopez (TV series)|George Lopez]]'' || Technical Coordinator/Associate Director/Technical Director/Writer/Director || 60 episodes\n|-\n| 2002-03 || ''[[Reba (TV series)|Reba]]'' || rowspan=2|Camera Operator || 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2003-05 || ''[[That's So Raven]]'' || 25 episodes\n|-\n| 2003-04 || ''[[Like Family]]'' || Associate Director ||\n|-\n