{"title_page": "Florida Gulf Coast Eagles baseball", "text_new": "{{Infobox College baseball team\n|name = Florida Gulf Coast Eagles\n|logo = FGCU wordmark.png\n|logo_size = 200\n|founded = 2003\n|university = Florida Gulf Coast University\n|coach = [[Dave Tollett]]\n|tenure = 18th<!-- 2020 is 18th season, as 2003 was his first -->\n|conference = [[Atlantic Sun Conference]]\n|division =\n|location = [[Fort Myers, Florida]]\n|stadium = [[Swanson Stadium]]\n|capacity = 1,500\n|nickname = [[Florida Gulf Coast Eagles|Eagles]]\n|record = 599\u2013348\u20133\n|national_champion = \n|cws =\n|regional_champ =\n|ncaa_tourneys = 2006, 2007, 2017\n|conference_tournament = 2017\n|conference_champion = 2008, 2009, 2010, 2014, 2019\n}}\n\nThe '''Florida Gulf Coast Eagles baseball''' team represents [[Florida Gulf Coast University]] in the sport of [[baseball]]. The Eagles team competes in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) and the [[Atlantic Sun Conference]] (A-SUN). Florida Gulf Coast has fielded a baseball team since 2003 and, as of 2019, has an all-time record of 599\u2013348\u20133 (a {{Winning percentage|599|348|8}} winning percentage).<ref>[http://www.winsipedia.com/georgia-tech Georgia Tech winning history], accessed May 17, 2018</ref> The Eagles play in [[Swanson Stadium]] in [[Fort Myers, Florida]], which has a capacity of 1,500.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|url=https://fgcuathletics.com/index.aspx?path=baseball}}\n\n{{Atlantic Sun Conference baseball navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Florida Gulf Coast Eagles baseball| ]]\n[[Category:NCAA Division I baseball teams]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox College baseball team\n|name = Florida Gulf Coast Eagles\n|logo = FGCU wordmark.png\n|logo_size = 200\n|founded = 2003\n|university = Florida Gulf Coast University\n|coach = [[Dave Tollett]]\n|tenure = 18th<!-- 2020 is 18th season, as 2003 was his first -->\n|conference = [[Atlantic Sun Conference]]\n|division =\n|location = [[Fort Myers, Florida]]\n|stadium = [[Swanson Stadium]]\n|capacity = 1,500\n|nickname = [[Florida Gulf Coast Eagles|Eagles]]\n|record = 599\u2013348\u20133\n|national_champion = \n|cws =\n|regional_champ =\n|ncaa_tourneys = 2006, 2007, 2017\n|conference_tournament = 2017\n|conference_champion = 2008, 2009, 2010, 2014, 2019\n}}\n\nThe '''Florida Gulf Coast Eagles baseball''' team represents [[Florida Gulf Coast University]] in the sport of [[baseball]]. The Eagles team competes in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) and the [[Atlantic Sun Conference]] (A-SUN). Florida Gulf Coast has fielded a baseball team since 2003 and, as of 2019, has an all-time record of 599\u2013348-3 (a {{Winning percentage|599|348|8}} winning percentage).<ref>[http://www.winsipedia.com/georgia-tech Georgia Tech winning history], accessed May 17, 2018</ref> The Eagles play in [[Swanson Stadium]] in [[Fort Myers, Florida]], which has a capacity of 1,500.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|url=https://fgcuathletics.com/index.aspx?path=baseball}}\n\n{{Atlantic Sun Conference baseball navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Florida Gulf Coast Eagles baseball| ]]\n[[Category:NCAA Division I baseball teams]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "Punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florida_Gulf_Coast_Eagles_baseball"}
{"title_page": "Groom Mine", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Short description|Defunct mine in Lincoln County, Nevada}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox mine\n| name               = Groom Mine\n| image              = File:Wfm usgs groom map.png\n| width              =\n| caption            = [[United States Geological Survey]] map depicting the location of Groom Mine\n| pushpin_map        =\n| pushpin_mapsize    =\n| pushpin_map_alt    =\n| pushpin_map_caption=\n| pushpin_image      =\n| pushpin_label      =\n| pushpin_label_position =\n| coordinates        = {{Coord|37.3462|-115.7692|display=inline,title}}\n| place              =\n| subdivision_type   =\n| state/province     = [[Lincoln County, Nevada]]<ref name=\"Issue31\"/>\n| country            =\n| products           = Silver<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Bulletin of Nevada State Bureau of Mines|series=Geology and Mining Series, Issues 1-16|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bmc1AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA161|title=The Mineral Resources of Southern Nevada|last=Carpenter|first=Jay A.|year=1904|publisher=University of Nevada|page=161|oclc=1432631}}</ref>\n| amount             = <!--include units-->\n| financial year     =\n| type               = [[Open-pit mining|Open-pit]] & [[Adit|underground]]<ref>{{cite report |author=Donald Zona |date=October 1985 |title=Draft Environmental Impact Statement Groom Mountain Range |url=http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a226049.pdf |publisher=United States Air Force |pages=3\u201324 |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218092001/http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a226049.pdf |archivedate=18 February 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| greatest depth     = {{convert|210|ft|m}}<ref name=BoM1977 />\n| opening year       = {{Start date|1866}}<ref name=PippenReno1986>{{cite report |first=Lonnie C. |last=Pippen |first2=Ronald L. |last2=Reno |first3=Stephen R. |last3=Durand |date=August 1986 |title=Archaeological Reconnaissance: An Archaeological Reconnaissance of the Groom Range Lincoln County, Nevada |url=https://archive.org/stream/archaeologicalrereno/archaeologicalrereno_djvu.txt |publisher=Desert Research Institute |page=62 |quote=A crude smelter may have been on the Groom Mine property in 1866 (Averett 1963:49). |access-date=9 February 2019 }}</ref>\n| active years       = 1872<ref name=\"District1989-162\"/>\u20131954<ref name=December2016Fox />\n| closing year       = {{End date|2015}}<ref name=SEP2015KLAS>{{cite news |last=Meek |first=Glen |date=16 September 2015 |title=Government takes family's land near Area 51 |url=http://www.lasvegasnow.com/news/government-takes-familys-land-near-area-51/249903883 |work=[[KLAS-TV]] |location=Las Vegas |access-date=10 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310175220/http://www.lasvegasnow.com/news/government-takes-familys-land-near-area-51/249903883 |archive-date=10 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| owner              = [[United States Government]]<ref name=SEP2015KLAS />\n| official website   = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| acquisition year   = 2015<ref name=SEP2015KLAS />\n| module             = <!-- or 'embedded' or 'nrhp' -->\n}}\n\n'''Groom Mine''', located in [[Lincoln County, Nevada]], first opened in the 1870s.<ref name=December2016Fox />  Most mining in the area, mostly of [[silver chloride]] ores, had finished by 1874.<ref name=\"District1989-162\"/> Groom Mine continued to operate, finally ceasing operations in 1954.<ref name=December2016Fox /> By 1956, official recordings of products of the Groom Mining District, which includes Groom Mine, shows that [[lead]] was the bulk of minerals harvested, which also included {{convert|145,000|ozt|kg}} of [[silver]] and about {{convert|45|ozt|kg}} of [[gold]].<ref>{{cite book|title=OF1998-01: Mineral and energy resource assessment of the Nellis Air Force Range|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N10nIMy-v1AC&pg=SA7-PA136|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|page=136|id=GGKEY:0JR4J3LY7P1|date=1998}}</ref> During [[World War II]], Groom Mine became surrounded by military activity, which continued into the 21st century.<ref name=FA2015 /> In the 1950s, the mine was exposed to fallout from nuclear testing that was being carried out at the [[Nevada Test Site]].<ref name=FA2015 /> During the late 20th century, military activities, including the destruction of a mill and the restriction of access to the mine, continued to affect work there.<ref name=Savage2014 /> The United States Government seized the mine under [[Eminent domain in the United States|eminent domain]] from its previous owners in 2015.<ref name=SEP2015KLAS /> Just compensation is under dispute in United States District Court, District of Nevada (Las Vegas), Judge [[Miranda Du]] presiding.\n\n==Background==\nThe rocks in the range date back to the [[Paleozoic]] era; the site is also covered by [[Tertiary]] rocks on its east and north sides.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Nevada Bureau of Mines and Geology|author2=J. V. Tingley|title=OF1984-01: A Mineral Inventory of the Caliente Resource Area, Caliente District, Lincoln County, Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yhDB8-dWv0kC&pg=PA28|year=1984|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|page=28|id=GGKEY:7TSA0GECEY0|oclc=32899352}}</ref> Prior to European exploration, the region was inhabited by [[Southern Paiute]] Native Americans.<ref name=Paine1996>{{cite journal |last1=Paine |first1=Gary |date=Spring 1996 |title=A Mine, the Military, and a Dry Lake: National Security and the Groom District, Lincoln County, Nevada |url=http://epubs.nsla.nv.gov/statepubs/epubs/210777-1996-1Spring.pdf |journal=Nevada Historical Society Quarterly |volume=39 |issue=1 |pages=20\u201342 |access-date=14 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230134150/http://epubs.nsla.nv.gov/statepubs/epubs/210777-1996-1Spring.pdf |archive-date=30 December 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all |ISSN=0047-9462}}</ref> Following the discovery of minerals in the [[Comstock Lode]] in 1859, prospecting of other areas in Nevada began.<ref name=\"NBMG1998-7\">{{cite book|title=OF1998-01: Mineral and energy resource assessment of the Nellis Air Force Range|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N10nIMy-v1AC&pg=SA7-PA1|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|page=7|id=GGKEY:0JR4J3LY7P1|date=1998}}</ref><ref name=\"NBMG1998-7\" /><ref>{{cite book|author=Joseph V. Tingley|title=SP019: Geologic and Natural History Tours in the Reno Area|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekf0wBY8LyUC&pg=PA54|year=2005|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|isbn=978-1-888035-09-4|page=54}}<br />{{cite web |url=https://www.gbcnv.edu/howh/MannyPenrod.html |title=What Happened to Manny? |last=Hickson |first=Howard |date=2003 |website=Howard Hickson's Histories |publisher=Great Basin College |access-date=9 February 2019 |quote=}}</ref> Mining in the area began in the late 1860s, after minerals were discovered in the [[Groom Range]] in 1864.<ref name=\"District1989-162\">{{cite report  |author1=Resource Specialists and Management Staff within the Caliente Resource Area |author2=554th Range Group Staff, Nellis Air Force Base |author3=Nevada State offices, Bureau of Land Management |date=24 May 1989 |title=Draft: Nellis Air Force Range Resource Plan and Environmental Impact STatement |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O9lNdtXGGLYC&pg=PP162 |publisher=Bureau of Land Management, Las Vegas District |page=162|oclc=1042984858}}</ref> A mining district to organize claims, called Groom District, was formed in 1869.<ref name=\"NBMG1998-7\" /> In 1871, the area was documented in the [[Wheeler Survey]].<ref name=Paine1996 />\n\n==History==\n===Mining===\nHuman habitation at the Groom Mine site may have begun as early as 1866.<ref name=PippenReno1986 /> A [[Land patent|patent]] for the Groom Mine was issued in 1872 and in 1885, the Sheahan family acquired the property.<ref name=\"District1989-162\"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Jack G. Quade|title=OF1986-09: Mineral Inventory and Geochemical Survey, Groom Mountain Range, Lincoln County, Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=An2GexDluCsC&pg=PA8|year=1986|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|pages=8\u2013|id=GGKEY:XT9W6WCT82L|oclc=32899397}}</ref> The mine was three days' travel from [[Indian Springs, Nevada|Indian Springs]] and {{convert|5,250|ft|m}} above sea level, making it very isolated.<ref name=Paine1996 /> According to [[Nevada Bureau of Mines and Geology]] in 1998, the property claim, which is commonly referred to as Groom, is officially named \"Conception\".<ref>{{cite book|title=OF1998-01: Mineral and energy resource assessment of the Nellis Air Force Range|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N10nIMy-v1AC&pg=SL154-PA40|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|page=154|id=GGKEY:0JR4J3LY7P1|date=1998}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the Conception claim, other claims in Groom Distract were made and held by the Sheahan family.<ref name=Paine1996 /> From 1915 until 1917, the mine was leased to Tom McCormick, who worked the mine.<ref name=Paine1996 /> In September 1917, a miner from [[Austria-Hungary]] who was employed by Groom Mining Company died at the mine.<ref>{{cite book|author=Nevada. Legislature|title=Appendix to Journals of Senate and Assembly ... of the Legislature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8-BKAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA6-PA35|year=1919|pages=35\u201336}}</ref> In the mid-to-late 1910s the mine produced silver worth about $250,000.<ref>{{cite book|title=Geology and Mining Series|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bmc1AAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA121|year=1904|publisher=University of Nevada|page=121}}</ref> The shipping of mined products became difficult with the closing of the [[Las Vegas and Tonopah Railroad]] at the end of that decade,<ref>{{cite book|title=Intermountain Industry and Engineering: Official Publication: Utah Motor Transport Ass'n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hzs5AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA39|year=1920|publisher=The Association|page=39}}</ref> which caused the mine to become temporarily idle.<ref>{{cite book|title=Intermountain Industry and Engineering: Official Publication: Utah Motor Transport Ass'n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hzs5AQAAMAAJ&pg=RA13-PA34|year=1920|publisher=The Association|page=34}}</ref> By 1922, the mine had two shafts, the longest being {{Convert|200|ft|m|abbr=}} deep.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Mines Handbook: An Enlargement of the Copper Hand Book; a Manual of the Mining Industry of North America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Smw_AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1219|year=1922|publisher=Stevens Copper Handbook Company|page=1219}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Groom Lake Road.jpg|thumb|Groom Road, built by the Sheahan family and Lincoln County|alt=a dirt road leading off towards the horizon]]\nIn 1942, construction of a mill that used a [[Mineral processing|gravity and flotation]] method began;<ref name=Paine1996 /> a source later referred to this mill as a [[concentration mill]].<ref name=Savage2014 /> By 1951, four people were living at the mine and the concentration mill had been completed.<ref name=Savage2014>{{cite book|author=Rebecca Solnit|title=Savage Dreams: A Journey into the Hidden Wars of the American West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rjdOAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA34|date=6 June 2014|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-95792-3|page=34}}</ref> Ore from Groom Mine, from which lead and silver were extracted, was found to contain [[cerussite]] and [[galena]].<ref name=\"Issue31\">{{cite book|author1=Stephen B. Castor|author2=Gregory C. Ferdock|title=Minerals of Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=flAhr0MbxM8C&pg=PA139|year=2004|publisher=University of Nevada Press|isbn=978-0-87417-540-0|page=139}}</ref> Beginning in 1950, roads approaching the mine from the west were closed due to military activities, leading to the Sheahan family and Lincoln County to build a road from the east;<ref name=FA2015 /> this is referred to as Groom Road in a 1986 report.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jack G. Quade|title=OF1986-09: Mineral Inventory and Geochemical Survey, Groom Mountain Range, Lincoln County, Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=An2GexDluCsC&pg=PA2|year=1986|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|pages=2|id=GGKEY:XT9W6WCT82L|oclc=32899397}}</ref>  During the 1950s, mining operations paused due to nearby [[List of nuclear weapons tests of the United States|nuclear tests]].<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" /> In 1954, production from the mine ended due to the destruction of a mill at the mine.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Neill |first=Marine |date=17 September 2015 |title=US air force threatens to destroy property next door to Area 51 after owners refuse to sell |url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/real-estate/us-air-force-threatens-to-destroy-property-next-door-to-area-51-after-owners-refuse-to-sell/news-story/245501b0ac154be2f5ac379496b183df |work=News Corp Australia |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314180829/http://www.news.com.au/finance/real-estate/us-air-force-threatens-to-destroy-property-next-door-to-area-51-after-owners-refuse-to-sell/news-story/245501b0ac154be2f5ac379496b183df |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nUntil 1956, the mine product totaled almost a million dollars in several minerals, including copper, silver, and gold;<ref name=\"District1989-162\"/> In 1977, the [[United States Bureau of Mines]] valued the output of Groom mine products at $3.75 million.<ref name=BoM1977>{{cite report |author=John R. Norberg |date=12 August 1977 |title=Mineral Resources in the Vicinity of the Nellis Air Force Base and the Nellis Bombing and Gunnery Range, Clark, Lincoln, and Nye Counties, Nevada |url=https://www.nrc.gov/docs/ML0037/ML003742795.pdf |publisher=United States Department of the Interior |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314175613/https://www.nrc.gov/docs/ML0037/ML003742795.pdf |archivedate=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was the most productive mine in the Groom Mining District<ref name=\"District1989-162\"/> and had been worked on by three generations of the Sheahan family.<ref name=Paine1996 /> Based on [[Gold panning|panning]] samples near Groom Mine, the area may also contain deposits of [[antimony]], [[barium]], lead, mercury, and zinc.<ref>{{cite report  |author1=Resource Specialists and Management Staff within the Caliente Resource Area |author2=554th Range Group Staff, Nellis Air Force Base |author3=Nevada State offices, Bureau of Land Management |date=24 May 1989 |title=Draft: Nellis Air Force Range Resource Plan and Environmental Impact STatement |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O9lNdtXGGLYC&pg=PP165 |publisher=Bureau of Land Management, Las Vegas District |page=165 |oclc=1042984858}}</ref> By 1959, the Sheahan family moved away from the mine but visited their property regularly.<ref name=FA2015 /> In 1984, the Sheahan family, who still owned the Groom Mine, also had the legal rights to most of the other 22 patented mining claims nearby.<ref name=\"Aug1984UPI\">{{cite news |last=Chrystal |first=Chris |date=6 August 1984 |title=Air Force: 'We had no legal authority' |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/08/06/Air-Force-We-had-no-legal-authority/2948460612800/ |work=United Press International |access-date=8 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314175646/https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/08/06/Air-Force-We-had-no-legal-authority/2948460612800/ |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> According to the [[Nevada Bureau of Mines and Geology]], it was estimated in 1963 that there is {{convert|30,000|t|kg}} of material that can be mined at Groom Mine.<ref>{{cite report |first=John L. |last=Munteen |first2=David A. |last2=Davis |first3=Bridget |last3=Ayling |date=2017 |title=The Nevada Mineral Industry 2016 |url=http://epubs.nsla.nv.gov/statepubs/epubs/210988-2016.pdf |publisher=University of Nevada, Reno |page= |docket= |access-date=9 February 2019 |quote= |oclc=1061602920 }}</ref> A 1990 [[Bureau of Land Management]] report stated that due to restricted access to the mine, it would lead to \"potential loss of income through inability to expand or further develop the claims\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Spang|first=Edward F.|title=Caliente Resource Area, Nellis Air Force Range Resource Plan: Environmental Impact Statement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uwkzAQAAMAAJ&pg=SL8-PA8|year=1990|publisher=Bureau of Land Management|pages=H\u20138}}</ref> Until late 2015, the Sheahan family periodically blasted for minerals at the mine;<ref name=December2016Fox>{{cite news |last=Craft |first=Andrew |date=13 December 2016 |title=Family fights government in land dispute near Area 51 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/science/2016/12/13/family-fights-government-in-land-dispute-near-area-51.html |work=Fox News |location=New York City |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174249/http://www.foxnews.com/science/2016/12/13/family-fights-government-in-land-dispute-near-area-51.html |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> by this time the family had owned the mine for 130 years.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Huff |first=Steve |date=12 September 2015 |title=True American Takes Stand Against Mysterious Area 51 Expansion |url=https://www.maxim.com/maxim-man/mysterious-area-51-expansion-2015-9 |magazine=Maxim |location=New York City |publisher=Biglari Holdings |access-date=15 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315201948/https://www.maxim.com/maxim-man/mysterious-area-51-expansion-2015-9 |archive-date=15 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Military interaction===\nIn 1941, Groom Mine was visited by individuals who stayed at the mine with the Sheahan family while surveying the area for a gunnery and bombing range to be used during World War II.<ref name=FA2015 /> The outhouse and bunkhouse at the mine were accidentally [[strafed]] during the war by aircraft using the Las Vegas Bombing and Gunnery Range.<ref name=Paine1996 /> Beginning in the 1950s, Groom Mine began to be impacted by nuclear tests at the Nevada Test Site;<ref name=FA2015>{{cite web |url=https://foxtrotalpha.jalopnik.com/the-unlikely-struggle-of-the-family-whose-neighbor-is-a-1741346156 |title=The Unlikely Struggle Of The Family Whose Neighbor Is Area 51 |last=Rogoway |first=Tyler |date=9 November 2015 |website=Foxtrot Alpha |publisher=[[Gawker Media|Jalopnik]] |access-date=8 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315003622/https://foxtrotalpha.jalopnik.com/the-unlikely-struggle-of-the-family-whose-neighbor-is-a-1741346156 |archive-date=15 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Groom Mine was {{convert|38|mi|km}} away.<ref name=\"Titus2001\">{{cite book|author=A. Costandina Titus|title=Bombs in the Backyard: Atomic Testing and American Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQfG-U5iAPYC&pg=PA56|year=2001|publisher=University of Nevada Press|isbn=978-0-87417-370-3|page=56}}</ref> In 1951, the [[United States Atomic Energy Commission|Atomic Energy Commission]] informed the Sheahan family of the planned detonations and set up instrumentation at the mine.<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\">{{cite book|author=Phil Patton|title=Dreamland: Travels Inside the Secret World of Roswell and Area 51|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WM6IxZvr0E4C&pg=PT93|date=31 October 2012|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-82860-6|pages=93\u201397}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Susan Wright|title=UFO Headquarters: Investigations On Current Extraterrestrial Activity In Area 51|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=81xoS94LSncC&pg=PA7|date=15 August 1998|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-0-312-20781-6|page=7}}</ref> The instrumentation was monitored by an employee of the [[United States Public Health Service]], who lived at the mine along with the Sheahan family.<ref>{{cite book|author=Sarah Alisabeth Fox|title=Downwind: A People's History of the Nuclear West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OeMoDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA59|date=November 2014|publisher=U of Nebraska Press|isbn=978-0-8032-5537-1|pages=59\u201360}}</ref> The first mention of a nuclear tests impacting operations at Groom Mine was the [[Operation Tumbler\u2013Snapper]] Easy Test, which led to the mine being evacuated due to its proximity to the detonation.<ref name=\"Childers2015-p79\" /> Following the detonation, measurements of radiation at the mine reached 0.19 [[Roentgen (unit)|roentgen]] per hour.<ref>{{cite book|author=Barton C. Hacker|title=Elements of Controversy: The Atomic Energy Commission and Radiation Safety in Nuclear Weapons Testing, 1947-1974|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uKp3ridsHrYC&pg=PA80|date=1 January 1994|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-08323-3|page=80}}</ref> It caused some structural damage, breaking the front door of the Sheahan's home.<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" /> Further away, [[nuclear fallout|fallout]] impacted nearby [[Tempiute, Nevada|Tempiute]].<ref name=\"Childers2015-p79\">{{cite book|author=Leisl Carr Childers|title=The Size of the Risk: Histories of Multiple Use in the Great Basin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mRAqCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA79|date=9 October 2015|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-5253-0|pages=79\u201380}}</ref> Returning to the mine had to be done using a different route; the normal route was too radioactive to travel on.<ref>{{cite book|author=Philip L. Fradkin|title=Fallout: An American Nuclear Tragedy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Clrz_0sJZrQC&pg=PA101|date=March 2004|publisher=Big Earth Publishing|isbn=978-1-55566-331-5|page=101}}</ref> The following Fox test in late May 1952 led to fallout falling on the mine;<ref name=\"Childers2015-p79\"/> the highest-recorded radiation was 0.32 roentgen per hour.<ref>{{cite report |first=Jean |last=Ponton |first2=Carl |last2=Maag |date=16 June 1982 |title=Shots Easy, Fox, Grace and How: The Final Tests of the Tumbler-Snapper Series 7 May - 5 June 1952 |url=http://www.dtra.mil/Portals/61/Documents/NTPR/2-Hist_Rpt_Atm/1952_DNA_6021F.pdf |publisher=Defense Nuclear Agency |page=78 |id=DNA 6021F  |access-date=6 February 2019 }}</ref> It was, however, the view of the Atomic Energy Commission that the nuclear detonations \"had not subjected Groom Mine personnel to any real danger from fallout\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Leisl Carr Childers|title=The Size of the Risk: Histories of Multiple Use in the Great Basin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mRAqCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA93|date=9 October 2015|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-5253-0|page=93}}</ref>\n\nBy May 1952, most of the Sheahan family had evacuated the mine and moved to [[Las Vegas]].<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" /> In July 1952, Martha, a member of the family who had been exposed to fallout, was diagnosed with cancer.<ref name=Paine1996 /> Following [[Operation Upshot\u2013Knothole]], the Sheahan family attempted to sell their claim to the Atomic Energy Commission but it refused, fearing it would set a precedent; instead the family received $1,100 for losses and damages resulting from the [[Operation Tumbler-Snapper]] tests.<ref>{{cite book|author=Leisl Carr Childers|title=The Size of the Risk: Histories of Multiple Use in the Great Basin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mRAqCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA246|date=9 October 2015|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-5253-0|page=246}}</ref> Following the adverse environmental impact observed by the two remaining family members at the mine caused by [[Upshot-Knothole Harry]], the Atomic Energy Commission said the blasts were designed to produce winds from the testing area towards Groom rather than towards Las Vegas.<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" />\n\nDuring 1953, the property was strafed and during the summer a bomb destroyed the mine's mill;<ref name=\"Solnit2014-35\">{{cite book|author=Rebecca Solnit|title=Savage Dreams: A Journey into the Hidden Wars of the American West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rjdOAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA35|date=6 June 2014|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-95792-3|page=35}}</ref> no specific claim was made by the Sheahan family against the [[United States Air Force]] (USAF) for the event.<ref>{{cite book|title=Groom Mountain Range, Lincoln County, Renewed Withdrawal from Nellis Air Force Range: Environmental Impact Statement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9Bw6AQAAMAAJ|year=1986|pages=3\u201313}}</ref> In 1954, the mining buildings were strafed by aircraft using [[Nellis Air Force Gunnery and Bombing Range]].<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" /> In 1956, the Sheahan family and others filed lawsuits against the Atomic Energy Commission because of damage caused by nuclear testing.<ref>{{cite book|author=Leisl Carr Childers|title=The Size of the Risk: Histories of Multiple Use in the Great Basin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mRAqCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA100|date=9 October 2015|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-5253-0|pages=100\u2013101}}</ref> In 1959, the lawsuit was withdrawn when the Sheahan family ran out of funds to continue legal action.<ref name=SEP2015CNN /> The property on which the mine is located has a view of an airfield known as [[Area 51]].<ref name=SEP2015KLAS /><ref name=FA2015 /> In the 1970s and 1980s, armed personnel arrived when the Sheahan family came onto their property, sometimes locking them into their own buildings.<ref name=FA2015 />\n\n[[File:NevadaTestRange 4808A.png|thumb|Groom Mine is depicted on a chart of the Nevada Test and Training Range made in 2008.|alt=A map with an overlay of restricted areas.]]\nIn 1984, the USAF seized lands around Groom Mine,<ref name=\"Aug1984UPI\" /> restricting access to the mine for the Sheahan family.<ref name=\"Solnit2014-35\" /><ref>{{cite book|author=Phil Patton|title=Dreamland: Travels Inside the Secret World of Roswell and Area 51|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WM6IxZvr0E4C&pg=PT76|date=31 October 2012|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-82860-6|page=76}}</ref> Some of the Sheahan family were issued with [[security clearances]] after 1984.<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" /> In 1986, the 1953 mill-destruction event was entered into the record of a subcommittee of the [[United States House Committee on Natural Resources]].<ref>{{cite book|author=United States. Congress. House. Committee on Interior and Insular Affairs. Subcommittee on Public Lands and National Parks|title=Additions to the National Wilderness Preservation System: Hearings Before the Subcommittee on Public Lands of the Committee on Interior and Insular Affairs, House of Representatives, Ninety-ninth Congress, First Session |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pgwmAAAAMAAJ|year=1986|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|page=215}}</ref> In 1987, the position of the United States Air Force was, \"we don't want to go in and tell them to get the hell out\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Rothberg |first=Daniel |date=10 September 2015 |title=Deadline expires for private land near Area 51 |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2015/sep/10/deadline-expires-private-land-near-area-51/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314180123/https://lasvegassun.com/news/2015/sep/10/deadline-expires-private-land-near-area-51/ |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1989, although it was within the [[Nevada Test and Training Range]], the United States Air Force allowed claimants access to their claims within the Groom Mining District, including Groom Mine.<ref>{{cite report  |author1=Resource Specialists and Management Staff within the Caliente Resource Area |author2=554th Range Group Staff, Nellis Air Force Base |author3=Nevada State offices, Bureau of Land Management |date=24 May 1989 |title=Draft: Nellis Air Force Range Resource Plan and Environmental Impact STatement |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O9lNdtXGGLYC&pg=PP166 |publisher=Bureau of Land Management, Las Vegas District |page=166 |oclc=1042984858}}</ref>\n\n===Government ownership===\nBeginning in late 2014, the [[United States Department of Defense]] attempted to purchase the property from the Sheahan family, originally offering $1.5 million.<ref name=December2016Fox /> By August 2015, the USAF had raised the offer to $5.2 million; the family continued rejecting the offers.<ref name=FA2015 /><ref name=AUG2015LVRJ>{{cite news |last=Rogers |first=Keith |date=31 August 2015 |title=Family rejects Air Force\u2019s $5.2 million bid for land near Area 51 |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/military/family-rejects-air-forces-5-2-million-bid-for-land-near-area-51/ |work=Las Vegas Review Journal |access-date=10 March 2018 }}</ref> In August 2015, a government press release described the mine as a \"safety and security risk\", even though the Sheahan family had not disclosed any activities of the Groom Lake facility.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ritter |first=Ken |agency=The Associated Press |date=7 September 2015 |title=Air Force wants owners to give up Nevada bombing range site |url=https://www.airforcetimes.com/news/your-air-force/2015/09/07/air-force-wants-owners-to-give-up-nevada-bombing-range-site/ |work=[[Air Force Times]] |location=Vienna, Virginia |access-date=13 March 2018 }}</ref> In September 2015, the commander of the Nevada Test and Training Range stated that the existence of the mine within the range led to \"tremendous expense\" due to \"canceling missions when they came out\";<ref name=SEP2015CNN>{{cite news |last=Kravarik |first=Jason |last2=Simon |first2=Dan |date=12 September 2015 |title=A battle is on for Area 51 in Nevada, but not the kind you might think |url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/09/11/us/area-51-nevada-legal-battle/index.html |work=CNN |location=Atlanta |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174710/https://www.cnn.com/2015/09/11/us/area-51-nevada-legal-battle/index.html |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> secret operations at the base could not proceed when civilians were present on the Sheahan's property within easy view of the installation. On 16 September 2015, the property was condemned under [[Eminent domain in the United States|eminent domain]] and given to the United States Government by a court order signed by federal Judge [[Miranda Du]].<ref name=SEP2015KLAS />\n\nIt was not determined at the time of transfer of ownership how much the Sheahan family would receive in just compensation for the government acquisition of Groom Mine; the USAF in 2015 estimated the land to be worth $1.2 million.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=United States of America v. 400 Acres of Land, more or less, situate in Lincoln County, State of Nevada |vol= |reporter=Case 2:15-cv-01743-MMD-NJK, Document 1-8 |opinion= |pinpoint= |court=[[Nevada District Court]] |date=September 10, 2015 |url=https://ecf.nvd.uscourts.gov/doc1/11515464558 |access-date=April 6, 2020|quote=Schedule G Estimate of Just Compensation: The estimated just compensation for the interests being taken is $1,200,000.}}</ref> In November 2015, the Sheahan family suggested the mine be protected as a [[National Historic Site (United States)|national historic site]];<ref>{{cite news |last=Meek |first=Glen |date=10 November 2015 |title=Family seeks appraisal of Groom Lake property near Area 51 |url=http://www.lasvegasnow.com/news/family-seeks-appraisal-of-groom-lake-property-near-area-51/265696384 |work=KLAS-TV |location=Las Vegas |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314181125/http://www.lasvegasnow.com/news/family-seeks-appraisal-of-groom-lake-property-near-area-51/265696384 |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> this coincides with a suggestion in a 1980s USAF report that recommended nominating Groom Mining District to be listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=Paine1996 /> By 2016, the USAF only valued Groom Mine at under a third of a million dollars;<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogers |first=Keith |date=2 May 2017 |title=Family accuses Air Force of lowball price estimate on land it seized near Area 51 |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/military/family-accuses-air-force-of-lowball-price-estimate-on-land-it-seized-near-area-51/ |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174406/https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/military/family-accuses-air-force-of-lowball-price-estimate-on-land-it-seized-near-area-51/ |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the Sheahan family's legal counsel valued the property as being worth over $100 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/6359/family-says-land-overlooking-area-51-is-worth-116m-usaf-says-330k |title=Family Says Land Overlooking Area 51 Is Worth $116M\u2014USAF Says $330k |last=Rogoway |first=Tyler |date=6 December 2016 |website=The War Zone |publisher=Time Inc. |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174611/http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/6359/family-says-land-overlooking-area-51-is-worth-116m-usaf-says-330k |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2017, the family claimed they were forced to leave millions of dollars worth of property at Groom Mine following the seizure;<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogers |first=Keith |date=2 May 2017 |title=Family fighting land seizure accuses US of \u2018bullying tactics\u2019 |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/military/family-fighting-land-seizure-accuses-us-of-bullying-tactics/ |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174708/https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/military/family-fighting-land-seizure-accuses-us-of-bullying-tactics/ |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> part of the property which was abandoned includes an antique anvil that was missing when personal property was reviewed in November 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogoway |first=Tyler |date=10 May 2017 |title=Family Demands To Know How A 200-Pound Antique Anvil Disappeared From Area 51 |url=http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/10100/family-demands-to-know-how-a-200-pound-antique-anvil-disappeared-from-area-51 |work=The Warzone |location=Time Inc. |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174736/http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/10100/family-demands-to-know-how-a-200-pound-antique-anvil-disappeared-from-area-51 |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In August 2019, it was reported that the family was hoping to have a jury trial to determine the value of the property.<ref>{{cite news |title=Family who owned Area 51 land sees planned events as proof in claim against the government |first=Carla| last=Wade| publisher=[[KTNV-TV]] |location=[[Las Vegas]]| date=August 22, 2019| url=https://www.ktnv.com/news/family-who-owned-area-51-land-sees-planned-events-as-proof-in-claim-against-the-government |access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> The trial was ultimately conducted in front of a three-member Land Commission. Prior to trial, the landowners accepted the Government's valuation of the mineral interests at $104,000 and went to trial only to contest the value of the surface rights as a tourist operation.<ref>{{cite book |title=United States District Court District of Nevada (Las Vegas) CIVIL DOCKET FOR CASE #: 2:15-cv-01743-MMD-NJK, STIPULATION Regarding Valuation and Trial Presentation of the Mineral Interest.}}</ref> The Court's ruling on the value of the surface rights is pending.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[Tikaboo Peak]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite archive |item =Groom Mining District Records |item-url =http://dewey.library.unr.edu/xtf/view?docId=ead/99-19-ead.xml |type =Special Collections |item-id =99-19 |date =1871-1930 |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = |file = |box= |collection =Dewey Library |collection-url = |repository = |institution =University of Nevada, Reno |location =Special Collections, University Libraries}}\n* {{cite archive |first= |last= |item =Groom Mine |item-url =https://pubs.usgs.gov/ds/1004/scans/nv/dma/1726_DMA.pdf |type = |item-id = |date = |page= |pages= |fonds = |series =All Defense Minerals Administration (DMA) Dockets |file = |box= |collection =Historical Files from Federal Government Mineral Exploration-Assistance Programs, 1950 to 1974 |collection-url =https://pubs.usgs.gov/ds/1004/ds1004_alldma.htm |repository = |institution =United States Geological Survey |location = |oclc= |accession= |ref=}}\n* {{cite archive |first=Alice P. |last=Broudy |item =Observed Damage at Groom Mine Following Shot of Plumbbob, July 9, 1964 |item-url = |type = |item-id = |date = |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = |file =5 |box=24 |collection =Alice P. Broudy Papers on Broudy v United States |collection-url =https://www.library.unlv.edu/speccol/finding-aids/MS-00097.pdf |repository =Special Collections and Archives |institution =University of Nevada, Las Vegas |location =Las Vegas, Nevada |oclc= |accession= |ref=}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.groommine.com/}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://westernmininghistory.com/mine_detail/10072154/ |title=Groom Mine |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2017 |website=Western Mining History }}\n{{Lincoln County, Nevada|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lincoln County, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Mines in Nevada]]\n[[Category:1875 establishments in Nevada]]\n[[Category:2015 disestablishments in Nevada]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Short description|Defunct mine in Lincoln County, Nevada}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox mine\n| name               = Groom Mine\n| image              = File:Wfm usgs groom map.png\n| width              =\n| caption            = [[United States Geological Survey]] map depicting the location of Groom Mine\n| pushpin_map        =\n| pushpin_mapsize    =\n| pushpin_map_alt    =\n| pushpin_map_caption=\n| pushpin_image      =\n| pushpin_label      =\n| pushpin_label_position =\n| coordinates        = {{Coord|37.3462|-115.7692|display=inline,title}}\n| place              =\n| subdivision_type   =\n| state/province     = [[Lincoln County, Nevada]]<ref name=\"Issue31\"/>\n| country            =\n| products           = Silver<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Bulletin of Nevada State Bureau of Mines|series=Geology and Mining Series, Issues 1-16|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bmc1AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA161|title=The Mineral Resources of Southern Nevada|last=Carpenter|first=Jay A.|year=1904|publisher=University of Nevada|page=161|oclc=1432631}}</ref>\n| amount             = <!--include units-->\n| financial year     =\n| type               = [[Open-pit mining|Open-pit]] & [[Adit|underground]]<ref>{{cite report |author=Donald Zona |date=October 1985 |title=Draft Environmental Impact Statement Groom Mountain Range |url=http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a226049.pdf |publisher=United States Air Force |pages=3\u201324 |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218092001/http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a226049.pdf |archivedate=18 February 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| greatest depth     = {{convert|210|ft|m}}<ref name=BoM1977 />\n| opening year       = {{Start date|1866}}<ref name=PippenReno1986>{{cite report |first=Lonnie C. |last=Pippen |first2=Ronald L. |last2=Reno |first3=Stephen R. |last3=Durand |date=August 1986 |title=Archaeological Reconnaissance: An Archaeological Reconnaissance of the Groom Range Lincoln County, Nevada |url=https://archive.org/stream/archaeologicalrereno/archaeologicalrereno_djvu.txt |publisher=Desert Research Institute |page=62 |quote=A crude smelter may have been on the Groom Mine property in 1866 (Averett 1963:49). |access-date=9 February 2019 }}</ref>\n| active years       = 1872<ref name=\"District1989-162\"/>\u20131954<ref name=December2016Fox />\n| closing year       = {{End date|2015}}<ref name=SEP2015KLAS>{{cite news |last=Meek |first=Glen |date=16 September 2015 |title=Government takes family's land near Area 51 |url=http://www.lasvegasnow.com/news/government-takes-familys-land-near-area-51/249903883 |work=[[KLAS-TV]] |location=Las Vegas |access-date=10 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310175220/http://www.lasvegasnow.com/news/government-takes-familys-land-near-area-51/249903883 |archive-date=10 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| owner              = [[United States Government]]<ref name=SEP2015KLAS />\n| official website   = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| acquisition year   = 2015<ref name=SEP2015KLAS />\n| module             = <!-- or 'embedded' or 'nrhp' -->\n}}\n\n'''Groom Mine''', located in [[Lincoln County, Nevada]], first opened in the 1870s.<ref name=December2016Fox />  Most mining in the area, mostly of [[silver chloride]] ores, had finished by 1874.<ref name=\"District1989-162\"/> Groom Mine continued to operate, finally ceasing operations in 1954.<ref name=December2016Fox /> By 1956, official recordings of products of the Groom Mining District, which includes Groom Mine, shows that [[lead]] was the bulk of minerals harvested, which also included {{convert|145,000|ozt|kg}} of [[silver]] and about {{convert|45|ozt|kg}} of [[gold]].<ref>{{cite book|title=OF1998-01: Mineral and energy resource assessment of the Nellis Air Force Range|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N10nIMy-v1AC&pg=SA7-PA136|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|page=136|id=GGKEY:0JR4J3LY7P1|date=1998}}</ref> During [[World War II]], Groom Mine became surrounded by military activity, which continued into the 21st century.<ref name=FA2015 /> In the 1950s, the mine was exposed to fallout from nuclear testing that was being carried out at the [[Nevada Test Site]].<ref name=FA2015 /> During the late 20th century, military activities, including the destruction of a mill and the restriction of access to the mine, continued to affect work there.<ref name=Savage2014 /> The United States Government seized the mine under [[Eminent domain in the United States|eminent domain]] from its previous owners in 2015.<ref name=SEP2015KLAS /> Just compensation is under dispute in United States District Court, District of Nevada (Las Vegas), Judge [[Miranda Du]] presiding.\n\n==Background==\nThe rocks in the range date back to the [[Paleozoic]] era; the site is also covered by [[Tertiary]] rocks on its east and north sides.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Nevada Bureau of Mines and Geology|author2=J. V. Tingley|title=OF1984-01: A Mineral Inventory of the Caliente Resource Area, Caliente District, Lincoln County, Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yhDB8-dWv0kC&pg=PA28|year=1984|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|page=28|id=GGKEY:7TSA0GECEY0|oclc=32899352}}</ref> Prior to European exploration, the region was inhabited by [[Southern Paiute]] Native Americans.<ref name=Paine1996>{{cite journal |last1=Paine |first1=Gary |date=Spring 1996 |title=A Mine, the Military, and a Dry Lake: National Security and the Groom District, Lincoln County, Nevada |url=http://epubs.nsla.nv.gov/statepubs/epubs/210777-1996-1Spring.pdf |journal=Nevada Historical Society Quarterly |volume=39 |issue=1 |pages=20\u201342 |access-date=14 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230134150/http://epubs.nsla.nv.gov/statepubs/epubs/210777-1996-1Spring.pdf |archive-date=30 December 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all |ISSN=0047-9462}}</ref> Following the discovery of minerals in the [[Comstock Lode]] in 1859, prospecting of other areas in Nevada began.<ref name=\"NBMG1998-7\">{{cite book|title=OF1998-01: Mineral and energy resource assessment of the Nellis Air Force Range|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N10nIMy-v1AC&pg=SA7-PA1|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|page=7|id=GGKEY:0JR4J3LY7P1|date=1998}}</ref><ref name=\"NBMG1998-7\" /><ref>{{cite book|author=Joseph V. Tingley|title=SP019: Geologic and Natural History Tours in the Reno Area|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekf0wBY8LyUC&pg=PA54|year=2005|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|isbn=978-1-888035-09-4|page=54}}<br />{{cite web |url=https://www.gbcnv.edu/howh/MannyPenrod.html |title=What Happened to Manny? |last=Hickson |first=Howard |date=2003 |website=Howard Hickson's Histories |publisher=Great Basin College |access-date=9 February 2019 |quote=}}</ref> Mining in the area began in the late 1860s, after minerals were discovered in the [[Groom Range]] in 1864.<ref name=\"District1989-162\">{{cite report  |author1=Resource Specialists and Management Staff within the Caliente Resource Area |author2=554th Range Group Staff, Nellis Air Force Base |author3=Nevada State offices, Bureau of Land Management |date=24 May 1989 |title=Draft: Nellis Air Force Range Resource Plan and Environmental Impact STatement |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O9lNdtXGGLYC&pg=PP162 |publisher=Bureau of Land Management, Las Vegas District |page=162|oclc=1042984858}}</ref> A mining district to organize claims, called Groom District, was formed in 1869.<ref name=\"NBMG1998-7\" /> In 1871, the area was documented in the [[Wheeler Survey]].<ref name=Paine1996 />\n\n==History==\n===Mining===\nHuman habitation at the Groom Mine site may have begun as early as 1866.<ref name=PippenReno1986 /> A [[Land patent|patent]] for the Groom Mine was issued in 1872 and in 1885, the Sheahan family acquired the property.<ref name=\"District1989-162\"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Jack G. Quade|title=OF1986-09: Mineral Inventory and Geochemical Survey, Groom Mountain Range, Lincoln County, Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=An2GexDluCsC&pg=PA8|year=1986|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|pages=8\u2013|id=GGKEY:XT9W6WCT82L|oclc=32899397}}</ref> The mine was three days' travel from [[Indian Springs, Nevada|Indian Springs]] and {{convert|5,250|ft|m}} above sea level, making it very isolated.<ref name=Paine1996 /> According to [[Nevada Bureau of Mines and Geology]] in 1998, the property claim, which is commonly referred to as Groom, is officially named \"Conception\".<ref>{{cite book|title=OF1998-01: Mineral and energy resource assessment of the Nellis Air Force Range|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N10nIMy-v1AC&pg=SL154-PA40|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|page=154|id=GGKEY:0JR4J3LY7P1|date=1998}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the Conception claim, other claims in Groom Distract were made and held by the Sheahan family.<ref name=Paine1996 /> From 1915 until 1917, the mine was leased to Tom McCormick, who worked the mine.<ref name=Paine1996 /> In September 1917, a miner from [[Austria-Hungary]] who was employed by Groom Mining Company died at the mine.<ref>{{cite book|author=Nevada. Legislature|title=Appendix to Journals of Senate and Assembly ... of the Legislature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8-BKAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA6-PA35|year=1919|pages=35\u201336}}</ref> In the mid-to-late 1910s the mine produced silver worth about $250,000.<ref>{{cite book|title=Geology and Mining Series|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bmc1AAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA121|year=1904|publisher=University of Nevada|page=121}}</ref> The shipping of mined products became difficult with the closing of the [[Las Vegas and Tonopah Railroad]] at the end of that decade,<ref>{{cite book|title=Intermountain Industry and Engineering: Official Publication: Utah Motor Transport Ass'n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hzs5AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA39|year=1920|publisher=The Association|page=39}}</ref> which caused the mine to become temporarily idle.<ref>{{cite book|title=Intermountain Industry and Engineering: Official Publication: Utah Motor Transport Ass'n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hzs5AQAAMAAJ&pg=RA13-PA34|year=1920|publisher=The Association|page=34}}</ref> By 1922, the mine had two shafts, the longest being {{Convert|200|ft|m|abbr=}} deep.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Mines Handbook: An Enlargement of the Copper Hand Book; a Manual of the Mining Industry of North America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Smw_AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1219|year=1922|publisher=Stevens Copper Handbook Company|page=1219}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Groom Lake Road.jpg|thumb|Groom Road, built by the Sheahan family and Lincoln County|alt=a dirt road leading off towards the horizon]]\nIn 1942, construction of a mill that used a [[Mineral processing|gravity and flotation]] method began;<ref name=Paine1996 /> a source later referred to this mill as a [[concentration mill]].<ref name=Savage2014 /> By 1951, four people were living at the mine and the concentration mill had been completed.<ref name=Savage2014>{{cite book|author=Rebecca Solnit|title=Savage Dreams: A Journey into the Hidden Wars of the American West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rjdOAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA34|date=6 June 2014|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-95792-3|page=34}}</ref> Ore from Groom Mine, from which lead and silver were extracted, was found to contain [[cerussite]] and [[galena]].<ref name=\"Issue31\">{{cite book|author1=Stephen B. Castor|author2=Gregory C. Ferdock|title=Minerals of Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=flAhr0MbxM8C&pg=PA139|year=2004|publisher=University of Nevada Press|isbn=978-0-87417-540-0|page=139}}</ref> Beginning in 1950, roads approaching the mine from the west were closed due to military activities, leading to the Sheahan family and Lincoln County to build a road from the east;<ref name=FA2015 /> this is referred to as Groom Road in a 1986 report.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jack G. Quade|title=OF1986-09: Mineral Inventory and Geochemical Survey, Groom Mountain Range, Lincoln County, Nevada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=An2GexDluCsC&pg=PA2|year=1986|publisher=NV Bureau of Mines & Geology|pages=2|id=GGKEY:XT9W6WCT82L|oclc=32899397}}</ref>  During the 1950s, mining operations paused due to nearby [[List of nuclear weapons tests of the United States|nuclear tests]].<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" /> In 1954, production from the mine ended due to the destruction of a mill at the mine.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Neill |first=Marine |date=17 September 2015 |title=US air force threatens to destroy property next door to Area 51 after owners refuse to sell |url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/real-estate/us-air-force-threatens-to-destroy-property-next-door-to-area-51-after-owners-refuse-to-sell/news-story/245501b0ac154be2f5ac379496b183df |work=News Corp Australia |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314180829/http://www.news.com.au/finance/real-estate/us-air-force-threatens-to-destroy-property-next-door-to-area-51-after-owners-refuse-to-sell/news-story/245501b0ac154be2f5ac379496b183df |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nUntil 1956, the mine product totaled almost a million dollars in several minerals, including copper, silver, and gold;<ref name=\"District1989-162\"/> In 1977, the [[United States Bureau of Mines]] valued the output of Groom mine products at $3.75 million.<ref name=BoM1977>{{cite report |author=John R. Norberg |date=12 August 1977 |title=Mineral Resources in the Vicinity of the Nellis Air Force Base and the Nellis Bombing and Gunnery Range, Clark, Lincoln, and Nye Counties, Nevada |url=https://www.nrc.gov/docs/ML0037/ML003742795.pdf |publisher=United States Department of the Interior |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314175613/https://www.nrc.gov/docs/ML0037/ML003742795.pdf |archivedate=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was the most productive mine in the Groom Mining District<ref name=\"District1989-162\"/> and had been worked on by three generations of the Sheahan family.<ref name=Paine1996 /> Based on [[Gold panning|panning]] samples near Groom Mine, the area may also contain deposits of [[antimony]], [[barium]], lead, mercury, and zinc.<ref>{{cite report  |author1=Resource Specialists and Management Staff within the Caliente Resource Area |author2=554th Range Group Staff, Nellis Air Force Base |author3=Nevada State offices, Bureau of Land Management |date=24 May 1989 |title=Draft: Nellis Air Force Range Resource Plan and Environmental Impact STatement |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O9lNdtXGGLYC&pg=PP165 |publisher=Bureau of Land Management, Las Vegas District |page=165 |oclc=1042984858}}</ref> By 1959, the Sheahan family moved away from the mine but visited their property regularly.<ref name=FA2015 /> In 1984, the Sheahan family, who still owned the Groom Mine, also had the legal rights to most of the other 22 patented mining claims nearby.<ref name=\"Aug1984UPI\">{{cite news |last=Chrystal |first=Chris |date=6 August 1984 |title=Air Force: 'We had no legal authority' |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/08/06/Air-Force-We-had-no-legal-authority/2948460612800/ |work=United Press International |access-date=8 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314175646/https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/08/06/Air-Force-We-had-no-legal-authority/2948460612800/ |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> According to the [[Nevada Bureau of Mines and Geology]], it was estimated in 1963 that there is {{convert|30,000|t|kg}} of material that can be mined at Groom Mine.<ref>{{cite report |first=John L. |last=Munteen |first2=David A. |last2=Davis |first3=Bridget |last3=Ayling |date=2017 |title=The Nevada Mineral Industry 2016 |url=http://epubs.nsla.nv.gov/statepubs/epubs/210988-2016.pdf |publisher=University of Nevada, Reno |page= |docket= |access-date=9 February 2019 |quote= |oclc=1061602920 }}</ref> A 1990 [[Bureau of Land Management]] report stated that due to restricted access to the mine, it would lead to \"potential loss of income through inability to expand or further develop the claims\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Spang|first=Edward F.|title=Caliente Resource Area, Nellis Air Force Range Resource Plan: Environmental Impact Statement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uwkzAQAAMAAJ&pg=SL8-PA8|year=1990|publisher=Bureau of Land Management|pages=H\u20138}}</ref> Until late 2015, the Sheahan family periodically blasted for minerals at the mine;<ref name=December2016Fox>{{cite news |last=Craft |first=Andrew |date=13 December 2016 |title=Family fights government in land dispute near Area 51 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/science/2016/12/13/family-fights-government-in-land-dispute-near-area-51.html |work=Fox News |location=New York City |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174249/http://www.foxnews.com/science/2016/12/13/family-fights-government-in-land-dispute-near-area-51.html |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> by this time the family had owned the mine for 130 years.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Huff |first=Steve |date=12 September 2015 |title=True American Takes Stand Against Mysterious Area 51 Expansion |url=https://www.maxim.com/maxim-man/mysterious-area-51-expansion-2015-9 |magazine=Maxim |location=New York City |publisher=Biglari Holdings |access-date=15 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315201948/https://www.maxim.com/maxim-man/mysterious-area-51-expansion-2015-9 |archive-date=15 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Military interaction===\nIn 1941, Groom Mine was visited by individuals who stayed at the mine with the Sheahan family while surveying the area for a gunnery and bombing range to be used during World War II.<ref name=FA2015 /> The outhouse and bunkhouse at the mine were accidentally [[strafed]] during the war by aircraft using the Las Vegas Bombing and Gunnery Range.<ref name=Paine1996 /> Beginning in the 1950s, Groom Mine began to be impacted by nuclear tests at the Nevada Test Site;<ref name=FA2015>{{cite web |url=https://foxtrotalpha.jalopnik.com/the-unlikely-struggle-of-the-family-whose-neighbor-is-a-1741346156 |title=The Unlikely Struggle Of The Family Whose Neighbor Is Area 51 |last=Rogoway |first=Tyler |date=9 November 2015 |website=Foxtrot Alpha |publisher=[[Gawker Media|Jalopnik]] |access-date=8 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315003622/https://foxtrotalpha.jalopnik.com/the-unlikely-struggle-of-the-family-whose-neighbor-is-a-1741346156 |archive-date=15 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Groom Mine was {{convert|38|mi|km}} away.<ref name=\"Titus2001\">{{cite book|author=A. Costandina Titus|title=Bombs in the Backyard: Atomic Testing and American Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQfG-U5iAPYC&pg=PA56|year=2001|publisher=University of Nevada Press|isbn=978-0-87417-370-3|page=56}}</ref> In 1951, the [[United States Atomic Energy Commission|Atomic Energy Commission]] informed the Sheahan family of the planned detonations and set up instrumentation at the mine.<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\">{{cite book|author=Phil Patton|title=Dreamland: Travels Inside the Secret World of Roswell and Area 51|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WM6IxZvr0E4C&pg=PT93|date=31 October 2012|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-82860-6|pages=93\u201397}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Susan Wright|title=UFO Headquarters: Investigations On Current Extraterrestrial Activity In Area 51|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=81xoS94LSncC&pg=PA7|date=15 August 1998|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-0-312-20781-6|page=7}}</ref> The instrumentation was monitored by an employee of the [[United States Public Health Service]], who lived at the mine along with the Sheahan family.<ref>{{cite book|author=Sarah Alisabeth Fox|title=Downwind: A People's History of the Nuclear West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OeMoDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA59|date=November 2014|publisher=U of Nebraska Press|isbn=978-0-8032-5537-1|pages=59\u201360}}</ref> The first mention of a nuclear tests impacting operations at Groom Mine was the [[Operation Tumbler\u2013Snapper]] Easy Test, which led to the mine being evacuated due to its proximity to the detonation.<ref name=\"Childers2015-p79\" /> Following the detonation, measurements of radiation at the mine reached 0.19 [[Roentgen (unit)|roentgen]] per hour.<ref>{{cite book|author=Barton C. Hacker|title=Elements of Controversy: The Atomic Energy Commission and Radiation Safety in Nuclear Weapons Testing, 1947-1974|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uKp3ridsHrYC&pg=PA80|date=1 January 1994|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-08323-3|page=80}}</ref> It caused some structural damage, breaking the front door of the Sheahan's home.<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" /> Further away, [[nuclear fallout|fallout]] impacted nearby [[Tempiute, Nevada|Tempiute]].<ref name=\"Childers2015-p79\">{{cite book|author=Leisl Carr Childers|title=The Size of the Risk: Histories of Multiple Use in the Great Basin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mRAqCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA79|date=9 October 2015|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-5253-0|pages=79\u201380}}</ref> Returning to the mine had to be done using a different route; the normal route was too radioactive to travel on.<ref>{{cite book|author=Philip L. Fradkin|title=Fallout: An American Nuclear Tragedy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Clrz_0sJZrQC&pg=PA101|date=March 2004|publisher=Big Earth Publishing|isbn=978-1-55566-331-5|page=101}}</ref> The following Fox test in late May 1952 led to fallout falling on the mine;<ref name=\"Childers2015-p79\"/> the highest-recorded radiation was 0.32 roentgen per hour.<ref>{{cite report |first=Jean |last=Ponton |first2=Carl |last2=Maag |date=16 June 1982 |title=Shots Easy, Fox, Grace and How: The Final Tests of the Tumbler-Snapper Series 7 May - 5 June 1952 |url=http://www.dtra.mil/Portals/61/Documents/NTPR/2-Hist_Rpt_Atm/1952_DNA_6021F.pdf |publisher=Defense Nuclear Agency |page=78 |id=DNA 6021F  |access-date=6 February 2019 }}</ref> It was, however, the view of the Atomic Energy Commission that the nuclear detonations \"had not subjected Groom Mine personnel to any real danger from fallout\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Leisl Carr Childers|title=The Size of the Risk: Histories of Multiple Use in the Great Basin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mRAqCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA93|date=9 October 2015|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-5253-0|page=93}}</ref>\n\nBy May 1952, most of the Sheahan family had evacuated the mine and moved to [[Las Vegas]].<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" /> In July 1952, Martha, a member of the family who had been exposed to fallout, was diagnosed with cancer.<ref name=Paine1996 /> Following [[Operation Upshot\u2013Knothole]], the Sheahan family attempted to sell their claim to the Atomic Energy Commission but it refused, fearing it would set a precedent; instead the family received $1,100 for losses and damages resulting from the [[Operation Tumbler-Snapper]] tests.<ref>{{cite book|author=Leisl Carr Childers|title=The Size of the Risk: Histories of Multiple Use in the Great Basin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mRAqCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA246|date=9 October 2015|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-5253-0|page=246}}</ref> Following the adverse environmental impact observed by the two remaining family members at the mine caused by [[Upshot-Knothole Harry]], the Atomic Energy Commission said the blasts were designed to produce winds from the testing area towards Groom rather than towards Las Vegas.<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" />\n\nDuring 1953, the property was strafed and during the summer a bomb destroyed the mine's mill;<ref name=\"Solnit2014-35\">{{cite book|author=Rebecca Solnit|title=Savage Dreams: A Journey into the Hidden Wars of the American West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rjdOAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA35|date=6 June 2014|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-95792-3|page=35}}</ref> no specific claim was made by the Sheahan family against the [[United States Air Force]] (USAF) for the event.<ref>{{cite book|title=Groom Mountain Range, Lincoln County, Renewed Withdrawal from Nellis Air Force Range: Environmental Impact Statement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9Bw6AQAAMAAJ|year=1986|pages=3\u201313}}</ref> In 1954, the mining buildings were strafed by aircraft using [[Nellis Air Force Gunnery and Bombing Range]].<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" /> In 1956, the Sheahan family and others filed lawsuits against the Atomic Energy Commission because of damage caused by nuclear testing.<ref>{{cite book|author=Leisl Carr Childers|title=The Size of the Risk: Histories of Multiple Use in the Great Basin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mRAqCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA100|date=9 October 2015|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-5253-0|pages=100\u2013101}}</ref> In 1959, the lawsuit was withdrawn when the Sheahan family ran out of funds to continue legal action.<ref name=SEP2015CNN /> The property on which the mine is located has a view of an airfield known as [[Area 51]].<ref name=SEP2015KLAS /><ref name=FA2015 /> In the 1970s and 1980s, armed personnel arrived when the Sheahan family came onto their property, sometimes locking them into their own buildings.<ref name=FA2015 />\n\n[[File:NevadaTestRange 4808A.png|thumb|Groom Mine is depicted on a chart of the Nevada Test and Training Range made in 2008.|alt=A map with an overlay of restricted areas.]]\nIn 1984, the USAF seized lands around Groom Mine,<ref name=\"Aug1984UPI\" /> restricting access to the mine for the Sheahan family.<ref name=\"Solnit2014-35\" /><ref>{{cite book|author=Phil Patton|title=Dreamland: Travels Inside the Secret World of Roswell and Area 51|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WM6IxZvr0E4C&pg=PT76|date=31 October 2012|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-82860-6|page=76}}</ref> Some of the Sheahan family were issued with [[security clearances]] after 1984.<ref name=\"Patton2012-90s\" /> In 1986, the 1953 mill-destruction event was entered into the record of a subcommittee of the [[United States House Committee on Natural Resources]].<ref>{{cite book|author=United States. Congress. House. Committee on Interior and Insular Affairs. Subcommittee on Public Lands and National Parks|title=Additions to the National Wilderness Preservation System: Hearings Before the Subcommittee on Public Lands of the Committee on Interior and Insular Affairs, House of Representatives, Ninety-ninth Congress, First Session |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pgwmAAAAMAAJ|year=1986|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|page=215}}</ref> In 1987, the position of the United States Air Force was, \"we don't want to go in and tell them to get the hell out\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Rothberg |first=Daniel |date=10 September 2015 |title=Deadline expires for private land near Area 51 |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2015/sep/10/deadline-expires-private-land-near-area-51/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314180123/https://lasvegassun.com/news/2015/sep/10/deadline-expires-private-land-near-area-51/ |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1989, although it was within the [[Nevada Test and Training Range]], the United States Air Force allowed claimants access to their claims within the Groom Mining District, including Groom Mine.<ref>{{cite report  |author1=Resource Specialists and Management Staff within the Caliente Resource Area |author2=554th Range Group Staff, Nellis Air Force Base |author3=Nevada State offices, Bureau of Land Management |date=24 May 1989 |title=Draft: Nellis Air Force Range Resource Plan and Environmental Impact STatement |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O9lNdtXGGLYC&pg=PP166 |publisher=Bureau of Land Management, Las Vegas District |page=166 |oclc=1042984858}}</ref>\n\n===Government ownership===\nBeginning in late 2014, the [[United States Department of Defense]] attempted to purchase the property from the Sheahan family, originally offering $1.5 million.<ref name=December2016Fox /> By August 2015, the USAF had raised the offer to $5.2 million; the family continued rejecting the offers.<ref name=FA2015 /><ref name=AUG2015LVRJ>{{cite news |last=Rogers |first=Keith |date=31 August 2015 |title=Family rejects Air Force\u2019s $5.2 million bid for land near Area 51 |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/military/family-rejects-air-forces-5-2-million-bid-for-land-near-area-51/ |work=Las Vegas Review Journal |access-date=10 March 2018 }}</ref> In August 2015, a government press release described the mine as a \"safety and security risk\", even though the Sheahan family had not disclosed any activities of the Groom Lake facility.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ritter |first=Ken |agency=The Associated Press |date=7 September 2015 |title=Air Force wants owners to give up Nevada bombing range site |url=https://www.airforcetimes.com/news/your-air-force/2015/09/07/air-force-wants-owners-to-give-up-nevada-bombing-range-site/ |work=[[Air Force Times]] |location=Vienna, Virginia |access-date=13 March 2018 }}</ref> In September 2015, the commander of the Nevada Test and Training Range stated that the existence of the mine within the range led to \"tremendous expense\" due to \"canceling missions when they came out\";<ref name=SEP2015CNN>{{cite news |last=Kravarik |first=Jason |last2=Simon |first2=Dan |date=12 September 2015 |title=A battle is on for Area 51 in Nevada, but not the kind you might think |url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/09/11/us/area-51-nevada-legal-battle/index.html |work=CNN |location=Atlanta |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174710/https://www.cnn.com/2015/09/11/us/area-51-nevada-legal-battle/index.html |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> secret operations at the base could not proceed when civilians were present on the Sheahan's property within easy view of the installation. On 16 September 2015, the property was condemned under [[Eminent domain in the United States|eminent domain]] and given to the United States Government by a court order signed by federal Judge [[Miranda Du]].<ref name=SEP2015KLAS />\n\nIt was not determined at the time of transfer of ownership how much the Sheahan family would receive in just compensation for the government acquisition of Groom Mine; the USAF in 2015 estimated the land to be worth $1.2 million.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=United States of America v. 400 Acres of Land, more or less, situate in Lincoln County, State of Nevada |vol= |reporter=Case 2:15-cv-01743-MMD-NJK, Document 1-8 |opinion= |pinpoint= |court=[[Nevada District Court]] |date=September 10, 2015 |url=https://ecf.nvd.uscourts.gov/doc1/11515464558 |access-date=April 6, 2020|quote=Schedule G Estimate of Just Compensation: The estimated just compensation for the interests being taken is $1,200,000.}}</ref> In November 2015, the Sheahan family suggested the mine be protected as a [[National Historic Site (United States)|national historic site]];<ref>{{cite news |last=Meek |first=Glen |date=10 November 2015 |title=Family seeks appraisal of Groom Lake property near Area 51 |url=http://www.lasvegasnow.com/news/family-seeks-appraisal-of-groom-lake-property-near-area-51/265696384 |work=KLAS-TV |location=Las Vegas |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314181125/http://www.lasvegasnow.com/news/family-seeks-appraisal-of-groom-lake-property-near-area-51/265696384 |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> this coincides with a suggestion in a 1980s USAF report that recommended nominating Groom Mining District to be listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=Paine1996 /> By 2016, the USAF only valued Groom Mine at under a third of a million dollars;<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogers |first=Keith |date=2 May 2017 |title=Family accuses Air Force of lowball price estimate on land it seized near Area 51 |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/military/family-accuses-air-force-of-lowball-price-estimate-on-land-it-seized-near-area-51/ |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174406/https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/military/family-accuses-air-force-of-lowball-price-estimate-on-land-it-seized-near-area-51/ |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the Sheahan family's legal counsel valued the property as being worth over $100 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/6359/family-says-land-overlooking-area-51-is-worth-116m-usaf-says-330k |title=Family Says Land Overlooking Area 51 Is Worth $116M\u2014USAF Says $330k |last=Rogoway |first=Tyler |date=6 December 2016 |website=The War Zone |publisher=Time Inc. |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174611/http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/6359/family-says-land-overlooking-area-51-is-worth-116m-usaf-says-330k |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2017, the family claimed they were forced to leave millions of dollars worth of property at Groom Mine following the seizure;<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogers |first=Keith |date=2 May 2017 |title=Family fighting land seizure accuses US of \u2018bullying tactics\u2019 |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/military/family-fighting-land-seizure-accuses-us-of-bullying-tactics/ |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174708/https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/military/family-fighting-land-seizure-accuses-us-of-bullying-tactics/ |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> part of the property which was abandoned includes an antique anvil that was missing when personal property was reviewed in November 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogoway |first=Tyler |date=10 May 2017 |title=Family Demands To Know How A 200-Pound Antique Anvil Disappeared From Area 51 |url=http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/10100/family-demands-to-know-how-a-200-pound-antique-anvil-disappeared-from-area-51 |work=The Warzone |location=Time Inc. |access-date=13 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174736/http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/10100/family-demands-to-know-how-a-200-pound-antique-anvil-disappeared-from-area-51 |archive-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In August 2019, it was reported that the family was hoping to have a jury trial to determine the value of the property.<ref>{{cite news |title=Family who owned Area 51 land sees planned events as proof in claim against the government |first=Carla| last=Wade| publisher=[[KTNV-TV]] |location=[[Las Vegas]]| date=August 22, 2019| url=https://www.ktnv.com/news/family-who-owned-area-51-land-sees-planned-events-as-proof-in-claim-against-the-government |access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> The trial was ultimately conducted in front of a three-member Land Commission. Prior to trial the landowners accepted the Government's valuation of the mineral interests at $104,000 and went to trial only to contest the value of the surface rights as a tourist operation.<ref>{{cite book |title=United States District Court District of Nevada (Las Vegas) CIVIL DOCKET FOR CASE #: 2:15-cv-01743-MMD-NJK, STIPULATION Regarding Valuation and Trial Presentation of the Mineral Interest.}}</ref> The Court's ruling on the value of the surface rights is pending.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[Tikaboo Peak]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite archive |item =Groom Mining District Records |item-url =http://dewey.library.unr.edu/xtf/view?docId=ead/99-19-ead.xml |type =Special Collections |item-id =99-19 |date =1871-1930 |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = |file = |box= |collection =Dewey Library |collection-url = |repository = |institution =University of Nevada, Reno |location =Special Collections, University Libraries}}\n* {{cite archive |first= |last= |item =Groom Mine |item-url =https://pubs.usgs.gov/ds/1004/scans/nv/dma/1726_DMA.pdf |type = |item-id = |date = |page= |pages= |fonds = |series =All Defense Minerals Administration (DMA) Dockets |file = |box= |collection =Historical Files from Federal Government Mineral Exploration-Assistance Programs, 1950 to 1974 |collection-url =https://pubs.usgs.gov/ds/1004/ds1004_alldma.htm |repository = |institution =United States Geological Survey |location = |oclc= |accession= |ref=}}\n* {{cite archive |first=Alice P. |last=Broudy |item =Observed Damage at Groom Mine Following Shot of Plumbbob, July 9, 1964 |item-url = |type = |item-id = |date = |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = |file =5 |box=24 |collection =Alice P. Broudy Papers on Broudy v United States |collection-url =https://www.library.unlv.edu/speccol/finding-aids/MS-00097.pdf |repository =Special Collections and Archives |institution =University of Nevada, Las Vegas |location =Las Vegas, Nevada |oclc= |accession= |ref=}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.groommine.com/}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://westernmininghistory.com/mine_detail/10072154/ |title=Groom Mine |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2017 |website=Western Mining History }}\n{{Lincoln County, Nevada|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lincoln County, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Mines in Nevada]]\n[[Category:1875 establishments in Nevada]]\n[[Category:2015 disestablishments in Nevada]]\n", "name_user": "Central Midfielder", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGovernment ownership:fixing grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Groom_Mine"}
{"title_page": "Metropolitan Opera Live in HD", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Live from the Metropolitan Opera}}\n\n'''Great Performances at the Met''' (also known as '''The Met: Live in HD''' and '''''Metropolitan Opera Live in HD''''') is a series of live opera performances transmitted in [[high-definition video]] via satellite from the [[Metropolitan Opera]] in New York City to select venues, primarily [[movie theater]]s, in the United States and other parts of the world. The first transmission was of a condensed English-language version of Mozart's ''[[The Magic Flute]]'' on December 30, 2006. Most of the video recordings are later made available for streaming at Met Opera on Demand.\n\n==History==\nTo transmit the series via satellite [[simulcast]] in the US and Canada, the Met has partnered with [[Fathom Events]]. The series is broadcast to [[AMC Theatres]], [[Cinemark]], [[Cineplex Entertainment]], [[Regal Entertainment Group]] (Regal Cinemas, United Artists and Edwards), Goodrich, Kerasotes, Marcus and [[National Amusements]] movie theaters as well as a series of independent venues such as arts centers and college campuses. Its aims include building a larger audience for the Met and garnering excitement for arts at a local level.\n\nThe original idea for presenting operas in this way came from the new incoming general manager of the Met, [[Peter Gelb]] in late 2006. Exhibiting the Met's performances in digital movie theaters is in line with other audience-expanding efforts by the Met such as radio broadcasts on [[Sirius Radio]], [[iPod]] downloads, live streaming video on the Met website, and free opening night screenings in [[Times Square]] and at [[Lincoln Center]]. The Met is also sponsoring free HD broadcasts into selected New York City public schools.<ref>[http://www.playbillarts.com/news/article/7484.html \"Metropolitan Opera to Offer Hi-Def Simulcasts in NYC Public Schools\"] Playbill.com, December 12, 2007</ref>\n\nThe simulcasts allow more people to experience the excitement of the Met's high-quality performance offerings. This audience includes current opera fans unable to get to New York City to see the shows in person and potential opera fans looking for an easy, affordable method of checking out a new art form.\n\nTom Galley, chief operations and technology officer of [[National CineMedia]], describes the experience by saying:\n{{quote|This Metropolitan Opera series is a unique opportunity for people to experience world-class opera in their local community, plus the movie theatre environment and affordable ticket price make these events something that the entire family can enjoy. If you\u2019ve never had the pleasure of attending a live opera performance before, this is the perfect opportunity to see why this magical art form has captured audiences\u2019 imaginations for generations.<ref>[http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/news/press/detail.aspx?id=2719 \u201c'Metropolitan Opera: Live in HD' Now Playing at a Theater Near You,\" press release, November 15, 2006]</ref>}}\n\nIn the US, the series has also been broadcast in both [[high-definition television|high definition]] and regular TV as part of the [[Public Broadcasting Service]]'s ''[[Great Performances]]'' series under the title ''Great Performances at the Met''. In addition, selected performances can now be viewed online.<ref>[http://www.classicaltv.com/the-informer/operas-from-the-met \"Operas from The Met\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003214056/http://www.classicaltv.com/the-informer/operas-from-the-met |date=2009-10-03 }} ClassicalTV</ref>\n\n===International expansion===\nThe first season included seven theatres in Britain, two in Japan and one in Norway. After its successful launch, several other countries joined for the second season and 100 screens were added, selling an additional 20,000 tickets. {{Citation needed|date=February 2008}} These included cinemas in Belgium, France, Germany, Italy, and Spain.\n\n2008 saw the network expand even further to include more screens in the countries named above plus other countries such as Australia, Austria, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Argentina (Buenos Aires and Mar del Plata),<ref>[http://www.fundacionbeethoven.com.ar/comunicacion/ Fundacion Beethoven, The Met HD en Vivo Buenos Aires]</ref> and Poland, as well as the territory of Puerto Rico.<ref>[http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/news/press/detail.aspx?id=3810 \"The Metropolitan Opera Announces Expansion of Live, High-Definition Transmissions to Eleven in 2008/09\" press release, April 22, 2008]</ref>\n\nReaction in the British press has been positive:\n{{quote|...opera is, in fact, managing to find new audiences, all over the world. Down at the Ritzy, my local cinema in Brixton, London, I've been able, since December, to see live broadcasts from the Metropolitan Opera in New York...<ref>[[Tom Service]], [http://music.guardian.co.uk/classical/story/0,,2268049,00.html \"Give me divas \u2013 not DJs\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'' (London), March 22, 2008</ref>}}\n\nThe author [[Peter Conrad (academic)|Peter Conrad]] praised Gelb's showmanship:\n{{quote|The relays are the brainchild of the Met's new general manager, Peter Gelb, or one of his innumerable brainchildren, part of a campaign both to rejuvenate the Met's audience in New York and to welcome what he calls 'the global opera community' into the fold. When I met Gelb in New York last week, I told him I'd decided that seeing ''The Barber'' in [[Clapham]] (just south of central London) was actually better than being at the Met. 'Oh no, that's bad,' he groaned. 'We must be doing too good a job.<ref>[[Peter Conrad (academic)|Peter Conrad]], [http://music.guardian.co.uk/classical/story/0,,2062672,00.html \"Opera from New York in your home town? Easy. Just go to the pictures\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'' (London), April 22, 2007</ref>}}\n\n==Production==\n{{asof|2011}} six Metropolitan Opera employees work full-time on Live in HD. About 40 people work on the technical aspects of each broadcast, with one comparing the scale of the logistics to the preshow coverage of the [[Emmy Award|Emmy]] or [[Academy Award]]s. Host [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] volunteers her services. No same-day substitution of a major cast member for a Live in HD performance was necessary until January 2010, perhaps because of the appeal of performing for a worldwide audience and the opportunity to appear on the subsequent DVD of the broadcast.{{r|steichen2011}}\n\n==Audience==\nMovie and radio broadcast revenue increased for the Met from about $5 million in 2006, Live in HD's first year, to $22 million in 2008, with Live in HD contributing the bulk of the growth.<ref name=\"steichen2011\">{{cite journal | url=http://oq.oxfordjournals.org/content/27/4/443.full | title=HD Opera: A Love/Hate Story | author=Steichen, James | journal=The Opera Quarterly |date=Autumn 2011 | volume=27 | issue=4 | pages=443\u2013459 | doi=10.1093/oq/kbs030}}</ref> For the 2009/10 season, the Met spent about $12 million in production and received about half of the $47 million box-office gross. After paying royalties to its cast and crew, the Met earned a $8 million profit.<ref name=\"adair20101008\">{{cite news | url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2010/10/the-metropolitan-operas-movie-screenings-turns-5-despite-early-skepticism.html | title=The Metropolitan Opera's live movie screenings turn 5, despite early skepticism | work=Los Angeles Times | date=2010-10-08 | accessdate=March 20, 2013 | author=Adair, Marcia}}</ref> The Met's Live in HD revenue for the 2012/13 season was $34.5 million.<ref name=\"maloney20140128\">{{cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/metropolis/2014/01/28/met-operas-budget-falls-short/ | title=Met Opera\u2019s Budget Falls Short | work=Wall Street Journal | date=2014-01-28 | accessdate=28 January 2014 | author=Maloney, Jennifer}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2008 study commissioned by [[Opera America]], most Live in HD attendees were \"moderate and frequent opera goers\". About one in five, however, did not attend a live opera performance in the previous two years, with some being completely new to opera and attending because of curiosity about it. The majority claimed to equally enjoy broadcast and live opera, and more than half stated they would \"very likely\" attend an opera performance at the Met if visiting New York.<ref name=\"oa2008fall\">{{cite news | url=http://www.operaamerica.org/content/research/Met%20HD%20Article.pdf | title=The Metropolitan Opera Live in HD: Who Attends, and Why? | work=Opera America | date=Fall 2008 | accessdate=September 8, 2012 | pages=39\u201344 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502032044/http://www.operaamerica.org/content/research/Met%20HD%20Article.pdf | archivedate=May 2, 2012 }}</ref> A 2011 [[University of British Columbia]] thesis found that \"''Live in HD'' does not at present cannibalize the local live opera audience ... [but] There is no evidence that [it] generates more live opera attendance or brings new audiences into local opera houses\".<ref name=\"vaneeden2011\">{{cite web | url=https://circle.ubc.ca/bitstream/handle/2429/33478/ubc_2011_spring_vaneeden_stephan.pdf?sequence=5 | title=The Impact of The Met: Live in HD on Local Opera Attendance | publisher=Faculty of Graduate Studies, University of British Columbia | date=April 2011 | accessdate=March 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA report outlines the economics of the Met's 2013\u20142014 season:\n<blockquote>Last season, 10 operas were transmitted via satellite into at least 2,000 theaters in 66 countries, including more than 800 U.S. theaters. Box office hit $60 million worldwide (average ticket prices were $23 last season), with theater owners splitting sales 50\u201350 with the Met (insiders say the split is more advantageous to the Met in North America) and [[Fathom Events|Fathom]] taking a small percentage as well.<ref>Pamela McClintock, [http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/met-opera-standoff-threatens-60-723614 \"Met Opera Standoff Threatens $60 Million Theater Business\", ''The Hollywood Reporter''] (online), August 7, 2014 on hollywoodreporter.com</ref></blockquote>\n\nVladica and Davis have utilised Q methodology to analyse audience reactions and judgments of entertainment value with respect to this series, and related cultural events transmitted to cinemas.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ryerson.ca/~c5davis/publications/Vladica-Davis%20-%20value%20propositions%20of%20live%20cinema%20-%201%20May%202013.pdf | title=Value propositions of opera and theater live in cinema | publisher=Ryerson University / World Media Economics & Management Conference, Thessaloniki, Greece, 23\u201327 May 2012 | date=23\u201327 May 2012 | accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref>\n\n==Seasons==\n\n===2006\u20132007===\nBeginning on December 30, 2006, as part of the company's effort to build revenues and attract new audiences, the Met broadcast a series of six performances live via satellite into movie theaters.<ref>[http://www.metoperafamily.org/operanews/news/pressrelease.aspx?id=1315 \"Tickets for Metropolitan Opera's High-Definition Movie Theater Simulcasts to Go on Sale 11/18\"]. ''[[Opera News]]'' Online, November 16, 2006.</ref> The series was carried in over 100 movie theaters across North America plus others in Britain, Japan and one in Norway.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/01/arts/music/01scre.html Campbell Robertson, \"Mozart, Now Singing at a Theatre Near You\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 1, 2007</ref> It included:\n*[[Julie Taymor]]'s production of Mozart's ''[[The Magic Flute]]'',<ref>[http://www.fathomevents.com/subpage/index.asp?EventID=610&code=METpage List of Met productions presented on HD in 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929232427/http://www.fathomevents.com/subpage/index.asp?EventID=610&code=METpage |date=2010-09-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.playbillarts.com/news/article/7502.html \"Metropolitan Opera's First Simulcast of 2007\u201308 Breaks Attendance Records\"] Playbill.com, December 17, 2007.</ref> on December 30, 2006, in an abridged English version conducted by [[James Levine]] and starring [[Ying Huang (soprano)|Ying Huang]] as Pamina, [[Matthew Polenzani]] as Tamino, and [[Nathan Gunn]] as Papageno.\n*Bellini's ''[[I puritani]]'', on January 6, 2007, starring [[Anna Netrebko]], [[Eric Cutler]] and Franco Vassallo in the roles of Elvira, Arturo and Riccardo, in the 1976 Sandro Sequi production conducted by Patrick Summers.\n*The world premiere of [[Tan Dun]]'s ''[[The First Emperor]]'', on January 13, 2007, with [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] in the title role of Emperor Qin in a production by Zhan Yimou and conducted by Dun himself.\n*Tchaikovsky's ''[[Eugene Onegin (opera)|Eugene Onegin]]'', on February 24, 2007, starring [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] and [[Ram\u00f3n Vargas]] in the roles of Onegin, Tatiana and Lensky in [[Robert Carsen]]'s simple but beautiful production conducted by [[Valery Gergiev]].\n*Rossini's ''[[The Barber of Seville]]'', on March 24, 2007, in the new hit production by [[Bartlett Sher]], with [[Peter Mattei]], [[Joyce DiDonato]] and [[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]] as Figaro, Rosina and Almaviva, and conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]].\n*Puccini's ''[[Il trittico]]'', on April 28, 2007, in another new hit production, this time by [[Jack O'Brien (director)|Jack O'Brien]] and conducted by James Levine. [[Maria Guleghina]], [[Salvatore Licitra]] and [[Juan Pons]], in the roles of Giorgetta, Luigi and Michele, sang in ''[[Il tabarro]]'', [[Barbara Frittoli]] starred in the title role of ''[[Suor Angelica]]'', and ''[[Gianni Schicchi]]'' was played by [[Alessandro Corbelli]] with [[Olga Mykytenko]] and [[Massimo Giordano]] in the roles of Lauretta and Rinuccio. [[Stephanie Blythe]] starred in all three operas, singing the roles of Frugola, the Princess and Zita.\n\nIn addition, limited repeat showings of the operas were offered in most of the presenting cities. Within the US, digital sound for the performances was provided by [[Sirius Satellite Radio]].\n\nThese movie transmissions were successful at the box office as well as having received wide and generally favorable press coverage.<ref>Elizabeth Fitzsimmons, [http://weblog.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20061231/news_1m31opera.html \"Movie theaters offer opera live from the Met\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070920072423/http://weblog.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20061231/news_1m31opera.html |date=2007-09-20 }}, ''San Diego Union-Tribune'', December 31, 2006</ref> The Met reports that 91% of available seats were sold for the HD performances.<ref>Richard Ouzounian, \"Opera Screen Dream: Met simulcasts heat up plexes in cities, stix\", ''Variety'', March 5\u201311, 2007, pp. 41/42</ref> According to General Manager Peter Gelb, there were 60,000 people in cinemas around the world watching the March 24 transmission of ''The Barber of Seville''.<ref>Peter Gelb, speaking during the intermission on March 24, 2007, noted that over 250 movie theatres were presenting the performance that day.</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that 324,000 tickets were sold worldwide for the 2006\u201307 season, while each simulcast cost $850,000 to $1 million to produce.<ref name=\"Daniel Wakin\">Daniel Wakin, \"Met Opera To Expand Simulcasts In Theaters\", ''[[The New York Times]]'', May 17, 2007</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132008===\nDue to the success of the first season, the Metropolitan Opera decided to increase the number of HD broadcasts to movie theaters from six to eight during the 2007\u20132008 season. Further, the number of available theaters expanded to 330 across the US and additional countries throughout the world.\n\nThe first showing on December 15, 2007, [[Charles Gounod|Gounod]]'s ''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]'', was seen on 477 screens and sold an estimated 97,000 tickets. The series continued by featuring seven more of the Met's productions following ''Rom\u00e9o et Juliette'' and ending with ''[[La fille du r\u00e9giment]]'' on April 26, 2008.<ref>[http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/news/press/detail.aspx?id=300 The Met Opera\u2019s 2007\u201308 Season to Feature Seven New Productions \u2013 the Most in More than 40 Years]</ref>\n\nThe Met planned to broadcast to double the number of theaters in the US compared with the previous season, as well as to additional countries. The number of participating venues in the US, which includes movie theatre chains as well as independent theatres and some college campus venues, was 343.<ref name=\"Daniel Wakin\" /><ref>[http://www.fathomevents.com/files/PRPDF/MET_07-08_Participating_LIVE_Theatre_List.htm \"Participating Theatres \u2013 Met Opera Live in HD Series \u2013 Live Performances\", announced October 2, 2007]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> While \"the scope of the series expands to include more than 700 locations across North America, Europe, Asia, and Australia.... The Met has said that it hopes to reach as many as one million audience members with this season's HD transmissions\"<ref>Adam Wasserman, \"Changing Definitions\", ''[[Opera News]]'', December 2007, p. 60</ref>\n\nThe schedule of live broadcasts included:\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Roberto Alagna]], [[Nathan Gunn]], conducted by [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]])\n*''[[Hansel and Gretel (opera)|Hansel and Gretel]]'' ([[Christine Sch\u00e4fer]], [[Alice Coote]], [[Philip Langridge]], conducted by [[Vladimir Jurowski]])\n*''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'' ([[\u017deljko Lu\u010di\u0107]], [[Maria Guleghina]], [[John Relyea]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Manon Lescaut (Puccini)|Manon Lescaut]]'' ([[Karita Mattila]], [[Marcello Giordani]], [[Dwayne Croft]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Peter Grimes]]'' ([[Anthony Dean Griffey]], [[Patricia Racette]], [[Felicity Palmer]], conducted by [[Donald Runnicles]])\n*''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' ([[Deborah Voigt]], [[Robert Dean Smith]], [[Matti Salminen]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' ([[Ram\u00f3n Vargas]], [[Angela Gheorghiu]], [[Ludovic Tezier]], conducted by [[Nicola Luisotti]])\n*''[[La fille du r\u00e9giment]]'' ([[Natalie Dessay]], [[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]], [[Alessandro Corbelli]], conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it}})\n{{Div col end}}\nBy the end of the season, 920,000 people\u2014exceeding the total number of people who attended live performances at the Met over the entire season\u2014attended the 8 screenings bringing in a gross of $13.3 million from North America and $5 million from overseas.<ref>Pamela McClintock, \"Live perfs have Met beaming\", ''Variety'', June 11, 2008, reporting on a survey conducted by [[Opera America]]</ref>\n\n===2008\u20132009===\nThe HD season for 2008\u20132009 included 11 productions, including the Opening Night Gala on September 22, 2008, (broadcast in North America only).\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n* Opening Night Gala (Excerpts from ''[[La traviata]]'', ''[[Manon]]'' and ''[[Capriccio (opera)|Capriccio]]'', starring [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]])\n*''[[Salome (opera)|Salome]]'' ([[Karita Mattila]], Kim Begley, Juha Uusitalo, conducted by [[Patrick Summers]])\n*''[[Doctor Atomic]]'' ([[Gerald Finley]], [[Eric Owens (bass-baritone)|Eric Owens]], [[Sasha Cooke]], conducted by [[Alan Gilbert (conductor)|Alan Gilbert]])\n*''[[La damnation de Faust]]'' ([[Marcello Giordani]], [[Susan Graham]], [[John Relyea]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Tha\u00efs (opera)|Tha\u00efs]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Thomas Hampson]], [[Michael Schade]], conducted by [[Jes\u00fas L\u00f3pez Cobos]])\n*''[[La rondine]]'' ([[Angela Gheorghiu]], [[Roberto Alagna]], [[Samuel Ramey]], conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it}})\n*''[[Orfeo ed Euridice]]'' ([[Stephanie Blythe]], [[Danielle de Niese]], Heidi Grant Murphy, conducted by [[James Levine]]\n*''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], [[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]], conducted by Marco Armiliato)\n*''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' ([[Patricia Racette]], [[Marcello Giordani]], [[Dwayne Croft]], conducted by [[Patrick Summers]])\n*''[[La sonnambula]]'' ([[Natalie Dessay]], [[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]], Michele Pertusi, conducted by [[Evelino Pid\u00f2]])\n*''[[La Cenerentola]]'' ([[El\u012bna Garan\u010da]], [[Lawrence Brownlee]], [[Alessandro Corbelli]], conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]])\n{{Div col end}}\nAs of February 2009, over 1.1 million tickets to HD broadcasts had been sold.\n\n===2009\u20132010===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Tosca]]'' ([[Karita Mattila]], [[Marcelo \u00c1lvarez]], [[George Gagnidze]], conducted by [[Joseph Colaneri]])\n*''[[Aida]]'' ([[Violeta Urmana]], [[Dolora Zajick]], [[Johan Botha (tenor)|Johan Botha]], conducted by [[Daniele Gatti]])\n*''[[Turandot]]'' ([[Maria Guleghina]], [[Marcello Giordani]], [[Marina Poplavskaya]], [[Samuel Ramey]], conducted by [[Andris Nelsons]])\n*''[[Les Contes d'Hoffmann]]'' ([[Joseph Calleja]], [[Anna Netrebko]], [[Kate Lindsey]], Alan Held, conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Susan Graham]], [[Kristinn Sigmundsson]], conducted by [[Edo de Waart]])\n*''[[Carmen]]'' ([[El\u012bna Garan\u010da]], [[Roberto Alagna]], [[Barbara Frittoli]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n*''[[Simon Boccanegra]]'' ([[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[James Morris (bass-baritone)|James Morris]], [[Adrianne Pieczonka]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Hamlet (opera)|Hamlet]]'' ([[Simon Keenlyside]], [[James Morris (bass-baritone)|James Morris]], [[Marlis Petersen]], conducted by [[Louis Langr\u00e9e]])\n*''[[Armida (Rossini)|Armida]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Lawrence Brownlee]], [[John Osborn (tenor)|John Osborn]], conducted by [[Riccardo Frizza]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2010\u20132011===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Das Rheingold]]'' ([[Bryn Terfel]], [[Eric Owens (bass-baritone)|Eric Owens]], [[Stephanie Blythe]], [[Richard Croft (tenor)|Richard Croft]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Boris Godunov (opera)|Boris Godunov]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9 Pape]], Aleksandrs Antonenko, Ekaterina Semenchuk, conducted by [[Valery Gergiev]])\n*''[[Don Pasquale]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], John Del Carlo, [[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]], [[Matthew Polenzani]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Don Carlo]]'' ([[Roberto Alagna]], [[Ferruccio Furlanetto]], [[Marina Poplavskaya]], [[Simon Keenlyside]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n*''[[La fanciulla del West]]'' ([[Deborah Voigt]], [[Marcello Giordani]], Lucio Gallo, conducted by [[Nicola Luisotti]])\n*''[[Nixon in China]]'' ([[James Maddalena]], Janis Kelly, [[Kathleen Kim]], conducted by [[John Adams (composer)|John Adams]])\n*''[[Iphig\u00e9nie en Tauride]]'' ([[Susan Graham]], [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Paul Groves (tenor)|Paul Groves]], conducted by [[Patrick Summers]])\n*''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'' ([[Natalie Dessay]], [[Joseph Calleja]], Ludovic T\u00e9zier, conducted by [[Patrick Summers]])\n*''[[Le comte Ory]]'' ([[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]], [[Joyce DiDonato]], [[Diana Damrau]], conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]])\n*''[[Capriccio (opera)|Capriccio]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Joseph Kaiser]], [[Russell Braun]], conducted by [[Andrew Davis (conductor)|Andrew Davis]])\n*''[[Il trovatore]]'' ([[Sondra Radvanovsky]], [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], [[Marcelo \u00c1lvarez]], [[Dolora Zajick]] conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it||lt=|WD=}})\n*''[[Die Walk\u00fcre]]'' ([[Deborah Voigt]], [[Jonas Kaufmann]], [[Eva-Maria Westbroek]], [[Bryn Terfel]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2011\u20132012===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Anna Bolena]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], Ekaterina Gubanova, [[Ildar Abdrazakov]], conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it}})\n*''[[Don Giovanni]]'' ([[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]], [[Marina Rebeka]], [[Luca Pisaroni]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Siegfried (opera)|Siegfried]]'' ([[Jay Hunter Morris]], [[Bryn Terfel]], [[Deborah Voigt]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Satyagraha (opera)|Satyagraha]]'' ([[Richard Croft (tenor)|Richard Croft]], Maria Zifchak, Rachelle Durkin, conducted by Dante Anzolini)\n*''[[Rodelinda (opera)|Rodelinda]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Andreas Scholl]], [[Stephanie Blythe]], conducted by [[Harry Bicket]])\n*''[[Faust (opera)|Faust]]'' ([[Jonas Kaufmann]], [[Ren\u00e9 Pape]], [[Marina Poplavskaya]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n*''[[The Enchanted Island (opera)|The Enchanted Island]]'' ([[David Daniels (countertenor)|David Daniels]], [[Joyce DiDonato]], [[Danielle de Niese]], [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], conducted by [[William Christie (musician)|William Christie]])\n*''[[G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung]]'' ([[Deborah Voigt]], [[Jay Hunter Morris]], [[Waltraud Meier]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Ernani]]'' ([[Angela Meade]], [[Marcello Giordani]], [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], [[Ferruccio Furlanetto]], conducted by Marco Armiliato)\n*''[[Manon]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], [[Paulo Szot]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[La traviata]]'' ([[Natalie Dessay]], [[Matthew Polenzani]], [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2012\u20132013===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[L'elisir d'amore]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Matthew Polenzani]], [[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]], [[Ambrogio Maestri]], conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]])\n*''[[Otello]]'' ([[Johan Botha (tenor)|Johan Botha]], [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Falk Struckmann]], conducted by [[Semyon Bychkov (conductor)|Semyon Bychkov]])\n*''[[The Tempest (opera)|The Tempest]]'' ([[Simon Keenlyside]], [[Isabel Leonard]], [[Audrey Luna]], conducted by [[Thomas Ad\u00e8s]])\n*''[[La clemenza di Tito]]'' ([[El\u012bna Garan\u010da]], [[Barbara Frittoli]], [[Giuseppe Filianoti]], conducted by [[Harry Bicket]])\n*''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'' ([[Marcelo \u00c1lvarez]], [[Sondra Radvanovsky]], [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Aida]]'' ([[Liudmyla Monastyrska]], [[Roberto Alagna]], [[Olga Borodina]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Les Troyens]]'' ([[Bryan Hymel]], [[Susan Graham]], [[Deborah Voigt]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Maria Stuarda]]'' ([[Joyce DiDonato]], Elza van den Heever, [[Matthew Polenzani]], conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]]\n*''[[Rigoletto]]'' ([[\u017deljko Lu\u010di\u0107]], [[Diana Damrau]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], conducted by [[Michele Mariotti]])\n*''[[Parsifal]]'' ([[Jonas Kaufmann]], [[Ren\u00e9 Pape]], [[Peter Mattei]], [[Katarina Dalayman]], conducted by [[Daniele Gatti]])\n*''[[Francesca da Rimini (Zandonai)|Francesca da Rimini]]'' ([[Eva-Maria Westbroek]], [[Marcello Giordani]], [[Mark Delavan]], conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it}})\n*''[[Giulio Cesare]]'' ([[Natalie Dessay]], [[David Daniels (countertenor)|David Daniels]], [[Alice Coote]], conducted by [[Harry Bicket]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2013\u20132014===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Eugene Onegin (opera)|Eugene Onegin]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], conducted by [[Valery Gergiev]])\n*''[[The Nose (opera)|The Nose]]'' ([[Paulo Szot]], Andrey Popov, Alexander Lewis, conducted by Pavel Smelkov)\n*''[[Tosca]]'' ([[Patricia Racette]], [[Roberto Alagna]], George Gagnidze, conducted by Riccardo Frizza)\n*''[[Falstaff (opera)|Falstaff]]'' ([[Ambrogio Maestri]], [[Angela Meade]], [[Stephanie Blythe]] conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Rusalka (opera)|Rusalka]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Dolora Zajick]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n*''[[Prince Igor]]'' ([[Ildar Abdrazakov]], [[Oksana Dyka]], [[Anita Rachvelishvili]], conducted by [[Gianandrea Noseda]])\n*''[[Werther]]'' ([[Jonas Kaufmann]], [[Sophie Koch]], [[David Bizic]], [[Lisette Oropesa]], conducted by [[Alain Altinoglu]])\n*''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' ([[Krist\u012bne Opolais]], [[Vittorio Grigolo]], [[Susanna Phillips]], conducted by Stefano Ranzani)\n*''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'' ([[Susanna Phillips]], [[Danielle de Niese]], [[Matthew Polenzani]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[La Cenerentola]]'' ([[Joyce DiDonato]], [[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]], [[Luca Pisaroni]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2014\u20132015===\nThe 2014\u20132015 season presented 12 operas in 10 HD transmissions, including (for the first time in the series) two \"double-bills\" where two short operas were staged together on the same program.<ref>[http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/liveinhd/live-in-hd-2014-15-season 2014\u201315 Live in HD Schedule] on metoperafamily.org. Retrieved 8 August 2014.</ref> [[John Adams (composer)|John Adams]]'s ''[[Death of Klinghoffer]]'' was originally planned for an HD transmission but was replaced by ''Il barbiere di Siviglia'' due to controversy after the work was accused of being anti-Semitic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metopera.org/en/news-and-features1/press-releases/releases/-The-Metropolitan-Opera-to-cancel-its-Live-in-HD-transmission-of-John-Adamss-The-Death-of-Klinghoffer-scheduled-for-this-fall |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-03-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225235243/http://www.metopera.org/en/news-and-features1/press-releases/releases/-The-Metropolitan-Opera-to-cancel-its-Live-in-HD-transmission-of-John-Adamss-The-Death-of-Klinghoffer-scheduled-for-this-fall/ |archivedate=2015-02-25 }}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'' ([[\u017deljko Lu\u010di\u0107]], [[Anna Netrebko]], [[Joseph Calleja]], [[Ren\u00e9 Pape]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[The Marriage of Figaro|Le nozze di Figaro]]'' ([[Ildar Abdrazakov]], [[Marlis Petersen]], [[Peter Mattei]], conducted by [[James Levine]]) \n*''[[Carmen]]'' (Anita Rachvelishvili, Aleksandrs Antonenko, [[Anita Hartig]], [[Ildar Abdrazakov]],  conducted by [[Pablo Heras-Casado]])\n*''[[The Barber of Seville|Il barbiere di Siviglia]]'' ([[Isabel Leonard]], [[Lawrence Brownlee]], [[Christopher Maltman]],  conducted by Michele Mariotti)\n*''[[Die Meistersinger von N\u00fcrnberg]]'' ([[Michael Volle]], [[Johan Botha (tenor)|Johan Botha]], [[Annette Dasch]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[The Merry Widow]]''  ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Nathan Gunn]], [[Kelli O'Hara]], [[Thomas Allen (baritone)|Thomas Allen]] conducted by [[Andrew Davis (conductor)|Andrew Davis]])\n*''[[The Tales of Hoffmann|Les contes d'Hoffmann]]'' ([[Vittorio Grigolo]], [[Hibla Gerzmava]], [[Thomas Hampson]], [[Kate Lindsey]]  conducted by [[Yves Abel]])\n*''[[Iolanta]]'' and ''[[Duke Bluebeard's Castle]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], [[Nadja Michael]], [[Mikhail Petrenko]],  conducted by [[Valery Gergiev]])\n*''[[La donna del lago]]'' ([[Joyce DiDonato]], [[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]], Daniela Barcellona,  conducted by Michele Mariotti)\n*''[[Cavalleria rusticana]]'' and ''[[Pagliacci]]'' ([[Marcelo \u00c1lvarez]], [[Eva-Maria Westbroek]], [[Patricia Racette]],  conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2015\u20132016===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Il trovatore]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Yonghoon Lee]], [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], [[Dolora Zajick]],  conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it}})\n*''[[Otello]]'' ([[Aleksandr Antonenko]], [[Sonya Yoncheva]], [[\u017deljko Lu\u010di\u0107]],  conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n*''[[Tannh\u00e4user (opera)|Tannh\u00e4user]]'' ([[Johan Botha (tenor)|Johan Botha]], [[Eva-Maria Westbroek]], [[Peter Mattei]], [[Michelle DeYoung]],  conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Lulu (opera)|Lulu]]'' ([[Marlis Petersen]], [[Susan Graham]], [[Johan Reuter]],  conducted by [[Lothar Koenigs]])\n*''[[Les p\u00eacheurs de perles]]'' ([[Matthew Polenzani]], [[Diana Damrau]], [[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]],  conducted by [[Gianandrea Noseda]])\n*''[[Turandot]]'' ([[Nina Stemme]], Marco Berti, [[Anita Hartig]],  conducted by [[Paolo Carignani]])\n*''[[Manon Lescaut]]''  ([[Krist\u012bne Opolais]], [[Roberto Alagna]], Massimo Cavalletti,  conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' ([[Krist\u012bne Opolais]], [[Roberto Alagna]], [[Dwayne Croft]],  conducted by [[Karel Mark Chichon]])\n*''[[Roberto Devereux]]'' ([[Sondra Radvanovsky]], [[Matthew Polenzani]], [[El\u012bna Garan\u010da]], [[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]],  conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]])\n*''[[Elektra (opera)|Elektra]]'' <ref>[http://www.metopera.org/metopera/liveinhd/live-in-hd-2015-16-season \"2015\u201316 Live in HD Schedule\"], on metopera.org</ref> ([[Nina Stemme]], [[Waltraud Meier]], [[Adrianne Pieczonka]], [[Eric Owens (bass-baritone)|Eric Owens]],  conducted by [[Esa-Pekka Salonen]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2016\u20132017===\nThe 2016-2017 season included the presentation of the first opera by a female composer in the series, ''[[L'Amour de loin]]'' of Kaija Saariaho, which also marked the first opera in the series to feature a female conductor, [[Susanna M\u00e4lkki]]. The presentation of ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'' marked the final performances in their respective roles by [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] (the Marschallin) and [[El\u012bna Garan\u010da]] (Octavian).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/13/arts/music/renee-fleming-final-bow-der-rosenkavalier.html | title=Watch Ren\u00e9e Fleming Take Her Final Bow in ''Der Rosenkavalier''|work=[[The New York Times]]| author=Michael Cooper | date=2017-05-13 | accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.wqxr.org/story/stopping-clocks-strauss-der-rosenkavalier | title=Stopping the Clocks With Strauss' ''Der Rosenkavalier''|publisher=[[WQXR-FM|WQXR]]|author=Merrin Lazyan|date=2017-05-11|accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' ([[Nina Stemme]], [[Stuart Skelton]], Ekaterina Gubanova, [[Ren\u00e9 Pape]], conducted by Sir Simon Rattle)\n*''[[Don Giovanni]]'' ([[Simon Keenlyside]], [[Hibla Gerzmava]], [[Malin Bystr\u00f6m]], [[Paul Appleby (tenor)|Paul Appleby]], [[Adam Plachetka]] conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[L'Amour de loin]]'' ([[Eric Owens (bass-baritone)|Eric Owens]], [[Susanna Phillips]], Tamara Mumford, conducted by [[Susanna M\u00e4lkki]])\n*''[[Nabucco]]'' ([[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Liudmyla Monastyrska]], Dimitry Belosselskiy, [[Jamie Barton]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]'' ([[Diana Damrau]], [[Vittorio Grigolo]], [[Mikhail Petrenko (bass)|Mikhail Petrenko]], Elliot Madore, Virginie Verrez, conducted by Gianndrea Noseda)\n*''[[Rusalka (opera)|Rusalka]]'' ([[Krist\u012bne Opolais]], [[Brandon Jovanovich]], [[Jamie Barton]], [[Eric Owens (bass-baritone)|Eric Owens]], [[Katarina Dalayman]], conducted by [[Mark Elder]])\n*''[[La traviata]]'' ([[Sonya Yoncheva]], [[Michael Fabiano]], [[Thomas Hampson]], conducted by [[Nicola Luisotti]])\n*''[[Idomeneo]]'' ([[Matthew Polenzani]], [[Alice Coote]], Elza van den Heever, [[Nadine Sierra]], conducted by James Levine)\n*''[[Eugene Onegin (opera)|Eugene Onegin]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Peter Mattei]],<ref>Replacing [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], who has withdrawn from opera performances, due to balance problems resulting from treatments for a brain tumor ([https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/08/arts/music/dmitri-hvorostovsky-citing-brain-tumor-withdraws-from-opera.html?_r=1 \"Dmitri Hvorostovsky, Citing Brain Tumor, Withdraws From Opera\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 8, 2016.</ref> Alexy Dolgov, \u0160tefan Koc\u00e1n, conducted by [[Robin Ticciati]])\n*''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[El\u012bna Garan\u010da]], Erin Morley, [[G\u00fcnther Groissb\u00f6ck]], conducted by [[Sebastian Weigle]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2017\u20132018===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Norma (opera)|Norma]]'' ([[Sondra Radvanovsky]], [[Joyce DiDonato]], [[Joseph Calleja]], [[Matthew Rose (bass)|Matthew Rose]], conducted by [[Carlo Rizzi (conductor)|Carlo Rizzi]])\n*''[[Die Zauberfl\u00f6te]]'' ({{ill|Golda Schultz|de}}, Kathryn Lewek, [[Charles Castronovo]], [[Markus Werba]], [[Ren\u00e9 Pape]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[The Exterminating Angel (opera)|The Exterminating Angel]]'' ([[Sally Matthews]], [[Alice Coote]], [[Christine Rice]], [[Iestyn Davies]], [[Rod Gilfry]], [[John Tomlinson (bass)|John Tomlinson]], Amanda Echalaz, conducted by [[Thomas Ad\u00e8s]])\n*''[[Tosca]]'' ([[Sonya Yoncheva]],<ref>Yoncheva replaces the originally scheduled soprano [[Krist\u012bne Opolais]], who withdrew for personal reasons. Yoncheva, who is also appearing in ''La boh\u00e8me'' and ''Luisa Miller'', will be \"the first artist to take on three principal roles in HD transmissions over the course of a single season.\" ([https://www.operanews.com/Opera_News_Magazine/2017/6/News/Sonya_Yoncheva_Met_Tosca.html \"Sonya Yoncheva to Replace Krist\u012bne Opolais in Premiere Performances of Metropolitan Opera's New ''Tosca''\"], ''[[Opera News]]'', 16 June 2017])</ref> [[Vittorio Grigolo]], [[\u017deljko Lu\u010di\u0107]], conducted by [[Emmanuel Villaume]])\n*''[[L'elisir d'amore]]'' ([[Pretty Yende]], [[Matthew Polenzani]], [[Ildebrando D'Arcangelo]], Davide Luciano, conducted by [[Domingo Hindoyan]])\n*''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' ([[Sonya Yoncheva]], [[Susanna Phillips]], [[Michael Fabiano]], [[Lucas Meachem]], conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it}})\n*''[[Semiramide]]'' ([[Angela Meade]], Elizabeth DeShong, [[Javier Camarena]], [[Ildar Abdrazakov]], conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]])\n*''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'' ([[Kelli O'Hara]], [[Amanda Majeski]], [[Serena Malfi]], Ben Bliss, [[Adam Plachetka]], [[Christopher Maltman]], conducted by [[David Robertson (conductor)|David Robertson]])\n*''[[Luisa Miller]]'' ([[Sonya Yoncheva]], Olesya Petrova, [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], conducted by [[Bertrand de Billy]])\n*''[[Cendrillon]]'' ([[Joyce DiDonato]], [[Alice Coote]], [[Stephanie Blythe]], [[Kathleen Kim]], conducted by [[Bertrand de Billy]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2018\u20132019===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n\n*''[[Aida]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Anita Rachvelishvili]], [[Aleksandr Antonenko]], [[Quinn Kelsey]], conducted by [[Nicola Luisotti]])\n*''[[Samson et Dalila]]'' ([[El\u012bna Garan\u010da]], [[Roberto Alagna]], [[Laurent Naouri]], [[Dmitry Belosselskiy]], conducted by [[Mark Elder]])\n*''[[La fanciulla del West]]'' ([[Eva-Maria Westbroek]], [[Jonas Kaufmann]], [[\u017deljko Lu\u010di\u0107]], Carlo Bosi, conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it}})\n*''[[Marnie (opera)|Marnie]]'' ([[Isabel Leonard]], [[Christopher Maltman]], [[Denyce Graves]], [[Iestyn Davies]], Janis Kelly, conducted by [[Robert Spano]])\n*''[[La traviata]]'' ([[Diana Damrau]], [[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]], Quinn Kelsey, conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n*''[[Adriana Lecouvreur]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], [[Anita Rachvelishvili]], [[Ambrogio Maestri]], conducted by [[Gianandrea Noseda]])\n*''[[Carmen]]'' ([[Cl\u00e9mentine Margaine]], [[Roberto Alagna]], [[Aleksandra Kurzak]], [[Alexander Vinogradov (bass)|Alexander Vinogradov]], conducted by [[Louis Langr\u00e9e]])\n*''[[La fille du r\u00e9giment]]'' ([[Pretty Yende]], [[Javier Camarena]], [[Stephanie Blythe]], Maurizio Muraro, [[Kathleen Turner]], conducted by [[Enrique Mazzola]])\n*''[[Die Walk\u00fcre]]'' ([[Christine Goerke]], [[Eva-Maria Westbroek]], [[Stuart Skelton]], [[Greer Grimsley]], [[Jamie Barton]], conducted by [[Philippe Jordan]])\n*''[[Dialogues des Carm\u00e9lites]]'' ([[Isabel Leonard]], [[Adrianne Pieczonka]], [[Karita Mattila]], [[Karen Cargill]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2019\u20132020===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n\n*''[[Turandot]]'' ([[Christine Goerke]], Yusif Eyvazov,<ref>Yusif Eyvazov ([http://archives.metoperafamily.org/archives/scripts/cgiip.exe/WService=BibSpeed/fullcit.w?xCID=357274 \"CID:357274\"] Met Opera Archive) replaced the originally scheduled Roberto Aronica.</ref> Eleonora Buratto, [[James Morris (bass-baritone)|James Morris]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n*''[[Manon]]'' ([[Lisette Oropesa]], [[Michael Fabiano]], Artur Ruci\u0144ski, Carlo Bosi, conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]])\n*''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' (Hui He, Elizabeth DeShong, Bruce Sledge,<ref name=Butterfly2019>The American tenor Bruce Sledge sang Pinkerton, replacing on short notice the previously scheduled Andrea Car\u00e8, and the Brazilian baritone [[Paulo Szot]] sang Sharpless, replacing the previously scheduled [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] ([http://archives.metoperafamily.org/archives/scripts/cgiip.exe/WService=BibSpeed/fullcit.w?xCID=357311&limit \"CID: 357311\"], Met Opera Archive).</ref> [[Paulo Szot]],<ref name=Butterfly2019/> conducted by Pier Giorgio Morandi)\n*''[[Akhnaten (opera)|Akhnaten]]'' ([[Anthony Roth Costanzo]], J'Nai Bridges, D\u00edsella L\u00e1rusd\u00f3ttir, Aaron Blake, [[Zachary James]], conducted by [[Karen Kamensek]])\n*''[[Wozzeck]]'' ([[Peter Mattei]], Elza van den Heever, [[Gerhard Siegel]], Christian Van Horn, conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]]) \n*''[[Porgy and Bess]]'' ([[Eric Owens (bass-baritone)|Eric Owens]], [[Angel Blue]], [[Denyce Graves]], [[Latonia Moore]], Frederick Ballentine, Alfred Walker, Golda Schultz, conducted by David Robertson)\n*''[[Agrippina (opera)|Agrippina]]'' ([[Joyce DiDonato]], Brenda Rae, [[Kate Lindsey]], [[Iestyn Davies]], [[Matthew Rose (bass)|Matthew Rose]], conducted by [[Harry Bicket]])\n\nThe following broadcasts were scheduled, but cancelled due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]]:\n\n*''[[Der Fliegende Holl\u00e4nder]]'' ([[Yevgeny Nikitin (bass-baritone)|Evgeny Nikitin]]<ref>replacing the originally scheduled [[Bryn Terfel]]</ref>, [[Anja Kampe]], Sergey Skorokhodov, [[Franz-Josef Selig]], conducted by [[Valery Gergiev]])\n*''[[Tosca]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], Brian Jagde, Michael Volle, conducted by [[Bertrand de Billy]])\n*''[[Maria Stuarda]]'' ([[Diana Damrau]], [[Jamie Barton]], [[Stephen Costello]], Michele Pertusi, conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]])\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2020\u20132021===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n\n*''[[Aida]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Piotr Beczala]], [[Anita Rachvelishvili]], [[Ludovic T\u00e9zier]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]]) \n*''[[Il Trovatore]]'' ([[Sonya Yoncheva]], Ekaterina Semenchuk, Roberto Aronica, [[Quinn Kelsey]], conducted by [[Michele Mariotti]])\n*''[[Fidelio]]'' (Lise Davidsen, [[Brandon Jovanovich]], Franz-Josef Selig, [[Tomasz Konieczny]], Golda Schultz, conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]]) \n*''[[Die Zauberfl\u00f6te]]'' (Christiane Karg, Stanislas de Barbeyrac, Thomas Oliemans, Kathryn Lewek, Stephan Milling, conducted by [[Gustavo Dudamel]])\n*''[[Romeo et Juliette]]'' ([[Nadine Sierra]], [[Stephen Costello]], Joshua Hopkins, Julie Boulianne, [[Ildar Abdrazakov]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n*''[[Don Giovanni]]'' ([[Peter Mattei]], [[Gerald Finley]], [[Ailyn P\u00e9rez]], [[Isabel Leonard]], Ben Bliss, conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]]) \n*''[[Dead Man Walking (opera)|Dead Man Walking]]'' ([[Joyce DiDonato]], Etienne Dupuis, [[Susan Graham]], Latonia Moore, conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]]) \n*''[[Die Frau ohne Schatten]]'' (Elza van den Heever, [[Nina Stemme]], [[Evelyn Herlitzius]], [[Klaus Florian Vogt]], Michael Volle, conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]]) \n*''[[Nabucco]]'' (George Gagnidze, [[Anna Netrebko]], Dmitry Belosselskiy, Varduhi Abrahamyan, Najmiddin Mavlyanov, conducted by Marco Armiliato)\n*''[[Il Pirata]]'' ([[Diana Damrau]], Javier Camarena, Nicolas Test\u00e9, conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]]) \n\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.metopera.org/season/in-cinemas/ ''Live in HD''], Metropolitan Opera\n*{{IMDb title|tt1019690}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Opera}}\n\n[[Category:Metropolitan Opera]]\n[[Category:Opera-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Live from the Metropolitan Opera}}\n\n'''Metropolitan Opera Live in HD''' (also known as '''The Met: Live in HD''') is a series of live opera performances transmitted in [[high-definition video]] via satellite from the [[Metropolitan Opera]] in New York City to select venues, primarily [[movie theater]]s, in the United States and other parts of the world. The first transmission was of a condensed English-language version of Mozart's ''[[The Magic Flute]]'' on December 30, 2006. Many of the video recordings are later rebroadcast via [[public television]] as part of the ''[[Great Performances]] at the Met'' series, and most are made available for streaming at Met Opera on Demand.\n\n==History==\nTo transmit the series via satellite [[simulcast]] in the US and Canada, the Met has partnered with [[Fathom Events]]. The series is broadcast to [[AMC Theatres]], [[Cinemark]], [[Cineplex Entertainment]], [[Regal Entertainment Group]] (Regal Cinemas, United Artists and Edwards), Goodrich, Kerasotes, Marcus and [[National Amusements]] movie theaters as well as a series of independent venues such as arts centers and college campuses. Its aims include building a larger audience for the Met and garnering excitement for arts at a local level.\n\nThe original idea for presenting operas in this way came from the new incoming general manager of the Met, [[Peter Gelb]] in late 2006. Exhibiting the Met's performances in digital movie theaters is in line with other audience-expanding efforts by the Met such as radio broadcasts on [[Sirius Radio]], [[iPod]] downloads, live streaming video on the Met website, and free opening night screenings in [[Times Square]] and at [[Lincoln Center]]. The Met is also sponsoring free HD broadcasts into selected New York City public schools.<ref>[http://www.playbillarts.com/news/article/7484.html \"Metropolitan Opera to Offer Hi-Def Simulcasts in NYC Public Schools\"] Playbill.com, December 12, 2007</ref>\n\nThe simulcasts allow more people to experience the excitement of the Met's high-quality performance offerings. This audience includes current opera fans unable to get to New York City to see the shows in person and potential opera fans looking for an easy, affordable method of checking out a new art form.\n\nTom Galley, chief operations and technology officer of [[National CineMedia]], describes the experience by saying:\n{{quote|This Metropolitan Opera series is a unique opportunity for people to experience world-class opera in their local community, plus the movie theatre environment and affordable ticket price make these events something that the entire family can enjoy. If you\u2019ve never had the pleasure of attending a live opera performance before, this is the perfect opportunity to see why this magical art form has captured audiences\u2019 imaginations for generations.<ref>[http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/news/press/detail.aspx?id=2719 \u201c'Metropolitan Opera: Live in HD' Now Playing at a Theater Near You,\" press release, November 15, 2006]</ref>}}\n\nIn the US, the series has also been broadcast in both [[high-definition television|high definition]] and regular TV as part of the [[Public Broadcasting Service]]'s ''[[Great Performances]]'' series under the title ''Great Performances at the Met''. In addition, selected performances can now be viewed online.<ref>[http://www.classicaltv.com/the-informer/operas-from-the-met \"Operas from The Met\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003214056/http://www.classicaltv.com/the-informer/operas-from-the-met |date=2009-10-03 }} ClassicalTV</ref>\n\n===International expansion===\nThe first season included seven theatres in Britain, two in Japan and one in Norway. After its successful launch, several other countries joined for the second season and 100 screens were added, selling an additional 20,000 tickets. {{Citation needed|date=February 2008}} These included cinemas in Belgium, France, Germany, Italy, and Spain.\n\n2008 saw the network expand even further to include more screens in the countries named above plus other countries such as Australia, Austria, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Argentina (Buenos Aires and Mar del Plata),<ref>[http://www.fundacionbeethoven.com.ar/comunicacion/ Fundacion Beethoven, The Met HD en Vivo Buenos Aires]</ref> and Poland, as well as the territory of Puerto Rico.<ref>[http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/news/press/detail.aspx?id=3810 \"The Metropolitan Opera Announces Expansion of Live, High-Definition Transmissions to Eleven in 2008/09\" press release, April 22, 2008]</ref>\n\nReaction in the British press has been positive:\n{{quote|...opera is, in fact, managing to find new audiences, all over the world. Down at the Ritzy, my local cinema in Brixton, London, I've been able, since December, to see live broadcasts from the Metropolitan Opera in New York...<ref>[[Tom Service]], [http://music.guardian.co.uk/classical/story/0,,2268049,00.html \"Give me divas \u2013 not DJs\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'' (London), March 22, 2008</ref>}}\n\nThe author [[Peter Conrad (academic)|Peter Conrad]] praised Gelb's showmanship:\n{{quote|The relays are the brainchild of the Met's new general manager, Peter Gelb, or one of his innumerable brainchildren, part of a campaign both to rejuvenate the Met's audience in New York and to welcome what he calls 'the global opera community' into the fold. When I met Gelb in New York last week, I told him I'd decided that seeing ''The Barber'' in [[Clapham]] (just south of central London) was actually better than being at the Met. 'Oh no, that's bad,' he groaned. 'We must be doing too good a job.<ref>[[Peter Conrad (academic)|Peter Conrad]], [http://music.guardian.co.uk/classical/story/0,,2062672,00.html \"Opera from New York in your home town? Easy. Just go to the pictures\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'' (London), April 22, 2007</ref>}}\n\n==Production==\n{{asof|2011}} six Metropolitan Opera employees work full-time on Live in HD. About 40 people work on the technical aspects of each broadcast, with one comparing the scale of the logistics to the preshow coverage of the [[Emmy Award|Emmy]] or [[Academy Award]]s. Host [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] volunteers her services. No same-day substitution of a major cast member for a Live in HD performance was necessary until January 2010, perhaps because of the appeal of performing for a worldwide audience and the opportunity to appear on the subsequent DVD of the broadcast.{{r|steichen2011}}\n\n==Audience==\nMovie and radio broadcast revenue increased for the Met from about $5 million in 2006, Live in HD's first year, to $22 million in 2008, with Live in HD contributing the bulk of the growth.<ref name=\"steichen2011\">{{cite journal | url=http://oq.oxfordjournals.org/content/27/4/443.full | title=HD Opera: A Love/Hate Story | author=Steichen, James | journal=The Opera Quarterly |date=Autumn 2011 | volume=27 | issue=4 | pages=443\u2013459 | doi=10.1093/oq/kbs030}}</ref> For the 2009/10 season, the Met spent about $12 million in production and received about half of the $47 million box-office gross. After paying royalties to its cast and crew, the Met earned a $8 million profit.<ref name=\"adair20101008\">{{cite news | url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2010/10/the-metropolitan-operas-movie-screenings-turns-5-despite-early-skepticism.html | title=The Metropolitan Opera's live movie screenings turn 5, despite early skepticism | work=Los Angeles Times | date=2010-10-08 | accessdate=March 20, 2013 | author=Adair, Marcia}}</ref> The Met's Live in HD revenue for the 2012/13 season was $34.5 million.<ref name=\"maloney20140128\">{{cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/metropolis/2014/01/28/met-operas-budget-falls-short/ | title=Met Opera\u2019s Budget Falls Short | work=Wall Street Journal | date=2014-01-28 | accessdate=28 January 2014 | author=Maloney, Jennifer}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2008 study commissioned by [[Opera America]], most Live in HD attendees were \"moderate and frequent opera goers\". About one in five, however, did not attend a live opera performance in the previous two years, with some being completely new to opera and attending because of curiosity about it. The majority claimed to equally enjoy broadcast and live opera, and more than half stated they would \"very likely\" attend an opera performance at the Met if visiting New York.<ref name=\"oa2008fall\">{{cite news | url=http://www.operaamerica.org/content/research/Met%20HD%20Article.pdf | title=The Metropolitan Opera Live in HD: Who Attends, and Why? | work=Opera America | date=Fall 2008 | accessdate=September 8, 2012 | pages=39\u201344 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502032044/http://www.operaamerica.org/content/research/Met%20HD%20Article.pdf | archivedate=May 2, 2012 }}</ref> A 2011 [[University of British Columbia]] thesis found that \"''Live in HD'' does not at present cannibalize the local live opera audience ... [but] There is no evidence that [it] generates more live opera attendance or brings new audiences into local opera houses\".<ref name=\"vaneeden2011\">{{cite web | url=https://circle.ubc.ca/bitstream/handle/2429/33478/ubc_2011_spring_vaneeden_stephan.pdf?sequence=5 | title=The Impact of The Met: Live in HD on Local Opera Attendance | publisher=Faculty of Graduate Studies, University of British Columbia | date=April 2011 | accessdate=March 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA report outlines the economics of the Met's 2013\u20142014 season:\n<blockquote>Last season, 10 operas were transmitted via satellite into at least 2,000 theaters in 66 countries, including more than 800 U.S. theaters. Box office hit $60 million worldwide (average ticket prices were $23 last season), with theater owners splitting sales 50\u201350 with the Met (insiders say the split is more advantageous to the Met in North America) and [[Fathom Events|Fathom]] taking a small percentage as well.<ref>Pamela McClintock, [http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/met-opera-standoff-threatens-60-723614 \"Met Opera Standoff Threatens $60 Million Theater Business\", ''The Hollywood Reporter''] (online), August 7, 2014 on hollywoodreporter.com</ref></blockquote>\n\nVladica and Davis have utilised Q methodology to analyse audience reactions and judgments of entertainment value with respect to this series, and related cultural events transmitted to cinemas.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ryerson.ca/~c5davis/publications/Vladica-Davis%20-%20value%20propositions%20of%20live%20cinema%20-%201%20May%202013.pdf | title=Value propositions of opera and theater live in cinema | publisher=Ryerson University / World Media Economics & Management Conference, Thessaloniki, Greece, 23\u201327 May 2012 | date=23\u201327 May 2012 | accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref>\n\n==Seasons==\n\n===2006\u20132007===\nBeginning on December 30, 2006, as part of the company's effort to build revenues and attract new audiences, the Met broadcast a series of six performances live via satellite into movie theaters.<ref>[http://www.metoperafamily.org/operanews/news/pressrelease.aspx?id=1315 \"Tickets for Metropolitan Opera's High-Definition Movie Theater Simulcasts to Go on Sale 11/18\"]. ''[[Opera News]]'' Online, November 16, 2006.</ref> The series was carried in over 100 movie theaters across North America plus others in Britain, Japan and one in Norway.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/01/arts/music/01scre.html Campbell Robertson, \"Mozart, Now Singing at a Theatre Near You\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 1, 2007</ref> It included:\n*[[Julie Taymor]]'s production of Mozart's ''[[The Magic Flute]]'',<ref>[http://www.fathomevents.com/subpage/index.asp?EventID=610&code=METpage List of Met productions presented on HD in 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929232427/http://www.fathomevents.com/subpage/index.asp?EventID=610&code=METpage |date=2010-09-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.playbillarts.com/news/article/7502.html \"Metropolitan Opera's First Simulcast of 2007\u201308 Breaks Attendance Records\"] Playbill.com, December 17, 2007.</ref> on December 30, 2006, in an abridged English version conducted by [[James Levine]] and starring [[Ying Huang (soprano)|Ying Huang]] as Pamina, [[Matthew Polenzani]] as Tamino, and [[Nathan Gunn]] as Papageno.\n*Bellini's ''[[I puritani]]'', on January 6, 2007, starring [[Anna Netrebko]], [[Eric Cutler]] and Franco Vassallo in the roles of Elvira, Arturo and Riccardo, in the 1976 Sandro Sequi production conducted by Patrick Summers.\n*The world premiere of [[Tan Dun]]'s ''[[The First Emperor]]'', on January 13, 2007, with [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] in the title role of Emperor Qin in a production by Zhan Yimou and conducted by Dun himself.\n*Tchaikovsky's ''[[Eugene Onegin (opera)|Eugene Onegin]]'', on February 24, 2007, starring [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] and [[Ram\u00f3n Vargas]] in the roles of Onegin, Tatiana and Lensky in [[Robert Carsen]]'s simple but beautiful production conducted by [[Valery Gergiev]].\n*Rossini's ''[[The Barber of Seville]]'', on March 24, 2007, in the new hit production by [[Bartlett Sher]], with [[Peter Mattei]], [[Joyce DiDonato]] and [[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]] as Figaro, Rosina and Almaviva, and conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]].\n*Puccini's ''[[Il trittico]]'', on April 28, 2007, in another new hit production, this time by [[Jack O'Brien (director)|Jack O'Brien]] and conducted by James Levine. [[Maria Guleghina]], [[Salvatore Licitra]] and [[Juan Pons]], in the roles of Giorgetta, Luigi and Michele, sang in ''[[Il tabarro]]'', [[Barbara Frittoli]] starred in the title role of ''[[Suor Angelica]]'', and ''[[Gianni Schicchi]]'' was played by [[Alessandro Corbelli]] with [[Olga Mykytenko]] and [[Massimo Giordano]] in the roles of Lauretta and Rinuccio. [[Stephanie Blythe]] starred in all three operas, singing the roles of Frugola, the Princess and Zita.\n\nIn addition, limited repeat showings of the operas were offered in most of the presenting cities. Within the US, digital sound for the performances was provided by [[Sirius Satellite Radio]].\n\nThese movie transmissions were successful at the box office as well as having received wide and generally favorable press coverage.<ref>Elizabeth Fitzsimmons, [http://weblog.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20061231/news_1m31opera.html \"Movie theaters offer opera live from the Met\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070920072423/http://weblog.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20061231/news_1m31opera.html |date=2007-09-20 }}, ''San Diego Union-Tribune'', December 31, 2006</ref> The Met reports that 91% of available seats were sold for the HD performances.<ref>Richard Ouzounian, \"Opera Screen Dream: Met simulcasts heat up plexes in cities, stix\", ''Variety'', March 5\u201311, 2007, pp. 41/42</ref> According to General Manager Peter Gelb, there were 60,000 people in cinemas around the world watching the March 24 transmission of ''The Barber of Seville''.<ref>Peter Gelb, speaking during the intermission on March 24, 2007, noted that over 250 movie theatres were presenting the performance that day.</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that 324,000 tickets were sold worldwide for the 2006\u201307 season, while each simulcast cost $850,000 to $1 million to produce.<ref name=\"Daniel Wakin\">Daniel Wakin, \"Met Opera To Expand Simulcasts In Theaters\", ''[[The New York Times]]'', May 17, 2007</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132008===\nDue to the success of the first season, the Metropolitan Opera decided to increase the number of HD broadcasts to movie theaters from six to eight during the 2007\u20132008 season. Further, the number of available theaters expanded to 330 across the US and additional countries throughout the world.\n\nThe first showing on December 15, 2007, [[Charles Gounod|Gounod]]'s ''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]'', was seen on 477 screens and sold an estimated 97,000 tickets. The series continued by featuring seven more of the Met's productions following ''Rom\u00e9o et Juliette'' and ending with ''[[La fille du r\u00e9giment]]'' on April 26, 2008.<ref>[http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/news/press/detail.aspx?id=300 The Met Opera\u2019s 2007\u201308 Season to Feature Seven New Productions \u2013 the Most in More than 40 Years]</ref>\n\nThe Met planned to broadcast to double the number of theaters in the US compared with the previous season, as well as to additional countries. The number of participating venues in the US, which includes movie theatre chains as well as independent theatres and some college campus venues, was 343.<ref name=\"Daniel Wakin\" /><ref>[http://www.fathomevents.com/files/PRPDF/MET_07-08_Participating_LIVE_Theatre_List.htm \"Participating Theatres \u2013 Met Opera Live in HD Series \u2013 Live Performances\", announced October 2, 2007]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> While \"the scope of the series expands to include more than 700 locations across North America, Europe, Asia, and Australia.... The Met has said that it hopes to reach as many as one million audience members with this season's HD transmissions\"<ref>Adam Wasserman, \"Changing Definitions\", ''[[Opera News]]'', December 2007, p. 60</ref>\n\nThe schedule of live broadcasts included:\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Roberto Alagna]], [[Nathan Gunn]], conducted by [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]]), broadcast on December 15, 2007\n*''[[Hansel and Gretel (opera)|Hansel and Gretel]]'' ([[Christine Sch\u00e4fer]], [[Alice Coote]], [[Philip Langridge]], conducted by [[Vladimir Jurowski]]), broadcast on January 1, 2008\n*''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'' ([[\u017deljko Lu\u010di\u0107]], [[Maria Guleghina]], [[John Relyea]], conducted by [[James Levine]]), broadcast on January 12, 2008\n*''[[Manon Lescaut (Puccini)|Manon Lescaut]]'' ([[Karita Mattila]], [[Marcello Giordani]], [[Dwayne Croft]], conducted by [[James Levine]]), broadcast on February 16, 2008\n*''[[Peter Grimes]]'' ([[Anthony Dean Griffey]], [[Patricia Racette]], [[Felicity Palmer]], conducted by [[Donald Runnicles]]), broadcast on March 15, 2008\n*''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' ([[Deborah Voigt]], [[Robert Dean Smith]], [[Matti Salminen]], conducted by [[James Levine]]), broadcast on March 22, 2008\n*''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' ([[Ram\u00f3n Vargas]], [[Angela Gheorghiu]], [[Ludovic Tezier]], conducted by [[Nicola Luisotti]]), broadcast on April 5, 2008\n*''[[La fille du r\u00e9giment]]'' ([[Natalie Dessay]], [[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]], [[Alessandro Corbelli]], conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it}}), broadcast on April 26, 2008\n{{Div col end}}\nBy the end of the season, 920,000 people\u2014exceeding the total number of people who attended live performances at the Met over the entire season\u2014attended the 8 screenings bringing in a gross of $13.3 million from North America and $5 million from overseas.<ref>Pamela McClintock, \"Live perfs have Met beaming\", ''Variety'', June 11, 2008, reporting on a survey conducted by [[Opera America]]</ref>\n\n===2008\u20132009===\nThe HD season for 2008\u20132009 included 11 productions, including the Opening Night Gala on September 22, 2008, (broadcast in North America only).\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n* Opening Night Gala (Excerpts from ''[[La traviata]]'', ''[[Manon]]'' and ''[[Capriccio (opera)|Capriccio]]'', starring [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]])\n*''[[Salome (opera)|Salome]]'' ([[Karita Mattila]], Kim Begley, Juha Uusitalo, conducted by [[Patrick Summers]])\n*''[[Doctor Atomic]]'' ([[Gerald Finley]], [[Eric Owens (bass-baritone)|Eric Owens]], [[Sasha Cooke]], conducted by [[Alan Gilbert (conductor)|Alan Gilbert]])\n*''[[La damnation de Faust]]'' ([[Marcello Giordani]], [[Susan Graham]], [[John Relyea]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Tha\u00efs (opera)|Tha\u00efs]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Thomas Hampson]], [[Michael Schade]], conducted by [[Jes\u00fas L\u00f3pez Cobos]])\n*''[[La rondine]]'' ([[Angela Gheorghiu]], [[Roberto Alagna]], [[Samuel Ramey]], conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it}})\n*''[[Orfeo ed Euridice]]'' ([[Stephanie Blythe]], [[Danielle de Niese]], Heidi Grant Murphy, conducted by [[James Levine]]\n*''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], [[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]], conducted by Marco Armiliato)\n*''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' ([[Patricia Racette]], [[Marcello Giordani]], [[Dwayne Croft]], conducted by [[Patrick Summers]])\n*''[[La sonnambula]]'' ([[Natalie Dessay]], [[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]], Michele Pertusi, conducted by [[Evelino Pid\u00f2]])\n*''[[La Cenerentola]]'' ([[El\u012bna Garan\u010da]], [[Lawrence Brownlee]], [[Alessandro Corbelli]], conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]])\n{{Div col end}}\nAs of February 2009, over 1.1 million tickets to HD broadcasts had been sold.\n\n===2009\u20132010===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Tosca]]'' ([[Karita Mattila]], [[Marcelo \u00c1lvarez]], [[George Gagnidze]], conducted by [[Joseph Colaneri]])\n*''[[Aida]]'' ([[Violeta Urmana]], [[Dolora Zajick]], [[Johan Botha (tenor)|Johan Botha]], conducted by [[Daniele Gatti]])\n*''[[Turandot]]'' ([[Maria Guleghina]], [[Marcello Giordani]], [[Marina Poplavskaya]], [[Samuel Ramey]], conducted by [[Andris Nelsons]])\n*''[[Les Contes d'Hoffmann]]'' ([[Joseph Calleja]], [[Anna Netrebko]], [[Kate Lindsey]], Alan Held, conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Susan Graham]], [[Kristinn Sigmundsson]], conducted by [[Edo de Waart]])\n*''[[Carmen]]'' ([[El\u012bna Garan\u010da]], [[Roberto Alagna]], [[Barbara Frittoli]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n*''[[Simon Boccanegra]]'' ([[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[James Morris (bass-baritone)|James Morris]], [[Adrianne Pieczonka]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Hamlet (opera)|Hamlet]]'' ([[Simon Keenlyside]], [[James Morris (bass-baritone)|James Morris]], [[Marlis Petersen]], conducted by [[Louis Langr\u00e9e]])\n*''[[Armida (Rossini)|Armida]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Lawrence Brownlee]], [[John Osborn (tenor)|John Osborn]], conducted by [[Riccardo Frizza]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2010\u20132011===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Das Rheingold]]'' ([[Bryn Terfel]], [[Eric Owens (bass-baritone)|Eric Owens]], [[Stephanie Blythe]], [[Richard Croft (tenor)|Richard Croft]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Boris Godunov (opera)|Boris Godunov]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9 Pape]], Aleksandrs Antonenko, Ekaterina Semenchuk, conducted by [[Valery Gergiev]])\n*''[[Don Pasquale]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], John Del Carlo, [[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]], [[Matthew Polenzani]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n*''[[Don Carlo]]'' ([[Roberto Alagna]], [[Ferruccio Furlanetto]], [[Marina Poplavskaya]], [[Simon Keenlyside]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n*''[[La fanciulla del West]]'' ([[Deborah Voigt]], [[Marcello Giordani]], Lucio Gallo, conducted by [[Nicola Luisotti]])\n*''[[Nixon in China]]'' ([[James Maddalena]], Janis Kelly, [[Kathleen Kim]], conducted by [[John Adams (composer)|John Adams]])\n*''[[Iphig\u00e9nie en Tauride]]'' ([[Susan Graham]], [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], [[Paul Groves (tenor)|Paul Groves]], conducted by [[Patrick Summers]])\n*''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'' ([[Natalie Dessay]], [[Joseph Calleja]], Ludovic T\u00e9zier, conducted by [[Patrick Summers]])\n*''[[Le comte Ory]]'' ([[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]], [[Joyce DiDonato]], [[Diana Damrau]], conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]])\n*''[[Capriccio (opera)|Capriccio]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Joseph Kaiser]], [[Russell Braun]], conducted by [[Andrew Davis (conductor)|Andrew Davis]])\n*''[[Il trovatore]]'' ([[Sondra Radvanovsky]], [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], [[Marcelo \u00c1lvarez]], [[Dolora Zajick]] conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it||lt=|WD=}})\n*''[[Die Walk\u00fcre]]'' ([[Deborah Voigt]], [[Jonas Kaufmann]], [[Eva-Maria Westbroek]], [[Bryn Terfel]], conducted by [[James Levine]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2011\u20132012===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Anna Bolena]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], Ekaterina Gubanova, [[Ildar Abdrazakov]], conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it}})\n*''[[Don Giovanni]]'' ([[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]], [[Marina Rebeka]], [[Luca Pisaroni]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Siegfried (opera)|Siegfried]]'' ([[Jay Hunter Morris]], [[Bryn Terfel]], [[Deborah Voigt]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Satyagraha (opera)|Satyagraha]]'' ([[Richard Croft (tenor)|Richard Croft]], Maria Zifchak, Rachelle Durkin, conducted by Dante Anzolini)\n*''[[Rodelinda (opera)|Rodelinda]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Andreas Scholl]], [[Stephanie Blythe]], conducted by [[Harry Bicket]])\n*''[[Faust (opera)|Faust]]'' ([[Jonas Kaufmann]], [[Ren\u00e9 Pape]], [[Marina Poplavskaya]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]])\n*''[[The Enchanted Island (opera)|The Enchanted Island]]'' ([[David Daniels (countertenor)|David Daniels]], [[Joyce DiDonato]], [[Danielle de Niese]], [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]], conducted by [[William Christie (musician)|William Christie]])\n*''[[G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung]]'' ([[Deborah Voigt]], [[Jay Hunter Morris]], [[Waltraud Meier]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Ernani]]'' ([[Angela Meade]], [[Marcello Giordani]], [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], [[Ferruccio Furlanetto]], conducted by Marco Armiliato)\n*''[[Manon]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], [[Paulo Szot]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[La traviata]]'' ([[Natalie Dessay]], [[Matthew Polenzani]], [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2012\u20132013===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[L'elisir d'amore]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Matthew Polenzani]], [[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]], [[Ambrogio Maestri]], conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]])\n*''[[Otello]]'' ([[Johan Botha (tenor)|Johan Botha]], [[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Falk Struckmann]], conducted by [[Semyon Bychkov (conductor)|Semyon Bychkov]])\n*''[[The Tempest (opera)|The Tempest]]'' ([[Simon Keenlyside]], [[Isabel Leonard]], [[Audrey Luna]], conducted by [[Thomas Ad\u00e8s]])\n*''[[La clemenza di Tito]]'' ([[El\u012bna Garan\u010da]], [[Barbara Frittoli]], [[Giuseppe Filianoti]], conducted by [[Harry Bicket]])\n*''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'' ([[Marcelo \u00c1lvarez]], [[Sondra Radvanovsky]], [[Dmitri Hvorostovsky]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Aida]]'' ([[Liudmyla Monastyrska]], [[Roberto Alagna]], [[Olga Borodina]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Les Troyens]]'' ([[Bryan Hymel]], [[Susan Graham]], [[Deborah Voigt]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]])\n*''[[Maria Stuarda]]'' ([[Joyce DiDonato]], Elza van den Heever, [[Matthew Polenzani]], conducted by [[Maurizio Benini]]\n*''[[Rigoletto]]'' ([[\u017deljko Lu\u010di\u0107]], [[Diana Damrau]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], conducted by [[Michele Mariotti]])\n*''[[Parsifal]]'' ([[Jonas Kaufmann]], [[Ren\u00e9 Pape]], [[Peter Mattei]], [[Katarina Dalayman]], conducted by [[Daniele Gatti]])\n*''[[Francesca da Rimini (Zandonai)|Francesca da Rimini]]'' ([[Eva-Maria Westbroek]], [[Marcello Giordani]], [[Mark Delavan]], conducted by {{ill|Marco Armiliato|it}})\n*''[[Giulio Cesare]]'' ([[Natalie Dessay]], [[David Daniels (countertenor)|David Daniels]], [[Alice Coote]], conducted by [[Harry Bicket]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2013\u20132014===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*''[[Eugene Onegin (opera)|Eugene Onegin]]'' ([[Anna Netrebko]], [[Mariusz Kwiecie\u0144]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], conducted by [[Valery Gergiev]]), broadcast on October 5, 2013\n*''[[The Nose (opera)|The Nose]]'' ([[Paulo Szot]], Andrey Popov, Alexander Lewis, conducted by Pavel Smelkov), broadcast on October 26, 2013\n*''[[Tosca]]'' ([[Patricia Racette]], [[Roberto Alagna]], George Gagnidze, conducted by Riccardo Frizza), broadcast on November 9, 2013\n*''[[Falstaff (opera)|Falstaff]]'' ([[Ambrogio Maestri]], [[Angela Meade]], [[Stephanie Blythe]] conducted by [[James Levine]]), broadcast on December 14, 2013\n*''[[Rusalka (opera)|Rusalka]]'' ([[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]], [[Dolora Zajick]], [[Piotr Becza\u0142a]], conducted by [[Yannick N\u00e9zet-S\u00e9guin]]), broadcast on February 8, 2014\n*''[[Prince Igor]]'' ([[Ildar Abdrazakov]], [[Oksana Dyka]], [[Anita Rachvelishvili]], conducted by [[Gianandrea Noseda]]), broadcast on March 1, 2014\n*''[[Werther]]'' ([[Jonas Kaufmann]], [[Sophie Koch]], [[David Bizic]], [[Lisette Oropesa]], conducted by [[Alain Altinoglu]]), broadcast on March 15, 2014\n*''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' ([[Krist\u012bne Opolais]], [[Vittorio Grigolo]], [[Susanna Phillips]], conducted by Stefano Ranzani), broadcast on April 5, 2014\n*''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'' ([[Susanna Phillips]], [[Danielle de Niese]], [[Matthew Polenzani]], conducted by [[James Levine]]), broadcast on April 26, 2014\n*''[[La Cenerentola]]'' ([[Joyce DiDonato]], [[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]], [[Luca Pisaroni]], conducted by [[Fabio Luisi]]), broadcast on May 10, 2014\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===2014\u20132015===\nThe 2014\u20132015 season presented 12 operas in 10 HD transmissions, including (for the first time in the series) two \"double-bills\" where two short operas were staged together on the same program.<ref>[http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/liveinhd/live-in-hd-2014-15-season 2014\u201315 Live in HD Schedule] on metoperafamily.org. Retrieved 8 August 2014.</ref> [[John Adams (composer)|John Adams]]'s ''[[Death of Klinghoffer]]'' was originally planned for an HD transmission but was replaced by ''Il barbiere di Siviglia'' due to controversy after the work was accused of being anti-Semitic